76561198206681324,Recommended,237930,28884396,"Posted: 31 December, 2016",all,VietnamFlashbacks,"That was one hell of a ride...I cannot believe that there aren't many people that know about this game, as it is simple amazing. It is a more than worthy successer to Supergiant's first game Bastion and its story is suprisingly hard hitting.Pros:- The game's soundtrack is phenomenal, and teh game's ability to allow the main character, Red, to hum along when out of combat helps the soundtrack shine.- The game is beautiful, but runs very well, even for my 3 year old laptop, which isn't at all built for gaming.- The combat system is simple, yet very fun, somewhat challenging (but not too challenging) and is very creative, making it a breath of fresh air.- Speaking of difficulty of the game, there are limitations, much like Bastion's panthenion system, which allow you to make the game harder if you feel that it is currently too easy for you.- The story respects you by allowing you to figure out and put pieces of the puzzle together, instead of constantly guiding you through the story, adding to the mystery of the game, which Bastion also had.- The world and level design is very good and certain interactions that you can have with the world help to flesh out the world that the game is set in.- There are extra challenged in the game and the game's story is replayable, if you would like to play the game with a different combination of powers.Cons:- The game is a little on the short side, with its main story coming to around 6 hours.- There aren't any section within the game that allow you to make choice which will affect the story, and - despite Bastion only having a few of these - I feel that they are missed.In all honesty the cons are really only nickpicks, and don't really affect the game too much, and I feel that Transistor is a step up from Bastion. I also feel like it could have been acknowledged as one of the best games of 2014, if it had been given its rightful attention as its stylistic gameplay and world, combined with the beautiful soundtrack and mysterious story, make it on of my personnal favourites."
,Recommended,237930,11718604,"Posted: 15 August, 2014",all,Zillastock,"This is a Sci-Fi Tactical RPG set in the luxurious neighborhood of a city. The RPG part is the usual leveling and acquiring of various attacks and abilities. The tactical side has you planning your moves and attacks during your 'turn' and during 'their turn' you run away. An interesting aspect in this game is that any ability can be used as an active ability, A passive ability or as an enhancement to an active ability. Gives a lot of different combinations to play with and the game encourages you to try them all out. It's also the main reason I'm considering playing again immediately. Something I rarely do.Story wise, You're Red, A super pop star, and something bad happens. Fortunately your over-sized all-purpose weapon talks to you and fills you in on what's going on. Well, The talking stick doesn't tell you everything. A lot of background is given through text and I found the setting it painted compelling. So much so that I wanted to explore and experience more of the city. I kind of interpreted that as a reflection of Reds' yearning for a part of her life that has been interrupted. I saw the fatalistic vibe as Reds' also.Visually the city is pleasing, clean and precise. While the more personal moments are done in a nice watercolor style. The music, Except for one stand out song, seems mostly ambient. Though there are some excellent subtle things done to the music, I wished it wasn't so subtle. Something to save for the next game perhaps.Overall, While the gameplay is excellent, The narrative seems more like an interesting experiment if not entirely successful. But I'll be there for SuperGiants next game sight unseen."
,Recommended,237930,10209125,"Posted: 23 May, 2014",all,Octopus on Fire,"I've been thinking for some time that cinema is leaving the spot open for new ways of storytelling. Videogames have tried to take that spot over the years, ofering now a great tool for writers and devs to reach their audience in ways movies can't.This level of inmersion is often used to put the player in other character's shoes, offering experiences with more or less background. Transistor favours the storytelling in spite of some of this inmersion, making the player an observer, not giving you absolute control, getting carried by the events, giving  you a broader view of what it has to deliver. And what a way to deliver it.Transistor executes flawlessly everything it attempts. It doesn't offer you the latest in graphics, the best music or the most action-packed gameplay, but it makes sure you enjoy every last bit of it. Don't take me wrong, the hand drawn graphics look gorgeous, the music is great and the gameplay is very, very enjoyable, but it's the way it delivers it to the player, what makes Transistor one of the very best games I've ever played. And I've been around since the 80's.The game takes all the good things from Bastion, all kinds of influences from our day, and builds a vivid, original world, so full of life and personality it makes everything else look so run-of-the-mill, so old and used. It tells the oldest Story ever told, a Tragedy. But it's the characters, the world they inhabit, the references to our world, the little details, the pauses, the many readings anyone can take from this story... It's more than just a game, just a story. It's an interactive piece of art.To sum it all up, don't miss this experience if you're looking for something else than quick, mindless fun in a game, because you'll be missing a classic. This game is gonna be high up in the history of videogames, at least as one of those ""hidden gems"", and will bring you memories (and probably a smile) when you stumble upon it in some years.Indie games are offering new, fresh, great ideas and masterpieces like Transistor only proves that it's a very good time to be a gamer, enjoy it while it lasts."
,Recommended,237930,31805467,Posted: 17 May,all,DirtyPhoenix,"Transistor is a game that's as much a game as it is a beautiful, moving piece of art. From the gorgeous visual style, the stellar music, an emotional and layered story and impeccable voice acting, not to mention the deep and mutating gameplay, it has near about everything that I crave from a videogame.The narrative is essentially about the relationship between a woman without a voice and man without a body. You are in a cyberpunk city called Cloudbank and something bad has just happened to you (the woman), causing you to lose your ability to speak and the man getting killed and his consciousness getting trapped inside the Transistor, the swordlike thing the woman carries. His voice constantly speaks to you, describes the happenings of the city and guides you. From here on out, Red - your character, must figure out who were behind this attack and make them pay. Before long you sense something is wrong with the city as well and it's changing too. Red and the Transistor's journey through this decaying city in persuit of vengeance is what makes up the story of this game. It's a very layered story with lots of subliminal themes, and it's told expertly and movingly, but none of these details are handed to you. You have to work for it and they are unlocked as you use different abilities in the game; while some people might find that off-putting, as far as I'm concerned that's a good gameplay design as it incentivizes experimentation and discovery of the numerous skill combinations you can put in place.The gameplay consists of turns where you pause the action and plan your steps and then unpause to watch the action roll out. You can also play it as a standard third-person game in real time but in more complex encounters this is neither feasible nor nearly as much fun as watching a perfectly planned attack execute. In the game you discover different 'functions', which are souls(?) of dead people you come across The interesting thing is that while most other RPGs have designated active and passive abilities, all the abilities in this game, these functions, can be used as active, secondary or passive abilities without restriction. So while for example Spark() lets loose a flurry of explosive shells when used as a primary function, it imbues a splitting and subdividing character to other function when combined with them as a secondary, and as a passive ability it spawns a copy of Red when under attack that'll divert enemy attention for a short time. Each function has different primary, secondary and passive characteristics like this and you're constantly judging whether a function will be more useful as a primary or perhaps augmenting another one. It is this gameplay element which immediately sets it apart from other RPGs, and leads to a potentially infinite loadouts as you can mix and match these functions to find completely different ways of dealing with enemies.A great game overall. Supergiant Games has quickly become one of my favourite developers and with the kind of work they did on Bastion and now Transistor, I'd be looking forward to their next game with baited breath. And yes, just like Bastion you'll cry at the end of this game as well. I know I did."
