,Not Recommended,237930,33314674,Posted: 6 July,all,Ignatius J. Reilly,"Game might be the best example of style over substance I've ever come across. While every aspect of visual and audio is excellent, the rest of the game is incrdibly limited in scope. Beyond the slick presentation what you're really getting is a mediocre action-RPG and not much more than that. It's a pseudo real-time/turn-based system that quickly turns dull.The combat revolves around making sure you're out of harms way while you wait for your turn meter to recharge, then when you have it back, making sure to do the most damage possible. The hurry up and wait didn't really appeal to me, and I found it more frustrating than anything. There's defeinitely some tactical consideration in terms of positioning, and skill usage, but not enough to make up for the combat's overall repetetive nature. And this is a problem, becuase the game basically boils down to room by room clearing, each with either a fight or a small story point. Starts to feel very predictable. They crucified FFXIII for this same corridor-like design, so I don't know how Transistor gets away with it...I've given this game a solid shot, restarting twice, and every time I beat the first boss, my desire to continue completely disolves. Oh well. I think for me, there are far better options when it comes to ARPGs, so I don't see any reason to bother with this one, despite it's stellar presentation."
,Not Recommended,237930,15277604,"Posted: 9 April, 2015",all,The Deuce,"It isn't fun.Don't mince words with any junk about how it made you cry. Don't waste your time singing the praises of a video game because of its art or its music or (god help you) its story.The movement is slow and clunky. Pretty much every attack option leaves you wide open to enemy fire (your enemies suffer no such restrictions, of course).The idea is that you're going to freeze time and belt out a series of attacks, but every time you do that it stops being an action RPG and becomes a plain old RPG. After freezing time, you can only attack out of Turn with the aid of upgrades (for individual moves), so your choices are to be effective in combat or to be involved in the combat, basically.There's some genuinely cool ideas. No one's going to deny that. Combining all your moves to give them cool side-effects is really nifty, the setting is fascinating (and ties directly into the gameplay) and there's real merit to blending strategy with action like this. But it all sort of falls flat on its face with how uninvolved it is.All Transistor needed was a couple more mobile attacks, the sort of thing you can use on the move or that doesn't slow you down massively, and a dodge roll.♥♥♥♥♥♥that gives you REAL options when you don't want to use Turn.It put in a flourish and a sing-song button instead.Make of that what you will."
76561198025148836,Not Recommended,237930,28729558,"Posted: 27 December, 2016",all,Aurelius,"After playing and loving Bastion, I had high hopes for Transistor.  Unfortunately, several glaring issues wth the gameplay just kept me from enjoying the game.  The story seems fine, if rather tough to piece together, so I will not cover that here.Obviously Transistor will be compared to Bastion, so I will do that as well.  The pros to Bastion's gameplay are-Wide range of weapons that can be used in combinations for different playstyles-Upgrade system that adds noticable benefits to both your character and his weapons-Strong core gameplay (dodging, blocking, attacking, etc.) that rewards skill and timing and prevents overreliance on healing items-No unnecessarily punishing elements (i.e. undodgeable/unblockable attacks), so deaths are almost always your faultTransistor on the other hand, seems to go directly against what worked in Bastion for core gameplay.-No natural block or dodge ability (aside from the teleport dash and invisibility functions), so there is no way to mitigate damage-Slow-moving character that tends to get caught on obstacles, exacerbated by the lack of a natural dodge-No healing aside from a late-game function, so some fights become battles of attrition-Several enemies whose attacks are unavoidable (dogs, creeps, jerks), even with the aforementioned functions, so fights involving these enemies are unnecessarily punishing-Environments that offer little room for maneuveringAll of this combined results in a gameplay experience that is a chore to endure, particularly later on when high-health enemies with unavoidable attacks appear in numbers.  The teleport dash function can help, but even when dashing away in a straight line enemies can still catch and damage you.  And the environments' cramped design means that you end up dashing in circles trailing enemies that keep picking away at your health in between dashes.  Fights become a race to see if you can kill these enemies before you lose a critical function.It is a shame that I could not enjoy the game due to these awful design choices.  The function system is an intriguing feature with great depth that could have enabled a wide range of playstyles.  Unfortunately the poorly-designed basic  gameplay means that this system cannot be used to its full potential."
