76561197998782039,Recommended,237930,10195430,"Posted: 22 May, 2014",all,Knight Of Virtue,"Another great game by Supergiant Games, though very different from their first, Bastion.The combat in Transistor involves a highly flexible ability system that lets you mix and match your abilities to create new abilities that play out in real time combat with some turn based elements. The combat constantly makes players choose when the optimal time to use their slotted abilities are, and when to use the planning mode (a mode that freezes enemies while you queue up and then execute some abilities before the enemies get to move again) as using abilities or planning mode can put things on cool down and make you vulnerable for follow up.However the combat does start a bit slow as you only start with a couple abilities and unlock both more abilities and more upgrade slots (the slots that let you combine abilities) as you go, so it starts slow but picks up fast as you go along. Similarly enemies are very easy at the start and most players will find fights fairly easy till most of the upgraded late game enemies start showing up. If those still aren't enough for you, you can activate ""Limiters"" which are optional and make the game even harder (such as spawning more enemies and make them do 2x damage).The story is very good and personally I enjoyed it even more than Bastion, though it is done very differently. Where Bastion gave the player a lot of knowledge, including knowledge the players character wouldn't know, and all but held the players hand through the story, Transistor gives you story through the eyes of it's characters, and it's up to the player to gain an understanding of what is going on in the story through the information their character is given throughout the game. This gives the story greater depth and immersion, but can also make the story more difficult for some people to understand or for those who skip through a lot of the dialogue. If you want to know everything about the in-game world then you might not enjoy the story of Transistor, however if you like to see a story from the view of a character present at the time and immersion that can bring, then you will probably find the story of Transistor amazing.Finally the length of the game runs about 5-6 hours. There is NG+ (and I hear NG++, though I haven't quite gotten there yet) and you can get further upgrades for playing NG+ so if you enjoy the gameplay there is some incentive to play past the ending of the story (you can get a couple hours of gameplay just trying out different ability loadouts with the amount of combinations available), though if you only want the game for story then there isn't much incentive for multiple play throughs unless you want to revisit the story.In summary the game is simply amazing. Both the combat and the story have a lot of depth to them. Though players who want the story spelled out for them or more twitch based combat may want to consider looking elsewhere. For those coming from Bastion know that this game is great as well but it is also VERY different, so don't expect Bastion 2.0 in a sci-fi setting, both the gameplay and story are done in a very different fashion so be sure to keep that in mind if you decide to pick it up."
