76561197972291747,Recommended,237930,11079739,"Posted: 4 July, 2014",all,meathorse,"Thumbs up because:- Pretty- Quality voice actor (a true rarity!)- Flexible combat skill management system- Innovative non-death penalties for losingShame I don't enjoy playing it. Especially since Supergiant also made Bastion, the undisputed best creative work mankind has ever produced.The plot? I don't get the plot, which is amazing considering how much talking that damn memory-stick-for-a-sword does. At the onset, characters are introduced in quantity and events transpire rapidly... I promptly acquired an unrecoverable amount of plot knowledge debt. Storywise, Transistor quickly spreads out in width, but not in depth... not until my anticipation had degenerated into indifference. I perpetually felt one step behind whatever was happening.Transistor has a hybrid real-time/turn-based combat system (which makes up the bulk of the game) that isn't worth dwelling on. It's admirably done, and there's surely an audience for it, but I found it repetitive, predictable and boring.The way that Red's skills are managed however... this is the good stuff. The real good stuff. Your combat abilities are called ""functions"". They sit in a great, big uncategorized pile. You can combine and use them however you see fit. Functions can be ""installed"" in 1 of 3 ways; as one of your 4 active abilities, as upgrades to those 4 abilities, or as passives. There are combinations that work very well, and combinations that work very poorly. Playing around with them is a treat. And you WILL play around with different function combinations whether you like it or not... because when your health runs out, rather than die, you lose the use of an active function. It stays disabled for long enough that you'll be compelled to replace it with something else in the meantime. It's a clever alternative to traditional gaming death that doesn't break flow, does invoke a penalty, AND promotes experimentation. Out of desperation, I was forced into using function combinations that I never would have otherwise... and oftentimes the effects were a pleasant surprise.I believe that other people will find virtue or indifference where I find fault. Thumbs up and uninstalled."
,Recommended,237930,10267411,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,Phaazoid,"Another quality experience from SuperGiant Games.The gameplay itself was solid.  Being able to mix and match all of the existing powers in so many ways had a great sandbox feel to it.  However, all of the enemy encounters were very scripted, limiting how long you could experiment.It saddened me a little that the gameplay was confined to these short bursts of action.  I'm not sure if it was done this way in order to preserve the points of narration, or becuase the art was just so good, from such a small studio.  I wonder if the game may have felt longer if the presentation of the combat had been approached differently. However, the combat that was there was very enjoyable, with lots of quirks to explore.The music, art, and story were all superb.  But, these only feel on par because of what was sacraficed to attain them - gameplay and length of the game. The new game+ is required to get all of the game's achievements, yet doesn't add anything of value except for more gameplay.  This feels lazy to me, the gameplay should have been scaled for a single playthough instead of forcing the player to loop through again.  It might have some significance to the story, but that doesn't justify forcing the player to do everything again.But for all of the picking I'm doing, I do recommend the game.  The first time I played it through, the experience was incredibly tight, the story sucked me in, and I was equally enthralled by the gameplay and the art.  I recommend this game, but maybe wait for the steam sales."
