76561198052781610,Recommended,237930,10421875,"Posted: 10 June, 2014",all,TheJugglernaut,"I often find myself remissed that ""I'm not up to date with the latest games,"" or that ""I don't play as much as I used to.""  Perhaps that's because I don't find many games like Transistor.I recently found myself in the thralls of illness, and thus free from my daily responsibilites.  I decided to use this spare time to play the recently purchased Transistor.  In Transistor, the female protagonist (Red) is guided by an unknown familiar that is somehow trapped in the weapon that she wields: The Transistor.  You soon learn that they took her voice and she is driven, initially, by a sense of revenge and justice.  However, as the story unfolds, more questions arise as new entities are encountered and new perspectives are obtained.  Ultimately, many questions are left unanswered at the end of the story.  Even though you never truly know some of the details about Red's life before our story begins, and are left with a hazy understanding of the world that Red lives in, you gain absolute clarity of her character.First: Transistor was great to play.  Easy to pick up and learn, lots of options for upgrading and combining skills, and a nice medium for employing different strategies in fights.  The concept of essentially pausing battle in order to carry out attacks was very heavy early in the game, and it wasn't until later that I realized that it also played as an action/rpg style combat where using the transistor for planning was optional.  It proved to be beneficial to be proficient in both types of combat as I moved through the game. It was fun, challenging, and engaging to take the different challenges and encounter new enemies with abilities that I was already familiar with using against them.I found the story to be one of the best stories for any video game I have played.  It was compelling, it was beautiful, it filled me with sorrow and it filled me with joy.  It wasn't just the story that was compelling though; the way that they used Red's 'acquaintance' in the transistor to drive the story was a spectacularly subtle mechanism for keeping the player up to date with how Red might be moticated or directed by each event in the game.The music didn't really stick out in this game for me.  To clarify: the music was great.  Many games really showcase the music, or to use the music to alert the player to a change in envoronment or mood.  In Transistor, the music fits seamlessly into the story, the gameplay, the entire experience of the game.  The music is a huge part of the game, helping to immerse the player into the ""Transistor experience"" by helping establish the setting rather than distracting from it in order to let you know that you're in a new place, or that danger is afoot!The artwork? Beautiful.  Like the music, it seemed perfectly suited to this story to provide the most engaging, immersive experience.  It's easy enough to find the art for the game online or previews, so I won't say much more here.Everything about this game worked together to provide a wonderful, spectacular experience that I have been encouraging others to try since I've played it.  My love for video games has been rekindled, and I hope to see more games like this.How is the replay value?  I'm going to find out!"
