,Recommended,237930,16615392,"Posted: 22 June, 2015",all,Proxeh,"Transistor is a beautiful game, from the art, world and music. It shows what it would feel like if you were inside the most fancients and most elegant of computer architecture. The is really cute with using computer jargon in it's gameplay and story elements. Such as not having enough memory to load all your functions. The story seems good, but is easily missable, the game emplores you to look for the story via reading the terminals and listening to your transistor blade. Where Transistor really shines is it's combat and difficulty. The combat is very unique while it is in real time there is a turn based element where you can unload a series of attacks simultaneous but doing so will leave you vulnerable to attack. So juggling between the turn based and real time combat is challenging and fun. The side missions which are the speed/perfomance/planning test are optional and quite fun. The planning tests I found the most fun, where you must defeat all the enemies in one turn. I would have like to see more tests and test variety. The games difficulty is dictated by limiters. Which are positive buffs to the enemies or negative buffs on you, you can decide how many are activate. The more that are active the more harder the game is. There is just enough different types of enemies to keep things fresh. I would have liked to see more creative boss battles as well as more of them. The game is quite short clocking around 4 - 5 hours if you're just doing the main story only. But it has a lot of replay value in it's combat and difficulty. Highly recommend if you are looking for a neo noir futuristic RPG which tries something new."
