,Recommended,237930,10188745,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,Borosov,"Before anything, I will preface this and say if you have any interest in ARPG's and are looking for a wonderful and short experience, you SHOULD pick this game up. Well worth the $20 in my opinion.  If you want a detailed explanation, feel free to read and a TLDR is at the bottom.PROS:◘Visually pleasing to the eyes, absolutly gorgeous presentation in both animation and the enviornment.◘Sound design is top notch.◘Narration done throughout the game is fun to listen to.◘Can play with either mouse or keyboard.◘Fairly intriguing theme and story get you interested◘Should run fairly well on most machines.◘Fairly challenging as you can easily be ""killed"" multiple times during any battle.○When you ""die"" in combat, 2 things can happen: The first is on the brink of death you engage a emergency Turn mode (Turn is explained later below) and can fight to kill a few more enemies. The second possibility is that you ""break"" a function from combat for a while, and after visiting 2 (or more) Function Kiosks you can reactive them. If you break them, you are then forced to play around with your kit to experiment with new loadouts.◘Variety of combat with many different enemies with various different upgrade versions of them.◘Absolutely STELLAR combat system along with the configurations along with it (Which are detalied below)○As you play the game, you obtain various skills and upgrades through leveling up or finding them around the world and they are called Functions.○You can use these Functions in 3 ways: The first is the Active Function which you use for combat that does its base effect. The second is the Upgrade Function, where you take one of your Functions and use it to augment another Active Function, giving it special or different effect. And lastly is the Passive Function, in which you take a Function and put it into a passive state where it will always give a effect, or activate at specific under different conditions. EVERY Function in the game connects together in one way or another.○As you play the game, you are allowed to fight in either real time where you cast your abilities against the enemies movements and actions with no cooldown penalty, engage the Turn system to pause the game and tactically decide how you want to approach the situation. In Turn you can move almost instantly anywhere and manually aim your shots and action which are limited by a action bar. You then execute the procedure and watch your plan unfold rapidly. However, the downside to this is that once you are done with your Turn actions, you cannot use your abilities until your Turn meter has recharged. Because of these 2 systems you have a choice as to how you want to fight your battles.◘You can use ""limiters"" to further increase the difficulty of the game and gain a small amount of bonus EXP for leveling.◘New game plus mode with all of your stuff you unlocked.CONS:◘The UI can be just a little bit wonky with assigning Functions to various roles.◘Because the story is not made apparently clear at first, you can easily get lost.◘Turn actions that detail the effects may not always be accurate, as enemies may dodge and it doesn't tell you that information.◘May be just a bit short for some, as I and other have managed to beat the game at around 6 hours.◘Because there is new game plus and not much more, some people may not find a lot of replayability from this, resulting a 6 hour experience for $20 dollars.◘The only real set of graphics options are just resolutions.TLDR: Great combat, visuals and fun for ARPG fans. Can be beaten in about 6 hours, and depending on the user the new game plus can offer replayability.Can be of a bumpy ride for the first hour for people to get used to, but you get over it quickly.Overall, I feel that just about everyone should buy this beauty. The devs that made this deserve every dollar they earn and then some for the amount of effort and love that was poured into this game."
76561197997489666,Recommended,237930,10203853,"Posted: 22 May, 2014",all,Rogue Physicist,"Transistor is an RPG by the creators of Bastion. Similarly to their previous game, the art, story, and sound design are all fantastic. The combat is a weird hybrid between real-time and turn-based that will probably be hit-or-miss with most people. The robust skill system was incredible and is probably one of Transistor's best features.The combat is different than most other games. You can move and attack in real time, but you'll find it difficult to survive without using the Turn() feature. Turn() pauses the game and allows you to plan out your next few movements and attacks. The planned actions will then be executed very quickly, without the enemies being able to attack or move. Turn() then goes on cooldown for a few seconds and most of your skill won't be usable. This creates a turn-like tempo in the the fights where you attack with Turn() and then play defensively when it's on cooldown.  The combat takes a little getting used to and won't be for everyone, but it really works well with the skill system.The skill system is one of the games best features. I didn't unlock all of the skill on the first playthough, but there are at least 16 of them. Each skill can be used in 3 ways.1. Active Skill: The skills you use in combat. You get 4 active skill slots.2. Augementation: Each active slot has two augmentation slots which alter the effect of the active skill.3. Passive Skill: Each skill has a different passive effect when placed in one of the 4 passive slots.Although this seems to be overly complex, you only start with a couple skills, the 4 active slots, and an augmentation slot for each of them. You gain additional skills and slots when you level up so the game does a good job of easing you into the skill system. Furthermore, the game does an excellent job of pushing you to experiement and try new skill combinations. I had a lot of fun experimenting with the skills and trying to find effective combinations.In conclusion, Transistor is a great game. If you liked Bastion, or are a fan of turn based RPGs, you should get this game. If you're unsure that you'll like the combat, you should look at a couple gameplay videos, but try not to spoil the story for yourself."
,Recommended,237930,11268276,"Posted: 15 July, 2014",all,Scratch17,"SuperGiant Games have seriously outdone themselves. Transistor is an amazing game. Visually, it's absolutely stunning. Gorgeous and complex in some places, and stark and stylized in others, you end up just looking around, taking your time to soak in all the visual details. Coupled with the absolutely enchanting soundtrack, it just sets the tone of the game perfectly. The combat is pretty smart and highly customizable as well, although the real-time aspect of it is a bit clunkier than, for example Bastion's, but that's not the main focus in Transistor. The story is kinda told to you through the Transistor sword; more as a companion than a narrator this time. You can also choose your level of involvement in the story as well, which is always a nice feature. You can play through in a straight line, or take your time and find all the little details of the city of Cloudbank and its citizens.Overall, a very VERY hearty recommendation for Transistor. Well done, SuperGiant."
