,Recommended,237930,10879092,"Posted: 27 June, 2014",all,fragranthills,"Just a great game all-around.Most everybody that's interested in this game will be comparing it to Bastion, so we'll go with that metric.In terms of gameplay, Transistor is quite different than Bastion.  Yes, they're both top-down hack-and-slashes at heart, but while Bastion's beating heart lies squarely in twitch/dodge/attack mechanics, Transistor is a more contemplative experience with its Turn() system.  In fact, the grand majority of Transistor ends up playing much more like a tactics game than a hack-and-slash game; use of skills outside of Turn() is limited and you'll spend most of your time outside of Turn() playing keep-away.  Some people may find this a downgrade, but if you're the sort of person that enjoyed Bastion and also logged hundered-hour files in tactical RPG games (myself included) you'll find yourself comfortable in the world of Transistor.In terms of style, Transistor is very much cut from the same cloth as Bastion.  That's to be expected when Bastion was such a beautiful and lovingly crafted game.  Painterly visuals abound, and Darren Korb (music) and Logan Cunningham (primary voice actor) are both back in top form, as I'm sure everyone not living in a cave is aware.  Come for the audio-visual niravana, stay for the gameplay.As far as criticisms are concerned, stability of the game is still a bit lower than could be desired at this point; I had to play around with the files of the game to overcome the dreaded startup crash bug that many people have been complaining of.  A minor criticisim:  If you're the sort of person that doesn't play around with the dynamic difficulty system (Bastion's Pantheon : Transistor's Limiters) you may find the game easy once you've unlocked some of the more powerful functions (I found it a bit trivial even with half the limiters on).  A New Game + feature and use of all the limiters is an easy remedy for those wanting more gameplay and more challenge.Three things that are fab:# Turn() system and executing sets that make you feel like a genius# Wonderfully detailed world and story# Extra story exposition linked to use of Functions for that extra bit of OCD fodderThree things that are butt:# May not work immediately on some computers# No Steamplay support as of yet# A bit easy for those seeking a teeth-grinding experienceAll in all, Transistor is a wonderful nugget of a game that you shouldn't hesistate to pick up, even at its introductory price-point.  If you liked Bastion for its artistic elements, you'll love Transistor, and if you enjoy tactical games you may end up liking Transistor even more than Bastion.  I know I did!  The main story lasted me roughly nine hours when doing everything available, and I have a bit of a completionist bent.  I have just started a New Game+ session."
,Recommended,237930,10263810,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,SinnerCoco,"Gorgeous game! Loved it to bits, the ending threw a curve ball of mixed emotions at me though hahahaha"
76561198020478540,Recommended,237930,10228972,"Posted: 25 May, 2014",all,JJ Black,"Transistor - the followup game to Supergiant's Bastion - does exactly what it's pedecessor does. Delivering a polished top down action-RPG with a narrative driven storyline. The game has a pronounced ""interactive storybook"" feeling resulting from the games total linearity but to be fair the book is pretty damn good.Logan Cunningham's narration of Bastion was one of the most prominent features of Bastion and in Transistor he fulfills much the same role. Being your ever present companion he lends the game a magical yet melancholy feel. He exposes you to the concept of the world, the story and the characters without overexplaining anything and leaving you to fill in the blanks.The combat is no slouch either. 16 different moves can be combined or used as passive improvements and tested in the many encounters scattered throughout the storyline. How about firing a blast that scatters into bombs which scatter into more bombs when they explode...and then scatter into even more bombs afterwards - yeah.The music is really awesome as well and supplements the feel of the whole game perfectly. I'm just in love with the song ""The Spine"".A highly imaginitive game, an adult fairy tale, emotionally and intellectually stimulating - the full package. A really enjoyable experience. It just leaves me wondering what Supergiant Games' next storybook is going to be like.10/10 - Showing that not every game has to be a sandbox!(If combat is too hard: try Spark()+Mask()+Purge() and the Bounce() Passive and just spam it)"
