76561198048623723,Recommended,237930,32909429,Posted: 27 June,all,Skynred,"One word: Functions.Functions are kinda sorta your ""skills"" in Transistor--and it's one of the most interesting skill systems I've ever seem. I like figuring out a good build of my own in anything I play, and Transistor's Functions allow just that.  What the Devs came up with here is brilliant.The game's story is weirdly intriguing. Its graphics and soundtrack are also very charming--but these things are secondary for me. The actual gameplay is what matters, and the game did not disappoint in that regard. To sum up:- You can either fight in real time, or pause, issue Red (your character) commands, watch as she executes it, and then play in real time for a few seconds while your ability to pause and issue orders recharges.- The Functions system, like I said before, is awesome.- The game is adequately challenging: it's hard, but not too much.- The final boss fight is quite interesting as well, rather unique.This is a very well thought-out game--you can feel the love that went into it. It doesn't copy anyone, it's none of that crap of ""hey, everyone's doing zombies or crafting games now, so let's do the same!"" Transistor is different, its refreshing, and its GOOD.The only downside is that it lasts only 7-8 hours. I got through it in one day. On the other hand, it's the only game I've played in 25 years or so of videogames that was very satisfactory even being so short--and there's also a New Game+ mode that let's you keep all your Functions and finally put together that dream build while fighting more and tougher enemies.In as few words as possible: although short, Transistor is totally worth your money."
