,Recommended,237930,12742729,"Posted: 2 November, 2014",all,Kaborer BrKN,"Supergiant Games, who're also behind Bastion, really know how to make games that shine through in my opinion.Games can sometimes seem bland and even unimportant and I play a lot of games that feel like that...When I encounter games like Transistor, I start thinking about why I even play the games that don't do thing as well. I held back with playing transistor for a very long time because people had been going into transistor to play another 'Bastion', and had been dissapointed. So I really wanted to forget the idea that this would be another 'Bastion' and I almost did, untill... I played the game.I didn't regard 'another Bastion' as something that would come in mechanical or storywise likeliness, but rather a game that did the same to me, that Bastion did.The game starts you off 'in medias res' and gives to few clues as to why you're here and what you're doing, the story unfolds at it's own pace and through the two-person monologue that takes place, with this time's narrarator. The game immediately striked me as a viual masterpiece, but that also leads me to one of my complaints... The only graphical option there is, is resolution. Now, I get it, most of the game is hand-drawn, which is really impresive, but it still wouldn't hurt to throw some graphical option in there, especially because there is a short part where Red, the main character, is really close to the screen and I noticed she was very, very blurry and was the one time I was taken out of the experience.Now that I've mentioned one critique, let's jusmp right into the next one... I want more, I mean I don't think there's anything wrong with the game being a 5-or-so hour experience but I have a hard time using the game's 'recourse' (NewGame+) because the game is so dependant on the narrative and the experience, that playing it a second time for challange seems like sacrificial butchering to me, with that said I understand that some people don't feel that way, It's just a bit short, so don't expect to be using 10+ hours on this game. ...This paragraph was me whining that I liked it so much that I want more.I must say, there are few things that capture me like this game, the whole of just work so damned well. I mean the atmosphere, the music, the visuals, the mechanical feel of the game, and the story clash toghether beautifully, and just make me feel the story so much, I even found myself answering on behalf of Red a few times. And not just that old ""Oh you're gonna die.""-type of stuff, but heartfelt replies to what happened in the world.The atmosphere is desolate and dystopian, you're alone and you're fighting against odds, in a world where help comes very indirectly. I ended feeling a longing for the people close to the main character, and I was afraid on her behalf not to see them again (Spoilers, someone you know is not with you at some part of the game). The visuals work very well with the atmosphere as the city to start is dark and empty while giving an urban-look which in it's whole is very unsetteling. Of course Darren Korb has done it again, and composed a masterpiece of a soundtrack which just hits the spot. I don't have much more to say about that, really. All of this of course compliments the story which I would characterize as beautiful, dystopian and tragic.The last thing I want to discuss are the mechanics. They strike me odd, but interesting,  and very appealing, but they feel heavy and a bit hard-maneuvarable. Surprisingly I don't have a problem with them though as I feel they reflect the position Red is in.In conclution:I love this game.I will soon be using this game to write a project, along with other similar games with narrators."
