76561198043797603,Recommended,237930,20433094,"Posted: 9 January, 2016",all,Your Uncle Bob,"I was intrigued by this game back when it was announced at PlayStation conference. The music and the art style got me. Well, I wasn't wrong. It's a fantastic game. A bit short, but sweet. Soundtrack is a blast. It reminded me of old Silent Hill days when some of the tracks were vocalized and performed by Mary Elizabeth McGlynn. I really liked it then and same thing applies here as well. ""We all become"" is easily something I can listen many times a day. Gameplay is a lot of fun. 4-5 hours in, and you can already make almost godly builds and breeze through the game. Too easy? Install limiters and test your build for the exchange of xp. The game does a very good job at describing what each skill does and how to mix them. Achievements are quite simple and straightforward as well. If you're into these kind of things, it should be a cinch. Story's good too. A little touching, I'd say. The only cons are that it's a little short and endgame isn't very exciting. I played roughly for 20 hours, loved it, but don't see myself going back to it for now.9/10 - would hum along again."
,Recommended,237930,10389205,"Posted: 7 June, 2014",all,A Fancy Fridge Magnet,"Transistor is a visually stunning game from the devs that made Bastion. The amount of detail in the areas that you don't even spend much time in is incredible. Hard to really say much more about it... it's a very unique style, similar in many ways to Bastion, but  more squared townsquare types of areas as opposed to the more natural style of Bastion (which was less angles, more curves.)Just like Bastion, the soundtrack is perfect and fits so well. It's something you can listen to outside of game and still be pleased.The story is delivered via dialogue and in-game text via computer terminals. The story is ok, but is just incredibly shallow and vague. Character motives are never really explained, it just feels like there were a few events that were described or implied, and you just have to go, ""oh okay."" It seems like a very small episode of a much larger story.The game play itself is actually fairly challenging and consists of a mixture of real-time combat and turn-based combat. Enemies appear on screen and you can attack them, but more often than not there are many of them, they're fast and disruptive. The turn-based combat is a mode you enter into, then you get to plan out your moves and attacks before having them execute in slow-motion. It's really satisfying, but is manadatory through the majority of the second half of the game. You just take way too much unavoidable damage otherwise.The enemies themselves actually feel fairly frustrating a lot of the time. There are certain units you REALLY have to priortize, otherwise you just won't win the fights. While priortizing those targets, you're pretty much getting attacked by all the others. Later on in the game these mechanics are less strategic and just more frustrating. There is also not much variety in the enemies... so the encounters end up being X amount of these guys, Y amounts of these guys, fight. Kind of lame, as it removes some depth and strategy that could come from complex fight scenarios, and instead goes for ""just throw more guys at him.""Attacks are called functions, an you unlock many, but can only equip 4 of them. The extras can be socketed into your 4 main functions to upgrade them (additional effects), or as passives that activate based on certain conditions. There's a lot of variety here, and different abilities work better in certain situations than others.If you lose all your health in combat, instead of dying one of your functions gets overloaded and you have to continue on fighting without it. I'm pretty sure the function that gets overloaded was the last one you used prior to ""death"", but not 100% sure. This cycle continues until you run out of functions completely I suspect (I never had this happen though.) It's a nice way of lessening the chances of you getting stuck and not being able to get by to continue the game... which is good because sometimes you get really unlucky in a fight and it prevents you from feeling like the game hates you as much. Functions become useable again after you access a couple of switcher terminal things later on in the levels, so until then you pretty much have to swap them out with other functions or go on without 4 functions.Overall, I think this game was pretty enjoyable. It has a very high level of thought and polish put into it. The combat system is incredibly good, but the combat scenarios are weak and frustrating at times. The game doesn't necessarily feel ""fun"" to play, which is the same gripe I had with Bastion, but that doesn't mean it wasn't enjoyable or not worth a playthrough. I think this mainly stems from both these games not really having ""low"" or ""bad"" points that make the great points stand out.The game is also incredibly short... I beat it in ~5 hours according to steam, and I tried to interact with as much as I could find. This is probably the biggest ""issue"" with it... it just ends up sort of unfulfilling. It does however have a New Game + mode, so you can continue to level and unlock more things, as well as a lot of ""challenge"" levels where you can hone your skills. I think this game should have had more hands working on it, in order to really make the scope much larger in terms of gameplay and story. There is absolutely no filler in the game which is good, but like I said earlier in the review, it feels like an episode of something much bigger.... so huge amounts of potential left unexplored. Still, the amount of time, effort and detail that went into this game is really apparent in every way imaginable. For what it's worth, if you've played neither of these games, I'd highly recommend playing Bastion before this."
