,Recommended,237930,10246293,"Posted: 26 May, 2014",all,Bl0rch,"Play this game!If you are a programmer or otherwise familiar with computers and electronics, you will especially find this game interesting.For those who need more detail, it's a real-time RPG that is in the same style as Bastion (it's from the same devs), also taking from cames like Syndicate, La Mulana, and Shadowrun (to name a few).The voice acting is superb, the music, very well done. The visuals are very crisp and paint a very good picture of the world driven by computers and machinery.The combat is very fast paced and can be difficult, but you are able to employ some planning by using the Turn() function to get the upper hand. You can level up and customize your abilities to fit your style, so there's a little something for everyone.If you are at all a fan of Bastion and you like RPG's, you need to play this game."
76561198030283156,Recommended,237930,18914738,"Posted: 6 November, 2015",all,Bullet Sponge,"A deeply inspired game. Transistor not only has a nice aesthetic, but a handful of well implemented and creative gameplay mechanics. It is a healthy marriage of arcade power-ups and tactics, where player experimentation is key. For games that promise both live and turn based action, the player is usually given the choice between either - in Transistor you will want to master both forms of gameplay if you wish to gain the edge.The most intriguing part of the game is the power-up system. Throughout the game the player collects a series of ""functions"". These functions can be used as new attacks - choosing up to a total of four moves. Each function has a unique effect, letting the player choose from sneak attacks, long range strikes, clustering explosions, summoning minions, and more, or any combination of these. But the functions aren't limited to simple attacks. In addition to the four move slots, the player also has four passive slots to install their functions, and each move has two upgrade slots. The upgrades are really something special, allowing the player to improve and expand on or even change completely the nature of a move. As the player collects more of these functions, playstyles can become more and more diverse. The number of possibilities are staggering.The gameplay itself is challenging enough that certain combinations may be found ineffective or require careful planning and skill to use. This is what makes the game whole as an interactive experience. The player has to strategize, adapt, evaluate, refine, rearrange. You can't just brute force your way through (though certain combinations do give a whole new meaning to ""brute force""). You can't just grind to max stats and max gear.If you like games that emphasize tactics and positioning, and enjoy making lots of experimental play styles. THIS is the game for YOU. If you don't, well, do me a favor, play it anyway."
