,Recommended,237930,10667749,"Posted: 22 June, 2014",all,Bastion,"One of the best games i've ever played.It's a short game, you can complete in about 5/6 hours, where you fight sets of enemies (called ""Process"") as you progress through the story.You fight the enemies with your abilities, that the game calls Functions. The interesting thing about it is that even though you have a set of abilities, the same ability can be used in different ways: as an active ability, as an upgrade to another ability or as a passive ability. The game tells you what each ability do in each of those 3 roles. This leads to an endless number of possible ways you can combine your abilities. Not only that but it does it in a very good way, since there's not exactly an obvious choice of ""loadout"" and multiple alternatives are viable and effective to fight against the enemies. It really leaves space for you to use the abilities the way you fell more comfortable with. In the beginning it might be hard to figure out which abilities to use and how you will use them, the amount of choices you have is a little bit overwhelming, but as you play you will learn the weaknesses and strengths of each one until it's really no longer a problem. The game helps you with that, you are given only a few abilities to use at the start and you unlock new ones little by little.The combat itself is very innovative. You can use your abilities just pressing its button, just like in an mmo or Diablo. But more often than not, you will be using the Turn() mode. In this mode the game is paused and you can plan your movements and the attacks you will do, then execute the plan. The game has no difficulty selection, but you can customize how hard the game can be by using the Limiters, some of them buff your enemies while others nerf the player in general. By choosing Limiters, the combat will be harder but you will receive more experience and level up faster as a result.This makes up the core mechanics of the game, which i greatly enjoyed.But an excellent mechanic is not only what this game has to offer.The visuals and the art style is incredible, i would dare to say it is the most beautiful isometric game i've ever saw. Really really good. The soundtrack is also very good, not only it is good on a musical standpoint as it also fits the game perfectly and contributes greatly for a better immersion.I would highly recommend this game to anyone, if you are still not sure, wait for a sale, otherwise buy it full price. And you may also want to grab the soundtrack. You will want it after playing the game."
,Recommended,237930,11420225,"Posted: 26 July, 2014",all,Varsoon,"If ever there was a game that flaunted its squandered potential, it is Transistor. What exists in Transistor is a duality of very captivating plot and brilliant-fun game design alongside dully written paragraphs of texts and tedious groan-worthy moments of play. Conceptually, Transistor presents a lore rich world with gameplay options that are variable enough to suit the player's desires and offer a huge variety of play. In practice, Transistor's plot is delivered to the player in a scattershot and confusing fashion, with text logs providing most of the lore and significant interactions of the game. In play, Transistor's multi-faceted system becomes either exploit-a-strategy to win or get destroyed. Environments that the game tells us are really interesting end up feeling more like arenas for the next fight, and the entire game gets wrapped up in moving from arena to arena, hoping the plot will become more accessible by the next big fight. The beautiful art direction and captivating soundtrack offer just that more of the tease of what Transistor could have been. For its low price, it's certainly worth enjoying what Transistor is--a touching, sometimes-confusing romp through a cyberpunk strategy combat world."
