,Recommended,237930,10947606,"Posted: 29 June, 2014",all,Spaghetti Sloth #420blazescope,"If you prefer quality over quantity this game is for you. Transistor is a fantastic game with amazing soundtracks that you hear throughout the game. The gameplay itself is quite unique but the best way I could describe it is if you had Dragon Age:Origin's ability to stop time and every move or attack you plan,sucked up this time bar that let you stay in that frozen time and after you unleash your barrage of attacks it would just charge back up read for you to use again. This is pretty crucial to most combat in the game so you'll tend to spam it as soon as it comes off cooldown. The story when you first start is pretty confusing and I pretty much had no idea what was going on until I was done with a 1/3 of the game and the game isn't really straightforward with the storytelling so you pretty much have to go through with the tidbits that are given to you at the beginning and just complete the puzzle by either completing files or going through OVC terminals or just listening to what the characters say during their dialogues. The customization allows you to format abilities you can use during a battle, augment those abilities onto another ability that enhances it in some way, or you can decide to augment it onto your body. You can pretty much switch however way you want it anytime during the game provided you get to a terminal which is pretty common throughout the whole game. I was actually impressed with how the game looked overall and it pretty much looked like a work of art, not counting the gameplay aspects or the phenomenal soundtracks. The replayability is pretty much the same as Bastion and it lets you restart over and is called Recursion, keeping your abilitites and level so you can go through the whole game fighting the same late game enemies you would be fighting at the end of the game. Transistor is short, you could probably finish the whole game in around 10 hours but sweet jesus it's 10 really good hours without even touching the Recursion aspect. Transistor is GOTY material, buy it, try it, cry at how short it is."
,Recommended,237930,12590299,"Posted: 20 October, 2014",all,SagaciousJones,"Transistor blends Bastion’s fast-paced isometric combat with a methodical tactical planning mode to create a unique action system that fits well within its vibrant urban sci-fi setting. You can assign each ability as an action command, a passive bonus, or as an upgrade to another ability, which allows for a vast variety of combinations. This character customization, as well as your options to tweak enemy abilities, provides you significant freedom to tailor your game experience.  Bastion’s combat sandbox and escalating challenge modes return, complementing Transistor’s many avenues for player experimentation. The combat system, however, does significantly favor the planning mode, leaving you relatively weak during the real-time portions while you wait for your planning ability to recharge.  The gorgeous character art and atmospheric music paint a beautiful presentation over the solid gameplay, but the story feels stretched thin as major characters and events receive only minor acknowledgement before moving on. Moreover, the omnipresent narrator says little of value and his comments come across as a scattered stream-of-consciousness in contrast to the wise insight of Bastion’s commentary. Transistor retains many of Bastion’s best elements and distinguishes itself with its unique hybrid action, but fails to entirely match its predecessor’s heights.4/5 – Really liked it."
