76561198007579261,Recommended,237930,16906047,"Posted: 6 July, 2015",all,Bomoo,"Before we begin, let us establish something that should be obvious from the game's title, but apparently isn't to some players:THIS IS NOT BASTION 2Playing it like it was Bastion 2 can only lead to frustration and disaappointment. To appreciate Transistor, you must approach it respectfully, on its own terms, and not guided by your own expectations, as, really, you should be doing with every game worth talking about.While it uses some of the same innovative mechanisms that were introduced in Bastion, it is not, nor does it try to be, more of the same - something I admire with Supergiant's production that, apparently, some players of the game find frustration with. They could've easily printed money by making a Bastion 2, but chose to make something original instead. How can you not admire such a departure from the unscrupulous money grab that is sadly becoming the norm in this hobby?I've likely already gifted you this game if we're on reasonably friendly terms. But for everyone else, allow me to say that, speaking as an experienced gamer, this is my favourite game. It is, in a word, perfection, and those of you who know how critical I can be of these things should know I do not say that lightly. Perfectly harmonized design, art direction, music, writing, everything. The team at Supergiant, earning themselves a place as my personal favourite developers, and in any case an honoured spot on the true A-list, have here created another superbly crafted game that I warmly encourage everyone to try and experience."
,Not Recommended,237930,16717479,"Posted: 26 June, 2015",all,Snuggles,"A couple of things - one - Puzzlefox's excellent thumbs down review adequately summarizes many of my complaints about the game, lack of variety, almost non-existent story, a tedious rather than rewarding challenge area, and simplistic enemies.  So there is that - having loved bastion to tag this game with any of those things (which it excelled at) is really disheartening. However aside from those issues I had some of my own (ignore my logged playtime, I got in about 3-4ish hours off the books.I still haven't finished this game. I may come back and change my review if I can ever stand to drudge my way through it. Until such a time - here are the reasons why despite loving bastion and SuperGiant; I consider this game a misfire and would only recommend it to people when it's on sale or if they simply want to support the studio without buying multiple copies of bastion.Combat.I really like turn-based games. I am enjoying my third playthrough of Invisible Inc at the time of writing this review, I also actually mucked around with the challenge modes and New Game + in Bastion, so I can get into some hack n slash. What I can't get into, no matter how hard I try, is violently switching between those two formats over and over in a fight. Or more accurately, I can't get into doing a ""turn"" and then running around or hiding for a few seconds while it recharges. It breaks my immersion, feels tedious, and honestly makes every fight in the game a chore. I know some people are really into this; and it clicks for them. I am deeply envious of those people because if the game had full turn-based I am positive I would have at least had the stomach to make it to the end.Story/NarrationI am combining these two, because I have yet to make it to the second boss (I am assuming there are three) in any playthrough and the second nail in the coffin is the narration. I love Logan as a voice actor, he essentially sold Bastion for me, and I'm not saying he needs to display a huge range in the early game. However - dribbling the story out slowly is simply less effective for me when he sounds so utterly emotionless and bored while delivering every single line. His dry quips never land, and honestly it's like they woke him up after trapping him in a sound booth and made sure he only recorded lines while still wiping the sleep from his eyes.Again - this might change in Act 3 or something - but if you bore me in the beginning I may never make it that far.Style.Initially I was really loving the art design. I still love the menus, music, and overall style. However one thing I lamented is that as I move from one section of the city to the next, I can barely tell any real difference. Part of what worked in Bastion was that each area felt distinct. With this game each area might have some slight variation, but the overwhelming same-ness of it all started to really wear on me. It didn't help that the random white blocks that popped up detracted from any sense of geography or style. In Bastion it was shop-carts, barrels, and plants. In this game it's just white blocks. White blocks. White Blocks. I'm not sure what they were going for here but it definitely contributed to my overall boredom.So inevitably it comes to this. If I had to rate it on a scale, I'd give it a 5/10. A well-polished game from a really good developer that simply misses several of the targets I really needed it to hit. However I don't get a scale, I just get a recommend or not. I don't recommend it, certainly not for $20. No one is sadder than me that I feel this way, and I sincerely hope their next game wins me back over."
