76561198037739127,Recommended,237930,11523839,"Posted: 2 August, 2014",all,TattleTale,"I bought TRANSISTOR at $13.39 and I got about 20 hours of high-quality playtime out of the purchase. I consider that a great buy.So many elements of this game standout:- The combat mechanics are fully customizable, strategic, and introduced in layers - as you play, not thrown at you all at once. There are so many creative ways to build that the heroine truly becomes your own.- The mixture of real-time/turn-based combat is seamless, and cleverly left in your control. I wish I could find more games with this system!- The story is compelling and told beautifully in sound and color (although much of it is open to your own interpretation). The voice-acting and artwork are first-rate.The downside is, the game will leave you wanting more - but in my experience, that is how all good books and films end. We wish there were another chapter."
,Recommended,237930,24425842,"Posted: 20 July, 2016",all,Mr. Darkness,"Transistor.I honestly can't tell which one, Bastion or Transistor were more to my liking. Both have their awesome unique mechanics and stunning music.When you start the game, you don't have a main menu, instead you are put right into the game. This really took my by surprise. I think you'll understand what I mean once you launch the game.So, lets get on with it.The Plot: 10/10Just like in Bastion, you are thrown right into the game without any introduction. Just a gal with a sword-like object which apparently talks. First I had no idea what was talking to me. The further you go into the story, the more is revealed, along with the backstory of Red (the main character, the musician). Soon it appears that 4 villans, the Camerata, those who basically own the city Cloudbank. Not only that, they are mostly scientists who care for the city, but made a mistake, and... well, you'll find out.Gameplay: 9/10Bastion had a right-left-midbutton gameplay, while here you get abilities that you use. Not only that, it is also followed with Turn() feature, a planning feature that allows you to stop time and make actions like walking and using abilities for the price of Turn() potential (lets call it that). For instance, a Breach() ability (your very first ability you have access to) uses 20 Turn().Not only that, you get some introduction to different characters who these abilities belonged to. For example, Red's ability is Breach(), an ability that stuns the target and makes it more vulnerable for 1.6 secs. Another one was a racer, when you used the transistor to ""absorb"" his essence, you retrieved an ability that allows you to blink. Furthermore, you can read info on these abilities that reveal about the character.Each ability can also be used as a passive or an upgrade to a different abilities. They can be swapped at any time when you get to an access point.And of course, remember the Shrine in Bastion? Here you have so called ""Limiters"", they work exactly the same as those things in the Shrine, except they also reveal info on the ""Process"" if used.Music: 10/10I won't comment on this. No point.Visuals: 10/10Seriously, the visuals are just amazing. Some may complain tho, that they don't like cyberpunk stuff, but to me, the art in this is majestic. The lights, the sketches, everything deserves a 10 in my opinion.Duration: 7/10Sadly, its rather short, but if you play with limiters you may get a longer enjoyment from this. That's exactly what I did with Bastion. Yet Transistor is still shorter than Bastion. I really wish it either had a continuation or just a longer gameplay. That may ruin the plot however.Replayable? Yes, definitely. Its worth replaying. Unlike Bastion, you don't have to grind here to get levels (because you can't, lol).Overall:I really want to give it 10/10, but I can't. I honestly just can't. I want it to be a bit longer, I want to get more enjoyment, maybe have a reality where Process comes from, where I can destroy its core, where I can have some sort of a choice like in Half-Life at the very end, or... I don't know. I just feel the urge for this to be longer.So any way.9/10, I can't wait for Supergiant games to release a new game. Maybe soon, maybe later, maybe next year (I actually heard they are working on a new game to be released in 2017).TL;DR Transistor is awesome, has great music, gameplay mechanics and great plot. If you feel like you need a game that would allow you to relax and feel some enjoyment, then this is it. I am a Dota 2 player myself, and nothing relaxed me more than Bastion and Transistor (especially transistor, tbh). Go buy it."
76561198027388146,Recommended,237930,10260196,"Posted: 27 May, 2014",all,TheAppetizer,"Transistor is a great action RPG with strategy components.  The combat is highly variable due to the customizable moveset; each ""function"" can be equipped as an action, a modification of another action, or a passive bonus.  The system allows for many playstyles and strategies which are fun to experiment with.  You can also pause time and queue actions to be executed rapidly, the tradeoff being that most moves will be rendered unusable for several seconds.The story here is largely told by a character who offers commentary in real time as opposed to in Bastion where a narrator is recounting the story.  Large parts of the plot are intentionally left open to interpretation, perhaps too much so, but it's a smart, multi-layered story that leaves you with lots to think about and at least a few pulled heart strings.The amazing soundtrack is by Darren Korb who did Bastion's soundtrack so that is another huge plus.  And lastly, there's a dedicated button for humming so there's really no legitimate excuse not to play."
