76561197970291212,Recommended,237930,11537712,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Psychohead,"First, I'll do the quick one: If you liked Bastion, just buy this and go. The story and music may not beasgood, but the art and gameplay areeven bettersomehow. Go go go.For everyone else: Transistor is an absolute blast. The mix-and-match nature of the combat system leads to all sorts of fun experimentation. The semi-turn-based nature is also unlike anything I've never played before, and that alone makes this game worth trying out. It takes a bit for things to really open up, as you have very few powers for the opening bits of the game. But once you've got a sizable arsenal, this game shines like a diamond.The setting and story are delightfully unusual, but immediately familiar to anyone who enjoyed Tron or Reboot. Supergiant still knows how to make a wonderful soundtrack, and Logan Cunningham is a welcome return as the voice of the eponymous Transistor.So what's not so great? The back quarter of the game does drag a little bit, and if you want more info on the world than what the story offers you, prepare to do an awful lot of reading of people's bios in menus. And while the general storyline and ending are fine, they do leave a lot up to guesswork and interpretation. That's not to say it's too complex, just that I was left wanting to know a bit more.Twenty bucks may be a bit high for some, as the game can be beaten in a few sittings. On the other hand, it also means the game is very tight. There's little wasted space, and there is a ""new game+"" feature if you're just not done once you're done. I highly, highly recommend this game to just about anyone, even if action games aren't normally you're thing. The combat is very adjustable to be as forgiving or brutally punishing as you like, and the turn system often makes it as much about thinking through a problem as about running around like a maniac."
