76561198035789880,Recommended,237930,11039246,"Posted: 2 July, 2014",all,Aerodynamics,"This game is amazing! As expected from Supergiant Games, the soundtrack and art direction are both stellar. There are two different choices for combat: real-time combat and turn based combat. In the turn based combat you can plan out your moves and execute them at the end of the planning turn. Your moves are called functions and can be implemented as an active, upgrade, or passive. The number of combinations surpasses even Bastion which leads to lots of flexibility to match all kinds of play styles. The story and cutscenes are also great.The game is a little short, it took me about 6 hours to beat. The whole experience was worth it though. You can also recurse through the story after you beat the game and keep all of your old functions. To recurse through the story and get all of the acheivements it took me an additional 12 hours (I liked wasting time testing out function combinations).If you liked Bastion, you will love Transistor. I can't recommend this game enough. Amazing."
,Recommended,237930,11052536,"Posted: 3 July, 2014",all,Tyrantsbane,"Supergiant Games has done it again.Transistor is an amazing experience in line with the developers previous game, Bastion.Story:Absolutely fantastic. You feel attached to the main character immediatly and the constant chatter of the Transistor deepens the experience to a whole new level. It isn't narrate in the vein that Bastion was, but in the fact that Transistor talks to you and makes comments as you go along. My only complaint in this section is that the game was short (about 5 hours). You'll be begging for more.Gameplay:Solid action RPG with a nice twist. The Turn() system is akin to the VATS system from Fallout where you pause time and can move and attack without much repercussion. The downside of this is if you use all of the meter, you have a cooldown where you can't attack and are vulnerable. Combat can be a little tough, as a lot of the enemies can deal some serious damage later on, so you have to be smart about your attacks.  As you level up you get to choose new skills, upgrade exsisting skills, and choose limiters. Limiters are akin to the Gods of Bastion, in which you can toggle them to increase the difficulty of the game.Music:Engrossing and enthralling. It sets such a mood in the game. Some serious talent here from the composer. Way better soundtrack than Bastion, and I thought Bastion was incredible already.Conclusion:While it is short, it is totally worth the admission price. It is a wonderful experience and I am looking forward for more games from the developers."
