,Recommended,237930,13777233,"Posted: 1 January, 2015",all,user 18,"Wholly enjoyed this game. The combat system is new, unique, and a real pleasure. This is without a doubt the best game I have ever played. Everyone needs to experience Transistor for themselves."
,Recommended,237930,12805228,"Posted: 5 November, 2014",all,Gordy the Pirate,"A visually striking piece of storytelling that drives home the point that you can create a fantastic storyline even when your main character is mute.I'm honestly not sure where to start with Transistor, other than to say this is one of those games I'd recommend everyone play before they die. The story is simple to follow while being beautifully mysterious at the same time, easily warranting a second playthrough just to pick up on the things that you overlooked before. Even if you don't care for a backstory though, what's happening in the forefront is more than enough to keep you interested, all the way up to the climactic end.The main characters--Red, the Transistor, and the four Camerata--are all well-designed and, perhaps more importantly, well-developed individuals who each have a personality that will stick with you well after completing the game. They're characters with motives that seem crystal clear in the beginning, but as the story unravels, your entire perspective gets turned on it's head.Red, the protagonist, is a female singer who refuses to let anyone control her, including the player. She may be mute, but she shows that she still has a prominent voice, despite the circumstances. The Transistor, Red's companion, is a cautious, loving individual that wants nothing more than Red's safety. He wants to protect her, but he's unable to in his immobile state. The Camerata, the villains of the game, is an organization that unleashes a malicious ""virus"" on the city known as the Process, slowly wiping out the entire civilization of Cloudbank. Uncovering the true motivations behind each of these characters is an exciting and surprising part of the narrative. It's hard to gush about this game without completely spoiling my favorite parts, so I'll stop my speech there.Besides the story, there are a few final things that really sold me on this game. First of all, the art direction of Transistor is absolutely stunning. Many times while playing I found myself doubling back just to appreciate the vistas a little longer. Honestly, I wish they'd release an art book, because I'd buy that in a heartbeat. On top of that, if you're familiar at all with Supergiant or Darren Korb, then you know how incredible this game's music will be. This soundtrack, along with the one from Bastion (Supergiant's previous game), are must-buys.Finally, if all of that isn't enough to convince you, the game has Logan Cunningham. And you can never go wrong there."
