,Recommended,237930,29165432,Posted: 10 January,all,Karina,"I've never heard of the Supergiant Games studio before, nor about any of their games, so a recommendation I've heard from my friend about Transistor was completely new to me. Not knowing anything at all about the game, buying it on its next sale was a bit of a risk, but one I'm very glad I made. Admittedly, I didn't think much of this little gem at first - played it for a few hours, got bored, and left it for many months - but revisiting and completing it again recently made me love it, and compelled me to write this review.Great things:- Beautiful art style. Very colourful, detailed and full of light, that never gets obnoxious at any point. It creates a strangely warm, inviting atmosphere to the world despite the rather grim events going on in the story.- One of the best soundtracks I've heard in a game, I want to find all of those songs to listen to in my own time (any help with that is appreciated).- Lovely protagonist, despite not having a voice Red is nonetheless a fascinating, strong character that gets very well developed over the short course of the game and whom you can really grow to resonate with and root for.- Engaging, well paced, mature storytelling, helped by your sword boyfriend's brilliant narrating skills.- Some unique mechanics - such as the Limiters, which handicap your combat in some way for a nice amount of bonus experience, and every ""Function"", the in game combat skills, having all sorts of active, upgrading and passive effects, allowing for loads of customization in your fights.- Red can hum to the melody of whatever song is currently playing, which is a very minor thing but one I found very amusing and I often idled in the game just doing that.- Luna.Good things:- Combat isn't entirely groundbreaking, but it's fun, the ""functions"" are diverse and great to play with, and has lots of strategy element to it - utilizing the turns as much as possible to create different combos tends to get you a lot farther than just bashing the Process over the heads with one skill over and over. It mixes turn based with fast paced combat and pulls it off, what is very nice to see and work with.- Nicely done character development of most introduced characters, including the main villains and the Camerata, despite the limited actual time dedicated to it.- Achievements aren't hard to get, the backdoor room challenges can get pretty tough when you progress through their stages but all of them are solveable with a bit of focused thinking. It's also great that besides achievements, those challenges give you a good bit of ingame experience, which you can't increase with limiters from what I observed but is very helpful either way. I recommend doing all of them at some point in every playthrough, if not for the boons then at least just to unlock more brilliant songs to idle around with.- Completion of the game's main story allows you to start a recursion playthrough, revisiting all of it with stronger enemies while retaining your level and all your functions, which is great.Cons (everything has some, I guess)- If you're interested in the deeper backstory of the game's main characters, the decryption system that unlocks bits of it is confusing and weird to get used to. You only get access to it by unlocking different combinations of functions, which takes a long time and doesn't feel worth it for ultimately just bits of reading.- Very linear and short. You do get your time to explore Cloudbank and other bits of the world, but your sword boyfriend pushes you through a solid set path that could really do with being longer.- Spoilerish, a more personal bit of input:While the ending was shocking and bittersweet, definitely meaning to provoke feelings, I feel that it could have had a much greater impact if you got to find something out about who your sword boyfriend is and why you should care about him. Unfortunately, no such thing ever happens in the game at all, you don't even get to find out his name, what is in my opinion slightly disappointing - sure, I know he loves Red and deeply cares about her, but who exactly is he? What is his background, what was he doing before he died? Were he and Red in love before the events of the game, or have they fallen for each other after what they've gone through together when he became a sword? It leaves too much unanswered for me.Overall, this game proves that games can be a gorgeous work of art as well as an interactive medium of fun, and I couldn't recommend it more to anyone looking to play through an adventure like no other. I will make sure to give Bastion a go one day and see if I enjoy it as much as this."
