,Recommended,237930,10215243,"Posted: 23 May, 2014",all,Poison,"Another good game from Bastion creators Supergiant. Not without flaws though, and not up to the high bar the group set previously with Bastion. Combat is weighted too heavily on use of Turn() movements, and it is straight up impossible to beat the game in only real time combat, unlike what Supergiant said during events like PAX. The game is far more linear than it should be, with almost no splitting off. Additionally, you are given a lot of customization with how you use your skills, but it will always boil down to what does the most burst damage at the time, since you can only effectively fight in Turn(). As such, it has very little replayability, since there is not going to be any variance in order of area completion or how you play the game, unlike Bastion. Lastly, enemies to far, far too much damage, the other reason open combat outside of Turn() isn't feasible. After the halfway point of game, most enemies will take well over half your HP in one attack or combo, and the AI is exceptionally aggressive and tracks movement during thier shots.Despite all this negatively, the game is still good. Art style is great, story is unusual but interesting, music is solid (though personally find it inferior to Bastion's western styling) and gameplay is mostly enjoyable. It may not be exceptional, but it's still above the average of most AAA releases these days."
76561198032532474,Recommended,237930,11081192,"Posted: 5 July, 2014",all,Robot Panda,"Transistor is a game about a girl and her sword against an all consuming enemy controlled by a shadow group with less than altruistic intentions. At first glance the combat system may seem simple with a Diablo like feel to it, that is until you begin to use the Turn() system making everything much more strategic giving you the ability to freeze time and carefully plan out your next move. While there are no talents or many lateral upgrades to choose from the game does have this intriguing upgrade system where you use one ability to augment another making it so you can tailor your ability set to best match your play style, or to better counter certain enemy types of which there are many. Logan Cunningham (Bastion) narrates the story from the point of view of the Transistor. What’s really nice is that they don’t try to hold your hand throughout the game, spoon feeding you the plot. No, instead the story unravels naturally letting you discover the plot for yourself which I really appreciated. All of this as well as a uniquely beautiful art style and an amazing soundtrack that is becoming a staple of these dev’s, Transistor makes for an excellent sophomore entry from developer Supergiant Games."
