,Recommended,237930,11537261,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Saphyr,"Personal Evaluation: My favorite ""Za Warudo"" power fantasy since F.E.A.R., SUPERHOT, and SSBB.The Objective: This third-person game is a mix of real-time and turn-based tactical action using a move selection and modification system that allows for many different play styles.  Functions, which can function as moves, mods, or passive buffs to the player, are aqcuired in the first story run and by leveling.  Applying these requires ""memory"", which you can also eventually expand by leveling.  Functions vary in utility from mobility to buffs and debuffs to damaging attacks and have various tactical effects depending on how they are applied.Executing moves outside of Turn(), the time-stopped mode where enemies are frozen to allow you to plan out a set of attacks, can be time-consuming in comparison to the Turn()-based execution unless the appropriate mod is applied.  In Turn(), your planning potential is aided by a flexible and calculated system where you can erase your moves to select a different one and see how much damage your actions are expected to incur on the enemy (emphasis on ""expected"", as some enemies can turn or teleport from backstab attempts that amplify damage).Similar to its predecessor, Bastion, the game features isometric elements, a ""sandbox"" where you can enter challenge doors or listen to the game's soundtrack (unlocked by completing challenges), and ""recursive"" gameplay (i.e. a New Game+ mode).  Unlike its predecessor, Transistor employs a death machanic that raises stakes without immediately ending a run.  Losing your entire health bar will disable one of your active functions (and, while not disabling them too, uninstall any mods applied to it), reducing tactical options for the round.  The function is recovered after getting through an additional round of enemies once your current round is resolved, and in the meantime, you are able to equip a new function in place of what was lost.  Losing all functions in a single round, while I have not experienced it, presumably results in necessarily restarting the round.  Retrying a round is also possible from the menu screen upon pressing Esc or your controller equivalent.The Subjective: I enjoy the mix of thinking on my feet to reach my Turn() with minimal health loss and planning out insane combos of moves in time-stop.  While it didn't happen often in the main story, losing functions got me to improvise, engaging me further in strategy and tactical consideration.  It is in the New Game+ Performance challenges that this need to improvise and find ways to reach Turn() without dying is magnified, as you gradually get access to functions and memory from a significant limitation, but losing them results in their complete disappearance; I found this challenge mode in particular to be the most difficult, but also the most informative with regards to how the functions can operate together.While you may desire to stick to some basic combinations, the game's challenge modes will present you with a variety of possible movesets that will work to great effect.  For me, it was a thrill to home in on my own hand-crafted deadly set of fuctions for the really stubborn enemies, but, even if I were to lose all but one of them, I still know several other options that will fit into place once I reach an access point to apply new functions.The story is pretty damn melancholic in its overall scope.  The destruction of the city at the hands of the enemy you encounter is not unlike what you see in Bastion, except that instead of the world having fallen apart, it is being remade to an unfamiliar and uninhabitable form.  The aeshetic of the established society reminds me much of the 1920 in the US, and its collapse, perhaps not coincidentally, seems to me to reflect how that prosperous decade would end... but that's just interpretation.Parting Words: I love being mean."
