,Recommended,237930,16704598,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,thainen,"Bastion was a major case of ""came for gameplay, stayed for aesthetics"". Transistor is more like ""came for aesthetics, stayed for aesthetics"". Gameplay is ok, but does not become tedius only because the game itself is rather short. Planning the turn and combining the effects are interesting mechanics, but have little actual depth and are fun only for the 6-7 hours it takes to beat the game once. Which is kind of perfect.Now, the aesthetics are brilliant. A futuristic sci-fi city where programming code is a part of everyday reality, is painted in the most unlikely style of Art Nouveau, and this unexpected combination provides a unique experience. Like in Bastion, sound is very tightly knit to the visual, to an almost synaesthetic effect.The story has two very different layers. The big picture is vague: to the very end we can only guess what the city actually is, can one leave it or not, what is the nature of the forse destroying it, and so on. This, however, is not sloppy worldbuilding, but rather a deliberate refusal to focus on the minutae of the narrative background and keep it blurred to focus on the story of Red, which is told with all the immediacy. A human story of hard work, love, betrayal, retribution and redemption gets through, from the first cue of the man in sword, to the last pictures in the credits."
