,Recommended,237930,13672759,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,JazzTap,"The art of this game is wonderful. (Characters. Areas. Songs. Story.) I will not elaborate further. I am sure others have.I do have a terminology quibble: a transistor is a switch controlled by voltage. Yes, it is the basic unit of a digital processor. No, you can't stab people with it, much lessstash their soul in it.Nor, taken literally, should you be able to proc stun / charm / slow / vuln / knocked-into-air on them. Gameplay-wise, these are your basic tools. By artfully arranging them - some being cheaper than others, some affecting more enemies at once, some merely being available at the time - into useful combos, a pleasing variety arises.Although the variety of (largely useful) abilities is remarkable, their tradeoffs won't particularly matter (due to some powerful, spammable late-game abilities) unless you up the difficulty. The system for doing so is remarkably flexible - rules of combat can be turned to the enemy's favor, or you can step outside the campaign (which you should be replaying at this point anyways) to pit a semi-fixed loadout against (yet )a(nother) set configuration of enemies.Cloaking enemies (temporarily untargetable) are annoying for how they drag out fights, later on. Others, that boot you out of turn-planning, violate the premise of the game - the few encounters they participate in become mere button-spamming, converting tension to panic. This is the worst quibble I have with the game. (Except maybe for the name of its titular artifact.)In summary: A fascinating post-mortem of a city that deserved to live. (Deserves, even. I'm imagining an art deco / cyberpunk life simulator.It would be a lot of work.) Coupled with the important, RPG-y business of blowing things up in increasingly efficient, then increasingly roundabout ways."
