76561198063224555,Recommended,237930,13837858,"Posted: 4 January, 2015",all,Vinacious G,"This game's sountrack is a melodic warm embrace upon your eardrums and inner soul.I'm on my second playthrough. Before I begin rambling, here's a quick list:1. This game is short, I probably finished my first playthrough in about 10 hours or so.2. Get the soundtrack, you will not regret it.3. This game is stunningly beautiful, and if you liked Bastion at all, you'll love this, possibly even more.4. The gameplay element to this is fascinating. You can, much like in Bastion, configure and reconfigure your protagonist as you please, taking her attacks apart and putting them back together again just like with sexy, exploding Lego's.5. The further you progress through the story the more upgrades and limiters you will choose to unlock.6. Limiters can be brutal (I turned 9 on immediately on my second run-through, thinking I was a boss with the NG+ system (New Game+) - No. I was wrong. I was hilariously wrong.7. I've heard the first ending isn't really the ending. I would not be surprised.8. The pace of the game is very quick, and the only distraction from the story are little rooms you can find to practice different setups and complete challenges. The first ones are easy, but on towards the end of the game the last two stability tests were rather challenging. This game makes you strategize sometimes ;P9. Again, this is one of those games this is more about pleasing your senses. Just let it happen.10. I would suggesting searching on Youtube the following tracks, and listening to them in this order:> Gateless> We All Become Instrumental> The Spine> Vanishing Point Hummed (sounds just like a theme from arguably one of the greatest games of all time and space)> In CirclesSeriously. Grand game. SO glad I got it on sale so I could buy the OST as well for the grand total of $10 and some change. Which I then used a gift card for X3"
