,Recommended,237930,29601669,Posted: 31 January,all,Ness1228,"If you playedBastion,then you should know what you're in for and, as such, can expect the same experience and be happy that you'll get an arguably better one from Transistor. If you haven't played Bastion, then continue reading.Transistor is right up there with Bastion in ""best games I've ever played"" for many of the same reasons as well; I'll start by discussing the gameplay itself. I played through the game using an Xbox360 Afterglow controller, and the controls are very intuitive and remappable in the options menu. Of course, the game can be played without a controller. In terms of difficulty, it's that comfortable difficulty that isn't easy but isn't frustratingly impossible; it's sometimes challenging, but it's nothing an average player shouldn't be able to handle. There are unlockable and completely optional ""limiters"" that make the game harder and give greater rewards from battle as a result. As you progress through the game, you'll unlock several different abilities that can be equipped in various ways, allowing you to find out for yourself which abilities and combat styles you personally prefer; there's no punishment for not using a certain ability, and (outside of the challenge rooms) you have complete freedom as to how you wish to tackle the many battles in the game.If I were to attempt to describe the combat mechanics, it'd be a turn-based real-time hybrid; you can attack in real-time (which is rather difficult, as most attacks have short start-up and ending cooldown animations), or you could take advantage of the Turn() function, which is the game's core combat mechanic. By activating Turn(), you essentially freeze time and are able to move and perform actions; when time is frozen, you don't actuallyperformthe actions until time is unfrozen, in which you then proceed to wreak havoc on the enemies. However, after you use this, there's a set cooldown period where you cannot useanyactions except for running around and evading enemy attacks until you can use Turn() again. It takes a little bit of getting used to and the game provides helpful tips at the top of the screen, as well as the first battle.As for the non-gameplay aspects, the pacing of the story in tandem with the narrative serves to keep the game entertaining and flowing smoothly. The plot develops the more you play, and you can unlock more information about character backstories by using different abilities in combat. The soundtrack is dynamic as it changes depending on the stage of battle. The entire game can be played in one long sitting (4~6 hours), but it auto-saves at each in-game terminal or whenever you enter a new area, so it's fine to play in short intervals if you don't have the time.For the record, I shouldn't even be able to run this game, as I don't meet the minimum requirements; however, turning down the resolution and a few other settings, I was able to play the game with an acceptable framerate with little to no issues. Of course, doing such things isn't good for my processor (pun intended)."
,Recommended,237930,24403986,"Posted: 19 July, 2016",all,Nobita-kun,"Transistor is AWESOME()-Great soundtracks, great battle system, great artworks, and the story really touches to the feelings. An exciting game to play!"
,Recommended,237930,13668479,"Posted: 28 December, 2014",all,Niitsuma Yuri,"Belo jogo, tanto no sistema do mesmo quanto na história.Me deixou focado e pensando no enredo por um bom tempo.A partir de recomeçar a campanha pela segunda vez, percebe-se que o jogo é um pouco curto. Mas valeu a pena ter jogado.Alá Mercado Livre: ""Recomendo""."
,Recommended,237930,11351288,"Posted: 21 July, 2014",all,Cottonbonbon,"Although Transistor has been reviewed and praised countless times before me, it goes without saying that this game is a glistening gem amiss a sea of franchise sequels whose sheen can be compared to that of rust and decay. But in order to really review this game properly, we would have to start off by comparing this game to supergiants first, and only other shining success of 2; Bastion.Like Bastion, Transistor's story begins in tragedy, with your main protagonist Red having to run from a group known only as the Camerata, who as far as you know have just failed to assasinate you. Why, you do not know, but in foolishly doing so have given you a powerful weapon known only as the transistor; A sword, posessed by a voice acting as your only aid that holds the key to stopping a mass outbreak of creatures known as the process, who do nothing but kill and assimilate anything and anyone who is unfortunate enough to step in their path.Overall the story is very, very immersive, and will keep you engaged until it's finale, where my only gripe with this game resides. In comparison to Bastion, Transistors climax is done quite well, but then it just ends in a very somber note with not much rhyme or reason, which in turn makes it a good, but inferior ending to that of it's predecessor. If you are like me who has played Bastion before Transistor, don't be too surprised if Transistors ending feels lackluster in comparison. Despite that though, it's story is still very much worth playing through, if not only once if you are a completionist like me (played 20 hours total, and unlocked all 33 acheivements). If you have not played Bastion before this game, then you will definately get to enjoy the fullness of the games narrative with unbiased eyes, which is probably the best way to play this game.I definately recommend playing this game at least once through, regardless if you have played Bastion before this or not; it is definately worth every minute of your time."
