76561198025027746,Recommended,237930,10598559,"Posted: 20 June, 2014",all,cpiitzer,"Simply put, Transistor is beautiful. The soundtrack composed by Darren Korb buzzes with electric, jazzy energy. The painted artstyle, courtesy of Jen Zee, drenches protagonist Red's world of Cloudbank in a gorgeous Art Nouveau - meets - cyberpunk atmosphere. If you played Supergiant Games's spiritual predecessor Bastion, you'll recognize Rucks's silky-smooth narration as the voice within Red's attendant sword, the titular Transistor. If nothing else, the game has an irreversible sense of style - from the way the Transistor, the titular weapon, trails along the ground, to the novel option to hum in time with the background music. Mute though she may be, Red - and the player - leave their voices imprinted upon the Processed world.Gameplay is innovative, and expands upon the isometric action style that Bastion perfected. The core of Transistor's mechanics are various Functions that represent an in-game concept - breaching, crashing, even calling for help. These translate into active abilities - a damaging linear attack, a single-target disable, and the ability to summon a robotic helper, respectively - as well as traits used to modify functions- the ability to extend range of functions, addition of a disable utility to functions, and modifying the trait to spawn weak allies when an enemy is killed - and passive abilities that can be used to modify yourself, which, for the sake of length, will not be mentioned. Combat is also made more strategic by the Turn() ability, which, when activated, allows the player to go into a pseudo-""planning mode,"" halting battle and allowing the player to input a certain number of Functions and movements. Upon deactivation of the Turn(), Red activates all of the moves near-instantaneously, but is vulnerable and has most Functions disabled until the Turn() meter passively regenerates. Players can choose to either maximize their Turn() potential, packing their moveset with tons of burst and evasion Functions, choose to play it real-time using sustain and distraction Functions, or a mixture of the two.Story is intimately tied to gameplay, as leveling up, using Functions, and empowering the enemy Process with certain upgrades allow for greater fleshing out of the world - a storytelling device that encourages the player to experiment with different approaches to the game. It does, however, mean that the story suffers somewhat in terms of actual content - a speedrunning player will find the plot threads to be confusing and sparse. Once one unravels all the various story threads though, , a greater plot does begin to emerge from the tangled network of Cloudbank's world.If any real criticism can exist for Transistor, it may be that it does not quite live up to Bastion, in terms of sheer narrative clarity. The characters, perhaps, never feel as fully realized as the Kid, Zia, or Zulf (though perhaps the incredible ending sequence will object.) But Transistor is its own subroutine, and to contradict a certain quote, when nothing changes, well - nothing changes."
76561198026977358,Recommended,237930,11917193,"Posted: 29 August, 2014",all,Potato,"Transistor is a game that managed to hold my attention like no other with its interesting setting and mysterious story line. This game has a fantastic soundtrack that complements the gameplay brilliantly, as well as a artistic style like no other. Because of this and the great time i had playing it all i have to say is  BUY this game, its is a MASTERPIECE."
