,Recommended,237930,10184197,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,S+,"I loved Bastion and I love this game even more.The narrative style is different but still present. The sound track is just as excellent as Bastion's if not more so. The art style is different but just as good. Everything you liked about Bastion is there and just as good, but different.Except the combat. The actual combat itself is brilliant and rewarding, with thousands of possible ability permutations and lacking the feeling that any one combination beats out the others. All the abilities are useful, all of them fun, and all of them let you tackle each fight in a variety of interesting ways.Some people have complained about the combat in this game, but their complaints are quite bluntly bewildering to me. While it does get increasingly challenging, and dying can be frustrating, I never had to redo any one fight more than twice, and the game autosaves often.I have not enjoyed a game this much in a very long time. It is exciting to even talk about. This is Game of the Year - or at the very least the Indie Game of the Year.For $20 you get around 9 hours of singleplayer content that is brilliantly designed, written, and narrated.For $10 you get a soundtrack that is around 1 hour, 9 minutes of excellent videogame soundtrack.In my opinion you do yourself a disservice not purchasing this game."
