,Recommended,237930,13791473,"Posted: 2 January, 2015",all,McCrazy,"Where to  begin with Transistor? It is a strikingly beautiful game that goes beyond the conventional bounds of what is typically considered to be standard in the sci-fi game genre. Done in a lush style, Supergiant Games utilizes a vibrant futuristic art-deco style that is as much of a character as the protagonist. Gameplay is similar to that Supergiant's first game, Bastion, with skills naturally being acquired as you level up and allowing you to add limiters to make the game as hard or as easy as you would like. Skills can also be arranged and combined together, allowing for experimentation, as well as unlocking finer details about the world Red, the protagonist, lives in. The story is fantastic and remarkably emotional for a relatively short game. Details are not missed in Transistor, with everything from style to soundtrack being considered and working together to create a truly stunning game."
76561197977294261,Recommended,237930,10922077,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,Bananas Ph.D,"What can I say about this game that already hasn't been said. If you liked Bastion, you'll enjoy this. It's not quite as action RPG oriented as Bastion, but the Turn() system is actually really intuitive and easy to pick up. If you enjoyed the narrator from Bastion, he's back as well - though in a role that's a little different, though I think is much better than his previous one. There's also a little less story and immediate exposition given to you this time, you'll have to play around with the different skills (called Functions()) in different slots in order to get some more background and story. With that being said however, I can understand why people wouldn't like this as much as Bastion - it's definitely a different game, not just Bastion with a reskin. However, I highly recommend it if you want beautiful artwork, a wonderful soundtrack, an interesting (if somewhat sparse) story, and a unique take on action RPGs."
