76561198039585037,Recommended,237930,10307420,"Posted: 31 May, 2014",all,flapitz,"Amazing game.  The art direction is beautiful, both in the graphics and the overall design of the game.  Even the music is amazing (so much so that I spent some time just listening to it in the various areas).  All the small attention to details in this game really shine, and help immerse a world unlike many I've seen.  They walk a line between fantasy and technology that is remarkable.  You will find all sorts of tech lingo sprinkled in - in fact your abilities themselves are called ""functions"" and when you pair them with other functions for augmentation, they call them ""subroutines"".The gameplay is also a lot of fun, and highly addicting.  It's a lot like a dungeon crawler in the way the skills work, but the real shining point is the fact that you can plan out your attack tactically using a time-stopping function called ""turn()"", which allows you to setup your next moves and execute them almost instantaneously.  In addition to this, there is a surprising amount of flexibility in the way you can play.  You have 4 slots main abilities, which can be any function, and each of these main abilities can have 2 augmentation functions (again, which can be any function).  In addition, you also have 2 passive slots which can be set to any function.  Depending on the arangement, you get different effects.  This allows you to play however you like - sniping from long range, getting up close and personal, specializing in area of effect, or even charming baddies or summoning allies.Finally, the game flows seamlessly in and out of ""cutscenes"" and actual gameplay beautifully.  The story is told in small, digestable chunks, rather than long winded cutscenes or forcing you to read countless pages of lore to understand what is going on.  The storytelling doesn't feel forced at all, but instead feels really natural.Overall, this game has me hooked, and I highly recommend it for someone looking for something unique and memorable, as well as entertaining and easy to jump into."
,Recommended,237930,12195417,"Posted: 22 September, 2014",all,Stranger,"Incredible! The combat is really fluent and has several angles to go about a fight. The Soundtrack is to DIE for! I bought it almost immediately of beating the game. The artwork is very nice and stylized. The story telling is nice, very well done. I loved every waking minute of this game, nor did I every get ungodly mad at it. It's a little on the short side but I feel that it has enough strengths to really make you happy for every penny you spent."
76561198079996186,Recommended,237930,11237284,"Posted: 14 July, 2014",all,vanguard_cva,"In a world where Tron meets Fritz Lang's Metropolis, there is a singer who has lost her voice wielding a sword who just found one - the eponymous Transistor. Together they battle a digital menace called The Process in order to...Well, what do they want to achieve actually? See, Transistor provides two challenges for the player: first, fighting The Process and second, actually understanding what is going on. While some people will hate this minimum style story telling, others will embrace it as another challenge to overcome and will find it very compelling.Combat, on the other hand, is much more straightforward, deeply strategic and very rewarding. You gain a number of abilities, each of which may be used by itself as an active attack, as support for another ability or as a passive enhancement to your character. Take Bounce, for example. By itself it is an attack that ricochets off enemies, hitting multiple targets in the process. Add it as support to another ability and now this attack will chain-hit. Assign it as a passive enhancement and it will make enemy attacks bounce off of you. Decisions, decisions...Adding to that is the Turn() sequence, which allows you to pause the game, queue up attacks and actions, and have them executed in bullet-time. Thus, strategy is much more important than good reflexes.Most important about Transistor, however, is that it is art. Not art as in the ""you might lable this as pre-post-retro modernism"" sense. It's art because it's beautiful in every aspect. There is a fundamental aesthetic vision that permeates all elements of the game and strings them together nicely. It just works, and it's gorgeous all the time.That being said, not everything is perfect about Transistor. Gameplay generally feels just a little bit rough. Menus like ability selection are somewhat clunky and Turn() can be hit-or-miss without much explanation. The key mechanic for getting more background info becomes somewhat tedious after novelty wears off, paling significantly in contrast to the Turn() mechanic. Some streamlining might have done wonders, but there are limits for indie companies, of course.Now, Transistor: The Game might have some issues, but Transistor: The Experience is awesome nonetheless. Visuals, soundtrack and voice acting all weave an atmosphere that carries the game over many flaws. What Transistor wants to do, it does really well.Rating: 8/10"
76561198012187180,Recommended,237930,10329228,"Posted: 2 June, 2014",all,IceFang,"I've been gaming for many years, and it's become very difficult to surprise and impress me.  Every once in a while, though, a game comes along that breaks the mold and offers a unique and refreshing experience.  After getting goosebumps during my encounter with the first boss, I knew that Transistor was one of those games.The enchanting music, surreal visuals, and captivating narration create a wonderful atmosphere for the story of Red, a popular singer who combats ""the process"" while wandering the enigmatic city of Cloudbank.  The satisfying gameplay is unlike anything I've ever experienced before:  a delicate yet harmonious balance of tactical planning and real-time combat.  Customizing Red's intricate skillset is particularly engaging and rewarding, and the player is permitted freedom to mix-and-match skills in a way that suits their own personal play style.In an age where video games are a dime a dozen, it can be so hard to spot the gems amidst the rubbish.  A good friend made this recommendation to me... Now I return the favor to you:  Do NOT miss this gem!"
