,Recommended,237930,30865223,Posted: 31 March,all,EpicDingo13,"I really really enjoyed Transistor. The story is pretty good. Transistor throws you into the dystopian and high tech city of Cloudbank. The game is narrated by your sword, the Transistor, and your goal in the game is to hunt down a group called the Camerata who brought the city into chaos. You play as Rad, a singer who's voice was stolen. The gameplay is really unique, and it's fun too. You pause the game to plan out how you attack. After you attack, you run around avoiding enemies in real time until you can plan out your next attack. It's probably best to watch some combat if you don't know what it's like. The game stays fresh with the continual implementation of new gameplay and story elements. You also have a very large variety of ways you can customize Red's combat abilities. The game encourages constantly shifting your combat style by rewarding you with extra story for doing so. This prevents the gameplay from getting repetitive due to using the same ability throughout the entire game. The boss battles (while few) are very fun. The soundtrack is also my favorite of any video game!  It reflects the game really well. It also features a few songs with vocal which are very good as well as fitting (in many games, I find songs with vocals can feel out of place). Transistor's art style is incredibly beautiful as well.This game is really strange. The story, gameplay, music, and art style give this game a strangely unique feel. These elements all compliment each other very well.  This weird atmosphere makes Transistor not only unique, but also amazing. Transistor's strange feel is especially clear when you plan out your turn during combat and the music switches to being hummed. Amazing game; buy it!"
