,Recommended,237930,32989149,Posted: 29 June,all,Villermen,"Transistor is a story-driven RPG with a unique combat style. When in an encounter, you can pause the game and plan your moves (up to a certain cost). The planned moves will be executed afterwards pretty much instantaneously. This enables taking a more strategic approach and setting up satisfying combos. The game features pretty, hand-drawn, graphics.You can gear yourself with functions. Functions can be abilities, passives applied to abilities and global passives. Every function can be combined with other functions to have a different effect, so the combat will stay fun as long as you have the mindset to keep changing your kit.The game is pretty fleshed out and definitely worth your time, but there were a few things that I didn't like about it:The game is linear. You move from encounter to encounter with walking and storytelling in between. I don't think a level progression system is really needed in this game, as you gain levels at a pretty much predefined rate. You can choose to do challenges to boost your level, but these are only available in a predetermined amount in specific places. You can enable limiters to gain levels (perks) earlier but you will gain disadvantageous perks. I personally don't think that this is worth it in the slightest, but it helped increase the game difficulty once I noticed that certain combos were just too strong for the enemies to deal with.The planned combat does not account for movement of the enemy in any way, therefore you miss a lot of attacks that initially show as having registered. This was quite frustrating before I noticed what was going on.And then there is one big issue I had with the plot (spoilers):Red's voice is stolen and put into a sword along with some guy by the Camerata. The Camerata release a virus outbreak that they don't control and will destroy the city. The leader of the Camerata helps Red to fix the problem, and then they fight so she can return to the city or something? (The game doesn't really touch why they have to fight.) Once back in the city, instead of fixing it, Red commits suicide with the sword to also get trapped in there with the guy in the sword she is now in love with.Why does Red go through the hassle of exacting revenge when she's going to kill herself anyway? The game tries hard to give the player a motive to continue: Destroying the Camerata and fixing the city. Only half of those issues is touched in the game, and I feel like the game just ended halfway through plot-wise.I just couldn't get into the plot, which I think is pretty important for RPGs."
