,Recommended,237930,16514893,"Posted: 18 June, 2015",all,tessaroonie,This game ruined my life
,Recommended,237930,12606536,"Posted: 24 October, 2014",all,Zid,"Slick on style, gorgeous in art, mesmerizing in music, Transistor is one of those games you can't help but pause and enjoy the moment. From start to finish, the game feels like a sweet serenade, like spending a romantic night with someone you fancy.Logan Cunningham's voice and dialogue hit the right spot as your companion, feeling neither a grating voice or a throwaway noise, but a comforting ally in keeping you headstrong. Fans of the developer's previous game, Bastion, might be slightly disappointed if they want a similar narrative structure, as the novelty is not presented here. Instead, a more familiar narrative of having a companion by your side is utilized, and honestly makes more sense given the story's direction.Combat is what you would expect from an isometric hack 'n slash, but actions are very nuanced and tend to have weight behind them (Not to mention that the attacks feel heavy). Much like how the star of the show for Bastion is the way it's narrated, the star of the show for Transistor is the tactical queueing system in combat called Turn(). Activating Turn() pauses combat, and lets you plan and queue up actions based on a resource bar, all in a simple yet informative display. Releasing Turn() afterwards will see the combat un-paused but have time slowed down, while you execute your action queue in a sped-up version instead. Once your queue is done, combat goes back to real-time along with you, and you must wait for your Turn() resource bar to refill if you want to use it again. Think the combat of Frozen Synapse meshed with the one from Dragon Age: Origins.This system turns an otherwise standard affair of combat into a deliberate pacing of rewarding attack plans and being pressured in defending yourself while you're waiting for the Turn() mechanic to be available again. Encounters tend to have fast and unforgiving enemies, and every Turn() you activate is a moment to breathe and think. Every detail you peruse in Turn() makes a few seconds in real-time become exponentially scrutinized in a paused setting by 10s of seconds. You can definitely play Transistor without Turn() though, but it's a difficult and rather bland experience (It tends to encourage you to utilize Turn() to experiment all sorts of options). The combat is all that much better and satisfying when you incorporate Turn(), and it has become one of the most fun systems I've ever had the pleasure of experiencing in a long time.Customization comes in with the skills and passives you bring into combat, and Transistor does it in an interesting way that looks simple at first (and it really is accessible), but is fairly deep and encourages experimentation. Every skill is essentially also a component, and thus can be used as upgrades to other skills, or be used as passive buffs instead. For example, Breach() as an active skill is a long-range attack that pierces through targets and obstacles. However, you can slot it into another skill as an upgrade, increasing the second skill's range and velocity. Or you can slot Breach() as a passive buff to yourself, which specifically grants you more resource in Turn(). This form of customization means the build you bring into every encounter is limited by your imagination and by what you need for your playstyle.Combined, the combat and customization make for an amazing experience that only gets better and not repetitive if you're willing to experiment all manners of things, such as specific build combinations and calculating positions. Still, it's worth noting that the encounters are a bit easy and repetitive once you find the best way for yourself to beat each enemy (especially with certain skills and combinations which I won't list here). If you want more difficult and rewarding fights, I recommend turning on some difficulty modifiers (that you can earn through leveling) until you find something just right for you. For me, I especially recommend turning on modifiers that buffs the enemy, rather than debuffing yourself, as I absolutely love the combat when you're at your best. Furthermore, the game has a New Game+ mode, which carries over your progression and your enemy's own progression, while also randomizing each encounters from there on out. Playing through New Game+ with all difficulty modifiers set on enemy buffs is one of the best gaming highs I'd ever had. While this really is a negative to some, it goes to show that Transistor's combat really shines when replaying at New Game+ and with difficulty modifiers on, and that it's a shame to not try otherwise.Transistor clocks in as a short game for its price for some people, and while that's enough to turn people away, the game really is a statement of quality over quantity, and for that alone, I applaud it. As an indie, it's exemplary and a highlight of the industry. As a game, it's a love song to the early and magical days of gaming where I was constantly amazed by actual new experiences, and wow, what an experience Transistor is. As a purchase, I have no regrets for its $20 price, but it's definitely a ""Your Mileage May Vary"" thing. I know quite a few people who just won't buy this game, or who regret doing so.  The $20 for me was for the quality, not quantity, and in that respect, it's very much worth that price. Make no mistake though, this is clearly a work of passion and dedication, something from the heart and from gamers who listen.Supergiant Games still shines past Bastion, and Transistor not only sits alongside Bastion, but probably outdoes it for some people. And I'd be one of them.Oh, and like other reviews have said, hold down Tab whenever you're able to in-game and not in combat. What that does itself sums up the entire game's quality and love in a button. You won't regret it, heheh."
,Recommended,237930,11199816,"Posted: 12 July, 2014",all,Empdee,"10/10 would play again...and I did.The visuals, story, soundtrack and gameplay are superb. So much fun was had, and so many feels were felt. Supergiant games really know how to make a damn fine game. First Bastion, now Transistor. Looking forward to their future projects!"
