76561197977274098,Recommended,237930,15986209,"Posted: 24 May, 2015",all,darien.shields,"Good, but not as good as Bastion.Fun and short, takes about a day or so to beat. Like Bastion, the visuals are gorgeous, if sometimes confusing, there's a nice variety of enemies and abilities giving you plenty of room to explore tactics. I don't think it really approaches the visceral fun of its predecessor; once I completed the game I had no urge to replay it to explore the combat more. The 20s Art Nouveau aesthetic is excellent.Where it falls down is writing and characterization. The plot is tangled up and never fully explained. You can piece together a lot of it if you stop and think, but none of it comes naturally and it breaks the flow quite badly. Even after the game was over I was scratching my head over a lot. This would have been admissable if the characterization was stronger. The narrative asks the player to care about the city the game takes place in, and the people who live in it, despite the fact that you only ever see any of them after they're dead. Logan Cunningham does an excellent job with the voice acting, but his character is simply not as charismatic as Rucks in Bastion, and like everyone else, you know next to nothing about him. This makes it even more difficult to care about him the way the game expects you to.Overall it's definitely not a bad way to spend an afternoon, but if you haven't picked up Bastion I'd play that first."
