76561198009687696,Recommended,237930,33460797,Posted: 11 July,all,Tiga-Claw,Ultimate battle between metrosexual and indie singer for an USB drive.
,Recommended,237930,28460052,"Posted: 18 December, 2016",all,Titiontot,"Transistor is Supergiant Games' second title after the amazing thing that was Bastion. With Transistor, it's certain that they really have a knack for creating unique, inspired, and fun experiences.Transistor is a unique, inspired, and fun experience. It's easily one of the best games I've ever played, but you've heard that a thousand times before.In Transistor you play as Red, a famous singer who as a result of some rather bizarre circumstances, has lost her voice. She picks up the Transistor, which is a cool sword that talks. Now she goes on this quest to figure out what the hell is going on and to get her voice back. The combat is something like a hack and slash combined with a strategy game. Red can have up to four skills to use, which she can attack enemies with in real time. If you push Space, you can enter Turn(). Turn() is a planning mode where time freezes. Here you can plan out Red's attacks ahead of time and then play them back, coordinating actions to clear out an entire room of enemies in one maneuver, using up portions of the Plan() bar for each action. On the downside, once you finish doing Turn(), you are extremely vulnerable and unable to defend yourself (under most circumstances) until the Plan bar refills again. It's a surprisingly unique system that manages to be enjoyable and holds a sizeable amount of depth. There are 10+ different ""Functions"" you can get throughout the game, but they can be used as upgrades, passive effects, or abilities all on their own. The idea of being able to freely mix and match these abilities in nearly infinite combinations makes for a variety of gameplay styles and really brought out the inner mad scientist in me.The story itself, while seemingly very simple to begin with, evolves to become rather complex. The Transistor talks to Red throughout her quest, sometimes about mundane things, sometimes about their situation. It serves a much different purpose than Rucks did in Bastion. Where Rucks was more of a narrator, to give insight on the world and set the mood for the story, the Transistor is more of a companion. By the end of the game, the Transistor felt like as much of a companion to me as it did to Red. You get insight into the world and Red as a character through what it says, and your interactions with it and the things around you are how the story unfolds. The way everything comes together is great and really left me satisfied with it all playing out the way it did. The story is not as straightforward as Bastion, however - to get a good understanding of all the plot elements you have to piece a lot of information together that's being given to you, and even the most subtle bits of dialogue may prove vital to comprehension. It's ultimately a very interesting tale in which I found myself getting pretty damn emotional about. For those who want to learn more, each Function is associated with a certain person in Transistor's universe, and by examining a Function after using it, you can learn more about some of the characters. This isn't integral to the story but it is a lovely and interesting extra for the people who seek it.What should be mentioned is that the presentation is absolutely gorgeous. The UI is dripping with a neat modern tech feel, and the world has a beautiful abstract futuristic-noir aesthetic. It was so nice to see and the colors and effects in combat really popped. The soundtrack is a massive part of the experience aswell - I don't really know my genres, but I do know that it's good. It all adds to the atmosphere, and a particularly amazing touch is that using Turn() causes the song currently playing to be replaced by Red humming the melody.Key Points+ Enjoyable and unique combat system+ Beautiful, atmospheric soundtrack+ Unique world+ Great story@ Story requires close attention and may be hard for some to understandGet If- You liked Bastion- You like games with futuristic worlds- You like adventure games with a narrative focus- You want a different kind of strategy action gameFinal VerdictThe game'll last you about 6-9 hours average I would say, and after that you can do Recursion, which is your standard New Game Plus mode. With an amazing atmosphere, great soundtrack, fun and experimental gameplay, and immersive story, there's little reason I can't recommend Transistor."
