,Recommended,237930,30173321,Posted: 25 February,all,calthaer,"Transistor is probably best described as a ""tactical hack & slash."" That odd combo of descriptors speaks to a set of game mechanics that is unique and, at times, complex. The ""trials"" they present you are especially challenging puzzles, as are boss fights. The game offers a wide array of stylistic capabilities, as well as ""limiters"" - options which you can turn on to enhance the difficulty (and your reward).The story is really nothing to speak of - the flimsiest outline of a plot, loosely carried along by vague, non-specific lines of dialogue uttered by cardboard characters with cool portraits but little personality. Don't get this expecting to find an engaging narrative - the gameplay is the real strength here.I paid this game the ultimate compliment and actually beat it. The game is satisfying, albeit frustrating at times - the ""challenge puzzles"" usually have a trick to figure out. Until you do it can feel like you're beating your head against a brick wall - sometimes unsure whether it's your tactics or your ability to execute that's at fault. That being said, the game is well worth it, especially if you enjoyed Bastion - and, frankly, I would recommend Bastion to anyone who's never played a SuperGiant game before I'd send them to Transistor."
