,Recommended,237930,11145159,"Posted: 8 July, 2014",all,Shovel,"If I made something this good, I could die happy. The sheer quality of everything in here, and I mean everything, is astounding, and it's proved that Supergiant know what they're doing in a big way. Let's look at some things, shall we?Firstly: The narrative and characters. The story is awright, I'm not really going to go into it cause it's worth experiencing it for yourself, but suffice to say I burned through it in two marathon sittings. There's really not an abundance of information tossed at you, but ne'er a word of the what is there is wasted. There's a weight and a reason to just about everything, and the information is meted out just enough for any kind of conjecture to be a huge adventure and great discussion material. The journey is littered with emotional moments, exploratory vignettes, memorable scenes and is paced so that you think you know what's going on most of the time. Transistor shows you this complex, meta world and incites a horrible thirst for more information that just isn't going to come unless you start digging. There's all these technical terms, but they aren't just tossed in, they all have a specific meaning that's not quite what you think. It's all just the right kind of subtle, and I really, really love it for that.The art: Transistor is a looker alright, but screenshots belie just how pretty it is in motion. There's tons of little quirky bits moving around and morphing, and the whole environment just feels so very alive, it's a little unsettling to see it still. There are also some wonderful set pieces featuring lovely art and occasionally some heart-felt voiceover work, and that stuff is excellent too. I would stick in some outstanding design stuff here, but I really can't pick between the enemies, the environments, the characters and the Transistor itself, it's all just fantastic and wondrous to behold. Every step forward is an adventure, you'll never know what you're going to see next.Musically, there's a hum button. A god-damned hum button. What does it do? Hum, duh. You mean gameplay-wise? Nothing! But you might find yourself sitting there holding it, because the music is so charming and great that a couple of seconds of downtime can't hurt and suddenly your finger aches. Seriously, the alternate versions of tracks, the use of music within the narrative, the changing themes during combat, the jukebox? I couldn't put it better myself.Now that's the arty stuff out of the way. A game can read, look and sound great and still play like a dead fish. Transistor? Ha! Not in the slightest, there's so much going on under the hood here. Each power is unlocked and has three potential uses, depending on where you slot it. Active uses that power, Upgrade adds it's effects to another power in an Active slot, and Passive confers other bonuses. The real meat is when you start unlocking multiple slots and more powers, cause each one is like a new, neat Lego brick to add to your arsenal in a dozen different ways. It encourages experimentation by giving you all these neat tools, but then if you flub a combat encounter and lose all your health, your most expensive power will be rendered Overloaded, and will be unslottable for another while in-game. This FORCES you to improvise and think on your feet, especially in the later stages where things start to get tough. Finishing a combat encounter with a power in one of the three flavours of slots will unlock one paragraph of backstory/biography about a person in the world. In other words, if you wanna know more about anything, you've gotta use all your powers in all ways in at least one fight. All this is so perfect and neatly done, mechanic-wise, I can't even convey how much I think it's great, it's just so right.Now, the thing that ties it all together. The cohesion between all of the above just amplifies all the good aspects in some sort of quality feedback loop that makes everything a zillion times better. The music being at the right point in combat or over a beautiful environment. All those words with real meanings that aren't qiute right, and figuring out what they mean here. Reading between the lines in all the information you find, piecing together a view of this world. The moment when you press hum at the exact right time, and a chill runs down your spine. The first time you use an old power in a new way and suddenly you have a new favourite. The instant you realise things weren't quite as you thought, and the music swells and someone says something portentious and suddenly you're right there, in this world, hoping against hope that you can change things. It all just combines like some sort of megazord into one of the best games. (That's it, there's not going to be a qualifier, just one of the best.)+Art is beautifulMusic is wonderfulMechanics are masterfulThe world is thoughtfulIt's great, buy it.-A little short, but sweet as hellYou'll have to dig for informationShe WHAT. Oh.Transistor is a worthy successor to the Supergiant name, after Bastion I wondered, ""Could they do it again?"" but they knocked any doubts I had right out of the park. To be honest, personally I'm not all that enthused by the isometric adventure-y way they put things, but Transistor is a work of art, it's a fantastic game with a excellent background and production values so high I can't even see them, and damned if I'm not gonna give it the praise it deserves."
