76561198065726595,Recommended,237930,33750367,Posted: 23 July,all,"Damn You, Murphy","Man, this game.Seeing as Supergiant's third game, Pyre, will be released a couple of days after this review, I thought it might be a good time to review Supergiant's other games as well. Transistor is the second game made by this studio, released in 2014, and after playing it on and off for a couple of years, it remains one of the games closest to my heart for a multitude of reasons.Transistor takes place in the fictional utopia of Cloudbank, which recently has had a string of incidents leading up to the spread of a robotic ""plague"" called The Process. You play as Red, a singer whose voice has been stolen literally and metaphorically by this upper ""secret society"" called the Camerata. You go around the city of cloudbank, attempting to end the spread of the Process and bring justice to the group of people who made it. This story is the best I have ever played through. It made me laugh, worry, and even cry. The story is fantastically written and got me attached to the characters. Even if you feel like you can’t get enough of the regular story, each ability has a little bit of lore tied to it that you can unlock by using the abilities differently.The gameplay itself is innovative and immersive (while feeling maybe a bit repetitive at times – as will be explained later). You wield a sword-type object called the Transistor. The Transistor can download the consciousness of deceased people to upgrade itself and create new abilities for the user. The primary combat mechanic is that of interchangeable and stackable abilities that can be combined in hundreds of ways as offensive or defensive. This allows for heavy replayability, trying new combinations of abilities to do different things. Similarly to supergiant’s previous game, Bastion, there are ways to make the game more difficult to add to replayability- these challenges are called limiters and, for example, make enemies stronger, limit your abilities, and the like. The game can play two ways interchangeably- a turn-based strategy game, or a real time ability-based brawler using this time-stopping mechanic called Turn(). The two seamlessly combine in and out of each other, feeling balanced, and still difficult.The art direction of this game is stunning. Similar to Bastion, the handdrawn visuals are beautiful and cinematic. They immerse the player in the world and make it feel alive. The menus all feel like they belong there, which is a level of detail that many games neglect. What Initially drew me to this game, however, was the superb soundtrack composed by Darren Korb-who also worked on Bastion's soundtrack. I found it on Supergiant's Bandcamp page after listening to Bastion's soundtrack there. The developers at Supergiant know that this is one of the strengths of their game, and added a button in this game that just allows Red to sit there and hum along with the soundtrack. That in itself is fantastic. The vocals of Red by Ashely Barrett breathe a new life into this game that I've rarely seen in other games. The voice acting in this game is rich and compelling, from the members of the Camerata, to the Transistor itself.As previously mentioned, there is some feeling of repetition. I mostly experienced this while replaying the game, but I also experienced this feeling in some of the combat parts of my initial playthrough. The problem of potential lack of replayability appears to have been recognized by Supergiant, however, and the team has created new challenges that some players would just run past like I did initially. The story overall is on the shorter side time-wise (as compared to triple a games), but the game definitely makes up for it with beautiful story- and worldcrafting. The final boss is innovative as well, but feels a bit clunky due to some mechanics choices.He has the same ""Turn"" ability as the player, which allows him to stop time and escape a meticulously planned move or clutch attack by the player. This ended up being frustrating for me, but it honestly didn’t detract much from the whole, seeing as it is an incredibly innovative mechanic for a boss to have- and I love to see small studios trying new things.Transistor definitely a game worth the price. It is a game close to my heart due to the attachment it builds in the player. As Supergiant's second game, it made a leap forward in production value, and I hope this trend will continue with Pyre. I wholeheartedly recommend this game to anyone and everyone- it has something to offer in all fields.As a side note, the soundtrack (which is stupendous) is available to listen to online at their Bandcamp page:https://supergiantgames.bandcamp.com/album/transistor-original-soundtrack.But I recommend that if you want to support the developers, you should purchase it on Steam or buy one of the hard copies at their website. They have it in vinyl, CD, or digital.https://store.supergiantgames.com/collections/transistor-merchandise."
76561198065530746,Recommended,237930,20373790,"Posted: 7 January, 2016",all,Snorty Saiga,"Super Giant Games had improved themselves after Bastion and created this outstanding piece of art. The artwork is stunningly beautiful, everything is flourished with colours. Moreover, they've changed the artstyle for the characters: from chibi-ish Bastion into a more realistic style. The soundtrack music blends perfectly with the game, it gives that futuristic cyberpunk atmosphere. Even in the song 'Sandbox', you can still here bleeps of machine, indicating it's some sort of an artificial environment.Super Giant Games is consistently giving the function to raise the difficulty level (Limiters) and also a wide range of play style just like Bastion.  The game is more of a tactical approach, but it also gives the option to go hack 'n slash/ beat'em up mode. The game is also more punishing by destroying a random Function everytime your health is depleted. Although the destroyed Function is recoverable, it might be a crucial one during that encounter.The storyline is a bit vague. Even if you listen closely to everyone, there are still questions remain. However, each of the side characters have been given surprisingly detailed  back stories, although they are not directly linked with the main storyline.Overall, this game is very much enjoyable: audibly, visually, and gameplay-wise. The only downside I had was the challenges and bosses, which I felt  are not as difficult as Bastion's."
