,Recommended,237930,23812631,"Posted: 25 June, 2016",all,mellopillow,"soundtrack is sexy, like me!"
,Recommended,237930,13891120,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,UpInFlames,"Red pulls the sword out of the man’s body. The sword talks to her, but she doesn’t speak back. She lost her voice and he lost his body. It was an eventful night. The sword is obviously too big for her, she drags it around, but somehow manages to muster the strength she needs to wield it in battle. The city of Cloudbank is being destroyed by a cybernetic virus called the Process, let loose by a shadowy organization named the Camerata. Red, a famous club singer, is a target of a failed assassination. Other prominent Cloudbank citizens have become unfortunate targets as well. But why? Transistor manages to deliver an interesting premise that takes place in a sci-fi world that fuses programming languages with a dystopian alternate reality to create something wonderfully unique.Narrative exposition is actually pretty light, most of the storytelling comes from Transistor, the titular sword who comments on everything that is going on. Terminals scattered across the city provide updates on the latest news. You can also learn additional information about the various characters by unlocking new weapons and limiters. Along with the beautiful visuals and great soundtrack, the storytelling paints a striking picture of the intriguing setting. However, it doesn’t really do much with it. Aside from the enemies and the dead bodies you stumble upon along the way, the city is barren. There is no interaction with anyone until almost the very end. Despite all the strong production values and wonderful artistry, Cloudbank still somehow manages to feel a bit empty and distant.The vast majority of time is spent in combat. You may confuse it with a turn-based combat system at first, but it’s really a real-time system. You can fight the Process’ minions in real-time without interruptions, but that may prove difficult. So the game offers you to use a “turn” which is in fact just a slightly more elaborate pause. During this turn, you can plan your moves including movement, abilities and weapon strikes. Once you’re satisfied, the game will then play out your orders. After that, all your abilities are on cooldown for a set amount of time during which you have to avoid enemy attacks by either taking cover or running around positioning yourself for your next “turn”. It takes a while to get into the groove of things, but once you get used to it, you’ll find it a very enjoyable and flexible system.What makes the combat really interesting is how you can use each of your functions (abilities and attacks) on a primary, secondary or passive slot. Each function provides different abilities or powers depending on which slot it occupies. This system enables plenty of combat experimentation sometimes leading to unexpected results. The game will also sometimes force you to experiment and swap out functions because losing chunks of life points leads to a function overload rendering it unusable for a while. My problem with the combat system isn’t really down to the combat itself, but rather the fact that the game doesn’t provide any options to tailor it to your preferences. For example, having the option to automatically initiate a turn on enemy sight and/or end of cooldown would have been really helpful instead of having to constantly keep track of the cooldown bar as you’re trying to dodge incoming attacks. Also, displaying your current function setup on icon mouse-over would have helped to be aware of your powers. Considering that you swap them out so much, it’s easy to forget what you’re using as you can only inspect your functions in detail at checkpoints.I walked away from Transistor with a feeling that a bit more could have been done regarding the design, gameplay and storytelling, but despite that, I found it to be a highly enjoyable and thoroughly unique action game with stellar presentation and an engaging emphasis on player experimentation.Highlights: Art direction, soundtrack, combat experimentationDownsides: Lack of options8 OUT OF 10 (GREAT)"
