76561197969417125,Recommended,237930,10484971,"Posted: 15 June, 2014",all,G00N3R,"I expect this review will be a little controversial, and I'll probably get lots of thumbs down, but in my opinion Transistor is kind of average. Not terrible, but not deserving of all the hype.The combat is fun. Plenty of freedom and variety. Along the way you unlock lots of different powers, each one has three different uses - either as a primary attack, a buff for a different primary attack, or a passive buff for your character. You can choose to combine these powers in whatever way suits your playing style and can adjust the combinations at checkpoints.In the later stages of the game I had a long range attack with a damage buff that also charmed the target to fight for me for a few seconds (allowing me some breathing space while the other enemies attacked the charmed one). I also had a cloak that would hide me from enemies, which also triggered an explosion in a radius around me, and then gave my next attack after de-cloak a further damage bonus. Meanwhile I was passively regenerating health, although I wasn't getting hit much anyway thanks to those other 2 combinations.There is some nice enemy variety as well, some are able to heal or shield others, cloak themselves, abilities that influence your own tactics in terms of which enemy to target first. The difficulty is also flexible because of the ""limiters"" system. These are unlocked through level up and either make enemies stronger or yourself weaker when equipped, and then grant bonus XP.But the story really dragged the game down for me. I have to admit, I don't really understand much of what happened. It throws you straight into the action without any setup and most dialogue feels like people talking in riddles. Lots of words without actually explaining anything. I guess there's a sword that can absorb dead people's souls (how? no idea) and some bad guys that are erasing the world (how? why? no clue). I kinda lost interest after a while. As much as I enjoy killing things, my favourite games are those that give context to my actions, give me a reason to care about why those things need killing, or why the world needs saving. Transistor completely failed in this respect. (Although, its indie, so I guess I'm just not intelligent enough to understand the deeper meaning or whatever).Overall ... well, everybody else in the gaming industry seems to think the game is super amazing, so I guess my recommendation wouldn't be worth much. I regret buying it for full price, but I would say pick it up on a 50% off sale if you like tactical combat."
