,Recommended,237930,15187177,"Posted: 3 April, 2015",all,Dominator Bob,"Story: 5/5The storytelling to Transistor is told through the interactions between Red, the mute singer protagonist, and her weapon possessed by her lover as well as various messages on computers you find throughout the 5-hour campaign. Plenty of blanks are left for you to fill, and the ending, although a bit confusing, is extremely open to interpretation.Visual: 5/5The game looks like a painting that is gradually losing its colors. At the beginning everything is colorful and brushed with bright colors but as the game progresses colors become darker and by the end there is almost no bright color. This beautiful take on artstyle really adds to the mood of the story and its themes. The city of Cloudbank is a beautiful piece of art that you will want to learn about and explore.Sound: 5/5The soundtrack for this game is amazing, especially the songs with lyrics. Every song felt perfectly attached to the mood of what was going on in the story at the time of whatever exploring or fighting being done at the time. The voice acting is brilliant, especially the voice of Red's lover. Sound effects for your attacks and enemy attacks fit perfectly.Gameplay: 4/5The combat system takes a while to get used to due to a lack of handholding, but after the learning curve it's one-of-a-kind. Abilities are obtained that can be used to experiment with various combinations of equipping some abilities to others or using them as passive effects. At death instead of returning to the last check point immediately an ability is lost until 2 checkpoints later and health is restored to max, forcing you to use the abilities you have left in new innovative ways. Time can be slowed down to make strategic decisions on what abilities to use. Limiters can be used to add challenge to the game while allowing you to level up faster.Replayability: N/AWill edit after I replay the game on its ""new game plus"" that allows replay with past unlocked abilities.Verdict:Transistor is an experience I have never had with any other game I have ever played. You will grow to care about the main characters, Cloudbank, and its inhabitants. The presentation value is extremely high with beautiful visuals, amazing sound design, and fantastic storytelling. The gameplay has a learning curve and can take getting used to, but once it clicks it's extremely addicting. Transistor is proof that video games can be art. If Transistor is on sale, you owe it to yourself to buy it."
76561198008758654,Recommended,237930,14642372,"Posted: 24 February, 2015",all,BtBedway,"That was fun - Short and very sweet.  Like Bastion?  You must try Transistor.  Unique Combat, Great Narrative, with an Ending to match.  Enjoy!"
76561198004565666,Recommended,237930,17359233,"Posted: 2 August, 2015",all,brickey.8,"If you are looking for Bastion 2, this is not it. Sorry. A lot of the design decisions are similar, but the combat system could not be more different, it's much more linear (you can't advance without killing all enemies, can't backtrack, and the number of fights you can skip are countable using fingers), and the wonderful narrator character has been replaced by one that's merely passable.That said, the game is pretty good if you're willing to accept it for what it is: Its own game.* The combat system has good depth (even if some abilities are woefully over/underpowered compared to the rest, and important hints are only displayed once in a way that you can easily miss them).* The story is ok (though you're left to fill in a lot of blanks on your own). It borrows a lot of cues from Bastion on presentation.* It has an equivalent of Bastion's Gods that lets you scale up the difficulty to whatever level you want at any save point (in fact I like this game's selection better than Bastion's, since it doesn't favor some weapons over others the same way).* New Game + keeps the difficulty scaling and your leveling going from the same point it was at the end of the game (good thing since the story is shorter), as if there were no interruption.* The way the lore unlocking is implemented encourages you to try out every ability in all three possible slots, which is a plus in my opinion.* It is pretty and has good music.Combat is a mix of real-time and turn-based, with the time between your ""turns"" scaling with how much you did during the last turn (though attacking without going into turn mode is a valid strategy and a few abilities are always available). It veers wildly between frantic, fun, methodical, tedious and everywhere inbetween, depending on the enemies and your skill loadout; but usually hovers near ""frantic and fun"". Instead of Bastion's variety of balanced weapons, you mix an match abilities an upgrades. Some are blatantly better than others but there's certainly no ""one good build""."
