,Recommended,237930,12687365,"Posted: 29 October, 2014",all,Dahaka,"It’s hard to play Transistor without comparing it to Bastion if you’ve had the pleasure of playing Supergiant’s first game.  Supergiant definitely has a look and feel that permeates through both games.  This is reflected in the art, music and the story which pulls you in slowly and encourages you to play multiple times to explore the depths of the characters and the world around you.The gameplay is quite different, however.  While Bastion was a fast paced brawler, Transistor explores turn based combat with an emphasis on experimenting with different playstyles.  It took me quite a bit longer to really get into the gameplay, but once I did I had a blast swapping abilities and looking for interesting combos.  Common to both games is a system that allows you to choose your own difficulty dynamically in the game by equipping items that adjust the power levels of your enemies and offer additional rewards.I ended up playing through the game twice without switching to another game in-between, and would highly recommend it to any of my friends."
