,Recommended,237930,11121571,"Posted: 7 July, 2014",all,С Г エ χ,"Transistor is a 2D isometric adventure game done by the same creators of bastion. Like bastion, the game looks beautiful, has a good soundtrack, and similiar to bastion, you're accompanied by a narrator/partner of sorts.  Unlike bastion, the combat is a bit different. Your character is slow, and doesn't really posses a guard, instead you can use evasive skills or initate turn(), which pauses the game and lets you queue up a certain number of actions.  It's an interesting mechanic and the way the game is set up lets you customize your abilites very well and inutitively. However, combat at later levels starts to get boring, you're either stunlocking the enemies or just hiding for your turn() to recharge, it's not at all the fast pased quick acting combat in Bastion.  I don't want to spoil anything, but the final boss is awful, it's like they shoved in a jrpg boss into an action game, you can't do anything about attacks, it's all about dealing damage quicker than it can.Wasn't a fan of the ending either, but that's a more personal thing."
,Recommended,237930,15325113,"Posted: 12 April, 2015",all,GooseAttack,"Possibly the best game I've ever played. Everything is perfectly designed and executed; the passion the creators have for every aspect of their craft shows throughout. I didn't think it would have been possible for them to have done better than Bastion (and some of the reviews I've seen don't rate it as highly) but in my eyes it's far superior, and I rate Bastion extremely highly.Two of the things I wasn't a big fan of in Bastion have been fixed in Transistor. Firstly, the narrator: he was great, but I'm not a big fan of voiceovers as a way of revealing the plot. In Transistor the commentary is provided by a companion, albeit a rather unconventional one.Second, the combat. In Bastion I found that once I got a weapon combination I really liked, I stuck with it and neglected the others, and fighting seemed to be a bit hack-and-slash. You can still play this way if you so wish, but the combat system has been expanded in the most incredible way to encourage you to try other things. Attacks can now be combined and stacked, and the effects of each combination are radically different and fantastically awesome. The sheer variety of possible attacks is mind-boggling, and they're all badass -- none is definitively 'the best'. There's also a very clever 'attack planning' mechanic available, which looks a bit like turn-based combat but really isn't. The combat system is quite unlike anything I've seen anywhere else, and I loved it.The art, music and story are so good it's impossible to do them justice in a review. The plot is revealed gently and subtly, and there are moments where a certain realisation dawned on me that required me to sit back and take a few minutes to process it.I didn't just enjoy playing Transistor; I feel genuinely privalged to have done so. This is a short, beautiful game that amply repays the time and cost."
