76561197980347122,Recommended,237930,21778766,"Posted: 11 March, 2016",all,Dungeon Man,"Awsome game, 10/10"
,Recommended,237930,21769250,"Posted: 11 March, 2016",all,MHLoppy,"A good chunk of Transistor owners will already have played through Bastion - if you liked that, chances are good you'll like this. I'll be talking from the perspective of somebody who played through Bastion as a whole twice, and finished my first Transistor run a good 5 minutes before writing this. Transistor plays quite similarly on the whole, imo. Game mechanics have an overall similar feel, but some elements have been evolved. Discounting the story, it's about as much of a sequel to Bastion as Mass Effect 2 was a sequel to Mass Effect 1.Weapon choices and strategy are dialled up, with a large mix of both active and passive slots (compared to 2 active + 1 special) - and any single weapon can be put into either slot, with differing effects. Weapons can also be layered on top of another in a slot, with another different effect depending on which weapon is on the bottom and what you put over it.Although real time movement and combat are still available, you need to make use of what is basically a ~5s time-freeze button on a ~10s cooldown against all but the most trivial enemies. This particular element is almost like a very toned down version of Frozen Synapse's turn based combat. You press the button, plan out your ~5s worth of moves carefully, press the button again and watch yourself execute those commands while everything around you moves in ultra-slowmo. After the commands are finished, everything goes back to normal and your beepity boopity magic time fridge goes on cooldown. The extra twist is that while this is on cooldown, you lose the ability to use pretty much all weapons, meaning you have to make good use of combat bonuses like backstab (hit from behind for extra damage on some weapons), combo (use your basic melee and then something else for a fixed ""combo"" damage bonus), as well as actual weapon combos (such as damage amplifying abilities before your hard hitters).Overall, I found this mechanic made the combat a superior experience, although my satisfaction did not actually increase compared to Bastion when completing combat. Successfully fighting off superior foes while outnumbered wasn't exhilerating - it was expected. Even after trialling loadouts to find the best ones and then pulling off the ""correct"" ordering for these rarely resulted in more than a ""cool, I can continue with the story now"" feeling. It never felt like a grind, it just wasn't as enjoyable to me as the mechanic suggested it might be. I am technically a competitive PvP player in LoL though, so my PvE opinion is probably a little harsh.New weapon stategies and fancy new magic fridge mechanic - anything else I should know related to combat? As a matter of fact, yes. The third major combat change is actually the dying mechanic. Instead of having regular extra chances on death, your weapons double as lives. If you ""die"" you lose your most valuable weapon for the remainder of this fight and the fight after, but regain all of your health. This makes combat very forgiving, and most of the highest value weapons are not your basic damage sources in combat, so finishing a fight never funnels into ""oh crap I have nothing but utility weapons"" unless you do really, really poorly in a fight (at which point it'll be faster to reload the fight anyway).Optional auto-targetting for weapons was removed, although with the magic fridge mechanic I didn't miss it at all. I actually thought combat in Transistor was far less frustrating in its ""bad"" moments. Some of Bastion's later fights were a little unpleasant, and some weapons did not work intuitively with the commando roll (which was also removed in Transistor, RIP) but I virtually never got frustrated with combat in Transistor.Graphics, audio, and story depth are about par compared to Bastion. There's ironically even fewer characters that you meaningfully care about, although there are quite a few extras that have a minimal, passing importance.Bastion's skill test areas told backstories for characters, and weapon drops were only forced to be used very briefly, with no ill-effect of any kind for swapping back to your old standbys. Transistor forces you to play around with every single unlock in every single slot to get all of that same backstory. I understand the decision for doing so (most people would be missing out on fun/good weapon combinations without it), but it wasn't my preference to have to knowingly choose a worse weapon combination if I wanted to read more backstory.There's a few other minor annoying details, but nothing I can't look past - certainly nothing that made me outright stop playing.One of my favorite parts of Transistor (at least over Bastion) is actually the ability to easily save progress and/or swap loadout. There are access points to do so after every fight or two, making it easy to take breaks as you progress through the game.It's basically another Bastion, but with a game's worth of experience for Supergiant Games to take on board, and I enjoyed it about as much as I did Bastion. And that amount is quite a lot.Second playthrough update: unlike Bastion, Transistor's combat actually continues to change over the course of the second run as new unlocks become available. Combos with close to full unlocks are more satisfying to pull off against tougher enemies as well."
,Recommended,237930,25314922,"Posted: 2 September, 2016",all,Sasaene,"I played this game after playing and loving Bastion. While I enjoyed Transistor, I found it paled in comparison to Bastion in terms of my immersion in the game. The turn-based aspect of the combat scenes was interesting, but I think overall it slowed the pace of the game too much, breaking some of the appeal for me. Bastion was fast-paced and fun, and time flew when I was playing it. But I found myself only able to play Transistor for about an hour without getting sick of it--it ended up being a bit of a labor to finish the story.The artwork was beautiful, the music was great too, and the story was interesting and creative. I enjoyed the cutscenes and reading about the corresponding character for each function. However, I did not really enjoy the actual combat scenes. Overall, I would recommend this game tentatively, but if you are choosing between Transistor and Bastion--pick Bastion."
