,Recommended,237930,28485883,"Posted: 20 December, 2016",all,p0isonedpanda,"Supergiant Games were on my radar ever since I picked up Bastion in 2011 and played the ever living crap out of it. Everything from the music to the gameplay really stood out to me in Bastion and I felt like it really fell on the right side of pretentious throughout. So when Transistor was released in 2014 I got really excited since not only was this another Supergiant Games release, but it also had the legend Darren Korb behind the soundtrack again. Unfortunately, back then I was super broke and had no way of getting Transistor so I only got to pick it up recently since now I'm slightly less broke. To quickly summarise my thoughts on this game, I feel like it doesn't live up to the legacy of Bastion and overall is nowhere near as good as Bastion. This said though, Transistor is a completely different game to Bastion and for the rest of this review I'll try to treat it as such, but I will be referencing Bastion in places where I deem it to be appropriate. ON TO THE REVIEW!SOUND - 8/10Let's just get this out of the way so we can talk about the harder stuff: Darren Korb is a ♥♥♥♥ing genius. He may not be the best music artist ever, but he does his job of making music for games really well. There's tons of memorable songs and all the songs with lyrics to them are catchy and fun. I'd argue this OST is better than Bastion's in some ways since I can listen to it while chilling and not feel offput by it. The narration was fine in this game, but not nearly as good as Bastion's which always felt super dynamic which made the game feel that much more alive. Overall, very good job in the sound department, as to be expected.VISUALS - 7/10In both Bastion and Transistor we had handpainted isometric scenes, both of which looked absolutely stunning. However, Bastion fell short with the characters since they were 3D models rather than sprites. It's easy to see why they did this, however it always felt a bit jarring to see these obviously 3D models on a very flat 2D backdrop. Transistor improves upon this a lot and while you can still tell that the characters are 3D models, it's far less noticeable and fits in quite nicely. However, I prefer the visuals of Bastion much more since they didn't feel as bland as Transistor's. Yes, I get that Transistor is meant to be set in what is essentially a post apocalyptic future, but everywhere I went felt quite samey. Overall, good job on the visuals but the environments could have been a bit better.STORY - 4/10This is where the♥♥♥♥♥♥really hits the fan for me personally since the story never really got me. If it's any indication of how the story stuck with me, I had to look up the story for the game on the Transistor Wiki before writing this review to refresh my memory. Now don't get me wrong, the story is actually good once you understand it, but that's the issue here: you have to understand it. Now, if you're like me you'll probably play the game in short bursts over the course of a few weeks, mainly due to the gameplay which I'll get to later. The issue with this is that you will probably lose track of some of the subtleties that are important to get the full impact of the story. It also doesn't help that this game is cryptic as ♥♥♥♥, making sure to never fully reveal what it's trying to convey. This is okay for the most part, but as you reach the later parts of the game it starts to get annoying. The worst part is that this game is really going for a dramatic and gripping story but it seems to fall short because of this cryptic delivery method.GAMEPLAY - 5/10The core mechanic in this game is quite interesting and novel, but that's also it's biggest problem. The fact that it's novel means it gets pretty tiresome pretty quickly. Now, for those who don't know the core mechanic in Transistor is the turn based combat mixed with real time combat. When you go through your first few battles, it's cool. When you get more abilities to mess around with, it's cool. But very soon you'll find a combo that's OP and you'll just spam that over and over until you win. At this point, you get pretty bored and if you too lost interest in the story, you lose a lot of drive to complete the game. The game will occasionaly throw curveballs at you, but they can be dealt with easily using your method with minor tweaks. It's worth noting that there is this system called ""limiters"" which make the game harder at the benefit of more XP gain from fights, but these feel like a cheap way of increasing difficulty with no real curve to it which makes it hard to really pick them up unless you're MLG pro or something like that.OVERALL - 6/10This is a good game, but I feel like it could have been so much better. The art as always is great, but the gameplay and story made it hard for me to just sit down and play it. I recommend this game to anyone who likes a good soundtrack in their game and likes reading into lore (since there is a♥♥♥♥♥♥ton of lore to read if you so wish). If you've come from Bastion expecting it to be Bastion, then you'll probably be disappointed like I was. Don't get me wrong, I still enjoyed this game, but I just feel so much more could have been done to make this game better."
