76561197977314644,Recommended,237930,13704750,"Posted: 29 December, 2014",all,Puppet #7,"SuperGiant games is one of the few studios that’s letting me hold onto believing I can honestly still expect to enjoy a video game as an adult (30+)Its obvious they're a group of developers who are both unique and inspired at the work they do- they have an actual ""voice"" and use their games as the media to share it with an audience. Both Bastion and Transistor while having entirely separate settings and characters, have a familiar thread visibly running thru one another- and its good.------------The most common complaint I see with both titles is the length of the game, as each even with the intended double play-thru can be completed entirely under 15-20hrs. With Bastion it felt short, however now playing thru Transistor- I think I see the formula: SuperGiant's games are more than just button mashers, they have a story- something to see unfold and listen to (literally) If they can say everytihng they need to say in 7 hours then that’s the length of the game-Respect your audience with concise quality- not hollow filler.At the end of Transistor- yeah, I wanted more, but not in the ""I feel ripped off sense"" it’s the ""I wanna see what these guys create next."" Don't forget its also surrounded by beautiful visuals, rock solid mechanics and some of the best voice overs in the business.Spoiler free Core review:I beat the game first run, no deaths, no retry's, so vanilla playthru without limiters in play is fairly straight forward- however enemies are deadly accurate at all stages and some later in the game have auto hit from stealth which is hard to deal with if you're not watching closely. The mechanic of losing abilities (temporary) instead of lives was a nice change from the usual system- it forces you to alter your playstyle on the fly and creates some really tense moments when your down to only one or two functions in your hotbar that don’t really synergize.If I had to list a Con, the Function screen is initially a bit obscure as to what skills are equipped or not and where, once you see that their borders change  and their descriptive text changes color to reflect where they are installed its actually an elegant system once you get used to it, but it took me a an hour or so to notice it.Other than that its minor things like if you rebind your primary four hotbar skills it doesn’t update the UI graphically to show the new keys- it’s just blank dots, again nit picking.So yeah, I can’t recommend this Studio's product enough- I actually feel bad for buying the game on sale, as soon as i drop this review I'm buying the soundtrack just to throw a couple more bucks their way in redemption :PSo SuperGiant if you see this- you've made a follower outta me my request: Your short stories and rock solid delivery hooked me, now give me a full novel to bite into."
