76561198052983021,Recommended,237930,14997886,"Posted: 21 March, 2015",all,jvgocavs_2000,"Transistor is a different take on the action RPG set in an alternate reality with a heavy influence of computer programing.  The world which you explore is one giant programed city that is on the fritz and you play as Red, a singer who lost her speech and is rapidly losing her world.  As you try to fight against the forces at work you unlock many interesting abilities that are at their best when you are ""programing"" your turn.  These ""programing"" sessions allow you to plan out your moves ahead of time and then watch them be carried out to the dismay of your opponents.  It’s a fresh take on the action RPG formula, and with plenty of abilities to unlock, mix and match and power up it stays fresh till the end.The visuals are solid and the music appropriate.  I did not find either the Narrator or Story to be nearly as interesting or impactful as that of Bastion, the spiritual predecessor of Transistor.  I mostly played thru the game to enjoy the combat hoping for a meaningful end to the story to make it all worthwhile, but the ending did not satisfy.  Overall a refreshingly different take on action RPG combat is offset by the week story and characters, still a worthwhile play, but a critically overrated one."
