,Recommended,237930,15895883,"Posted: 18 May, 2015",all,One Among Nothing,"Though ""perfect"" is subjective and ultimately unobtainable as a standard,Transistoris very close to reaching that standard.It is a game which, from the very beginning, provides just enough guidance without overwhelming with too much information. Controlling the game is simple and the unique mix of real-time action RPG and turn-based tactical RPG is very satisfying to master. The story is not told directly -- rather, it is presented over time by voice-over as you play, through subtle interactions between characters, and through clues in the world. No long-winded tutorials are necessary to get started, with a very simple introduction getting the player up and running in less than five minutes.There are some minor complaints I could raise, such as the lack of much exploration (the game is quite linear) or optional content (what optional missions are available are interesting but fairly simple). With the design being as solid as it is, however, I struggle to name how these weak points could be improved without weakening other points.Overall, I highly recommend this game. It's a perfect example of what can be done with design focused on the player's enjoyment, not on creating a spectacle. There are many options available for varying styles of play, there is easily-adjusted difficulty which should challenge even the most extreme of players, there is replay value with a very difficult New Game+ option, and most of all, the story is absolutely amazing.I could go on, but this is simply a game which must be experienced, not described."
