76561198025148070,Recommended,237930,10213351,"Posted: 23 May, 2014",all,EclipsedHusky,"So I have been playing Transistor lately...just ya know ten hours for just the first play through.Have to say this game is gaming PERFECTION!!!Combat is a mix between real time and turn base. You can use any skill you have equipped whilst in real time, but you can also press a button to trigger TURN. Doing this STOPS time, allows you to set up a turn so to speak.While in TURN you have a bar, each action you do takes some of this bar away. Things like walking, buffs, debuffs etc etc.  Best part of this system was how free you are to play with TURNs. You can use up 99% of the bar and still use something that would take more than what of the bar is left. Making for some majorly epic TURNs.On top of combat you have a story driven so deeply I seriously teared up at some parts. The world and environment is such a beautiful mix. Imagine TRON, and SecondLife somewhat mixed together. The Users are still themselves, but whilst in this world they consist as a program. This leads to some very, very interesting scifi, and imagination when it comes to the actual world in its self.Narration is done so powerfully at times I was at a lost of what to even say to myself! The main character Red, actually loses her voice in the actions that lead to the start of the story, so the entire thing is all narrated by your weapon the Transistor. This does not mean you have a silent heroine though. Throughout the world you can use monitors, most of these ask you really simple things like what weather you like. Some of these allow Red to talk to the Transistor. So look out for these they add so much depth with so little dialog it...gah I just I feel I need NEW words just to describe how much I love this game.It was also made by the same people that made Bastion. So it includes a lot of the ideas that Bastion held. Things like game changers that make it harder, this allows the player to make the gamer harder or just keep it normal without ever asking ""easy, normal, or hard?"" Which I feel is a prefect way to add difficulty to a game since again it is all up to the player, on top of making the game feel like it has changed in more ways that just ""enemy does more damage on higher difficulty!""If you put these things that make the game harder you get more EXP from fights by a set %. Which is cool because the EXP is based on a percentage system. Unlike other RPGs this game just says you are 0% through 100% to a level up so you actually level up at a great pace.Leveling up is also a perfect thing in this game! Almost EVERY level up offers YOU the CHOICE of what YOU want. When you start off the lower stuff will be like getting a new skill which can bounce off baddies, or maybe you want the thing that allows you to turn a baddy into an ally for a bit? Up to YOU!Music is beautiful. I won't even try to go into this, will say this though. It has emotion! Also if you hold down one of the buttons Red will hum, offering you extra sounds to the song currently playing which pretty much doubles the songs in a way!After your first big boss, you get a place that lets you do challenges. Some are a bit puzzle based where you have to kill all the baddies in one TURN. Others pit you against enemies with a pre-set skill selection making you have to figure out the uses effectively to win! They don't add a TON to the game, but they do offer extra EXP! :DLast thing I will say, the game has difficulty. By no means did I win without a few deaths, but even in DEATH they made this game so perfect. Instead of dying and having to start all over from your last save spot, you actually LOSE one of your skills, get full health back, and get to keep fighting. You then can get the skills back by going to a save spot. BEWARE I never allowed myself to lose a skill...I always retried, which in my opinion was more fun. Mainly due to the fact when I did retry I got to go back into the fight with a whole new set up and try new things!"
