76561198049349578,Recommended,237930,15877203,"Posted: 17 May, 2015",all,Borrell_IV,"Supergiant Games left the stakes really high after his first game, Bastion. It had an amazing combat system, lovely art style, and a compelling story.Transistor is something that is rarely seen these days, an experiment of sorts, with a challenging combat, beautiful artstyle, and a story that strains to be compelling, but slows the experience in some occasions. We take the role of Red, a red-headed singer who, after a concert, finds her friend stabbed by a huge sword in a back alley. After this event, Red loses her voice, takes the sword and seeks retribution while the city she lives in experiments some supernatural phenomena. Since our protagonist is mute, it is up to the soul of her friend, now living in the sword Transistor, to narrate  the story. My analysis will cover the major points of the game, with some plot spoilers in the end.The first thing that glimpses the eye in Transistor is the amazing art style. From the dress Red is wearing to the architecture, the menus and the HUD, everything looks gorgeous. It's important to remark this because the ambient makes a great games memorable. Every enemy is distinguishable and attractive, and it goes the same for every ability Red acquires. There's no question here, if it was for its art, Transistor would be a 10/10.The combat is the most surprising thing, and maybe one of the biggest obstacles if you are a close-minded player. In Transistor every ability has three ""status"". Active, which means that it can be used in combat; modifier, which alters or improves abilities; and passive, which gives the character some utility in combat. This abilities are selected in a MOBA sort of HUD, assigned to the buttons 1,2,3,4. At the beginning there's only the possibility to have active abilities, but through the game you can unlock slots to have modifiers and passives. In this slots we can combine the different abilities Red acquires when leveling up or through some events, and it's the meat of the game. Combining two or more abilities has different outcomes, and thus the combat becomes fully customizable.In combat, you can freely use these abilities or activate the ()turn option, which stops time and allows the player to plan different moves and combine abilities to eliminate the enemies. But be wary! If Red dies, she will temporarily lose one of the abilities, which sometimes can mean a death sentence. The game estimulates the player to experiment with the abilities by unlockable lore, which tells more about the story of the city and its inhabitants. It worked for me, sometimes finding myself using wacky combinations just to unlock everything, but I ended up with a set of favourite abilities.SPOILER ALERTThe plot is maybe the toughest part of the game, and I mean it. I had to stop playing because Transistor wouldn't stop talking, and eventually I got bored of listening. Even if the story between Red and Transistor is very interesting, and the trials and background is compelling, I felt that there was a depressing tune to it. I felt bad that, for once that we have an interesting female protagonist, she only hums. And that's the only downturn to the game. The interesting set of side characters only appear eventually, and I would have loved to know more about them, because the universe is very well constructed, but I can only catch a glimpse of what they could have been."
