,Recommended,237930,26255322,"Posted: 27 October, 2016",all,ahardgamesnight,"Wow. That ending. It's like I got stabbed in the heart. I was NOT expecting that at all. This game really messed with my head for a good two days because the ending left me so conflicted. Never have I felt so happy and sad for a video game character at the same time. Wow.....just........snap, that was such a good game.As for a REVIEW, I was really impressed by Transistor's mechanics, story, art (!!!) and music (!!!). Especially the last three. When I play a single-player game, I want a game that will give me a great, well-thought-out tale that keeps me interested through the whole experience. There was just enough details in this game to keep me running around with my killer thumb drive that had the souls of my enemies (and random strangers) installed into it, yet enough ambiguity to keep me curious.I love the simple RPG-like mechanics of being able to update the Transistor with the digital souls of my enemies, and even make the game intentionally harder for more XP. The ability to pause time and pull a 2250 version of Sherlock's ""mind planning"" thing was also awesome, and I found the creative side of me piqued as I installed bloatware into the processes that dared to subscribe me to a service I had no interest in. Chucking processes into the recycle bin of a USB has never been so fun!Oh my goodness, and the aesthetics, both visually and aurally; that just blew me away. Usually when I screenshot a game, it's because I'm like, ""Hey, I did a thing!"" and think that someday a human being will come into my life that will actually care about the image I captured. Not this game. No, I found myself taking plenty of screenshots because they would make great wallpapers for my computer. It's just so gorgeous, and the speakeasy techno-jazz music unexpectedly just adds to the mood like no other. Maybe it's because of this game I like ""Say U Wont"" by Brasstracks so much, because Darren Korb proved to me that Jazz and Electronic can get married and all sorts of wonderful kids running around the house like ""Old Friends"", ""Stained Glass"" and ""Coasting"". They're nowhere near as redneck as their cousins from the Bastion, such as ""A Proper Story"" or ""In Case of Trouble"", but they are still part of the same family where good ol' Darren somehow finds a way to make Electronic work with pretty much any music style.So yeah, if you like going hog-wild on freaky, white programs with a massive thumb-drive that just so happens to have your boyfriend's soul in its motherboard to the sound of surprisingly satisfying electro-jazz, then this is your game."
