,Not Recommended,237930,17017075,"Posted: 12 July, 2015",all,14123,"Let’s start with the story. Much like in Bastion, exposition is the name of the game. You play as a silent protagonist in an empty, broken and breaking world, trying to figure out what caused all this via narration, various news terminals scattered across the city of Cloudbank, and the function details. Much like in Bastion, of the defining features is the unique narration element, with the dude trapped inside the transistor sword-thing that you carry around compensating for the protagonist's silence. Unfortunately, unlike Bastion, the narrator is boring as♥♥♥♥♥♥ and the exposition feels half-baked at best. None of Cloudbank seems captivating or remotely interesting and even if it is, you'll never be hearing it from sword guy, as most of their cheesy lines alternate between professing his love for Red for the umpteenth time, and his hatred and distraught towards the process, the Camarada, and the destruction of Cloudbank. Unlike Rucks (the narrator in Bastion), sword dude never fleshes out the world in any meaningful manner, just namedrop after namedrop of locations that never tie into the story. The most fleshing out that any location ever got in Transistor was the pizza place, with a grand total of two mentions on separate occasions, now I know that they sell flatbread. Woo. Nevertheless, while you may disagree with my saying that the narrator's lines are boring, I'll provide an objective critique: the narration is less reactive than Bastion's, and not reactive enough to be engaging.Three-fourths into the story, you enter a room filled with enemies mulling about, upon attacking one, they all swarm you and sword dude suggests you make a quick escape. I had other plans in mind, and proceeded to wipe out all of the enemies, hoping for an interesting remark, and what happened when I cleared out all of the enemies? Nada. Zilch. Sword dude was busy thinking about the flatbread. To make matters worse, sword dude then says 'See ya, ladies' as I walk out. THERE ARE NO LADIES; I KILLED THEM ALL. This lack of reactive narration is prevalent throughout the entire experience. One of my favorited aspects of Bastion was the abundance of lines in the game and all of the minor details that the narrator would comment on, as though they were actually a real person, narrating my game in real time. In Transistor, I felt as though sword dude was just reading out generic exclamations from a script. 'Whoa, here we go, let's do this, look at that, that was rough,' seriously? Are we sure you aren't the new announcer for Forza?I think that this all stems from the fact that Cloudbank isn't an interesting setting in the first place and is both visually and thematically homogenous. The art-style, although very polished, in no way exotic, striking or unique. None of the areas were memorable, and this feeling of 'sameness' was only strengthened by the lack of any sort of world map that was present in Bastion. I have no idea how far away Fairview is from Highrise, because I can't travel there directly due to the game's linearity; I don't know how large the areas are, because I can't explore them completely them as individual areas, the areasfeelvery small,l because you spend less than half an hour walking through each one, and honestly, they all look the same. Even the isometric perspective that worked very well for Bastion feels cluttered in Transistor, full of very abstract buildings and objects that make for a rather jumbled landscape that all add to the unpleasant labyrinthine quality almost all of the areas have.  Cloudbank lacks culture of any kind, and where I was fascinated by both the Ura and the Caelondian in Bastion, all of their traditions, their way of life, their attitudes, none of the banal information given to you about Cloudbank is connected to anything else, it's just 'this is a pizza place, this a pool, this a storage facility.' Not once did the town ever feel magical, or sci-fi-esque, it was just a bland setting and a bustling town sans the bustle.The story itself is rather terrible. For starter's it's much less interesting and engaging than Bastion's, due to the fact that you spend 90% of the game clueless as to what's going on, and are then bombarded with information in the last twenty or so minutes of the game. Even then, the story is extremely convoluted and poorly put together, there are numerous glaring holes in the story and many things go either unexplained and are really poorly strung together. Bastion had several minute details that were left up to the fans to decide, but notintegral parts of the storyline, how did the Process originally begin? Who was it created by? Who created the Transistor? Some moments feel like a very far stretch, including the fact that a one-in-a-million chance Transistor corruption caused Red's voice to be stolen. Seriously? Although sword dude never stops reminding you that the Camarata took your voice, the game never really explains how, as though embarrassed by its half♥♥♥♥♥♥♥attempt at justification for Red's silence. Bastion did this much better by just never bringing it up and the narrator speaking for Zia and Zulf via indirect dialogue. For all we know, the Kid may well be able to speak, he just doesn't want to, but in Transistor, sword dude just wouldn't shut up about Red shutting up. Only after reading through the Steam Story Guide did I gainsomeunderstanding of the story. Writers, if your readers need a strategy guide to understand your narrative, you’ve done something wrong.Combat alternates between the enemies being frozen still and providing no challenge at all as you wail on them, and the inverse, where you helplessly walk around the combat zone with no shield, dodge, or retaliation method waiting for your 'freeze time' button to recharge. Two words: not fun.Transistor's combat system isn't sure as to whether it wants to be action-y or strategy turned-based-y. It fails to do both and ends up being repetitive and frustrating. The only challenge/threat during combat is trying not to die while you helplessly walk around the map and wait for your time-freeze to recharge. Trying to use the abilities in real-time is frustrating due to the long animations, the inability to chain attacks into combos, and the clunky aiming, essentially forcing you into usage of Turn().Then there are the bugs. Despite the fact that I finished this game almost a year after its initial release, there are STILL numerous visual glitches with the Turn() system that can force you to restart and combat encounter if you've got all the limiters turned on. Even without the glitches, I found that the Turn() tell-tales were often entirely wrong and generally useless. Attacks would be blocked when they were supposed to hit, or hit when they were supposedly blocked, trajectories on the haircuts and Load() mines were always off, seeing how much damage an AOE ability would do to every unit affected isn't possible and trying to effectively calculate damage to enemies with any chaining / splitting abilities was far beyond the Transistor's capabilities.TL;DR:This whole game just feels like a big step backwards for Supergiant Games. So many things they did well in Bastion they kept, but made worse in Transistor, and all of the 'innovations' feel half♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ I could forgive the terrible story if the mechanics were solid, and I could forgive the terrible mechanics if the story was interesting, but unfortunately, both are poor. The worst part is that the game has so much squandered potential, there could have been puzzles, there could have been more challenges, the skills could have been more interesting but none of this was realised and we're left with a disappointing and boring game.3/10.*You can enable these skills later on, but they're not very effective and cost memory that could better spent on increasing your offensive capabilities),"
