,Not Recommended,237930,33113293,Posted: 1 July,all,"""CRAZY"" Gaston","This seems kind of odd for me to do, but I actually can't recommend this title.Full disclosure: I bought the sountrack on vinyl, not just because I'm a filthy hipster, but because Darren Korb is a great composer. I also love the aesthetics of the game, and the UI is pretty well polished.The problem I have with this game is pretty central... the gameplay. The difficulty of the first playthrough is just pathetic, there's no challenge whatsoever. The difficulty ramps up in subsequent playthroughs, but nothing else changes... and even then, even with all limiters enabled, the challenge is pretty meh. The mechanics are also pretty meh, the only saving grace being the ability to combine different functions. The side-challenges are a bit tricky at first, but then they also fall fast into the MEH category of difficulty.And it's a rather short game, too. There's no new content in subsequent playthroughs, and the story feels incomplete (and what is there is unsatisfying and depressing). There's a pretty irritating trend in a number of games, like Oblivion, that throw the player into their universe without any explanation whatsoever. There is addtional ""lore"" information available, but it's a complete and utter red herring. You'll learn a lot about characters, most of whom you'll never meet, and their circumstances in a universe you don't understand. In other words, it's pointless to read the lore if there's no explanation.That having been said, I loved to play this game. If I saw someone playing it I'd probably grab the keyboard from them, and would play it just because I wanted to be *seen* playing it, not because I enjoy it. It's so cool. Yes, everything -- the music, the visuals, the characters -- are beautifully layered together in a way you don't see in most games... but games should be about gameplay.tl;dr style < substance"
