,Recommended,237930,14739092,"Posted: 4 March, 2015",all,eXcruciate,"Has a pretty cool combat system. Some of the best art style and design I have ever seen in a game. It is way too short, 6 hours or less, and it feels much shorter than that. Another bad thing is that it really has no replay value at all because it is incredibly linear and even though the enemies are tougher on the second playthrough, you still have to play with certain skills so you can do enough dmg and not get yourself muffed up. I've beaten it before on a friend's computer and just recently bought it on sale to add to my own collection and play through again. The entire game looks breathtaking. It has some of the most innovative gameplay I have ever seen as well. The combat functions around planned attacks in a pause menu that are executed when unpaused and you wait on it to recharge, so planning carefully later in the game is a must so you can mitigate the dmg in between attacks. What is cool too is that the penalty for death in battle is that each time you die a skill is removed, letting you continue but handicapping you somewhat for the remainder of the battle. After the battle, the skill is still unusable until you clear a couple of checkpoints, which is a great idea that promotes skill over continuous checkpoint reloading. What makes the gameplay so unique are the skills and their combinations. Any skills can be combined to make some very entertaining and well thought out attacks. The music is very fitting and very well done and the sound is great. If anything, this feels more like a triple A game than most triple A games in the past five to ten years. PC gaming has been in the sh-tter for years, but thankfully there are people out there like this that understand what a real game should be.8/10 but only catch it on sale because of its short length."
