,Recommended,237930,20383709,"Posted: 7 January, 2016",all,Ezah,"Transistor, to me, is one of those frustrating games where it does some things just amazingly well, but the rest of the game just doesn't go very well.Transistor doesn't really fit into any real genre molds. It plays from an isometric view and is an action game (akin to Bastion in a way), but you have the ability to freeze time using Turn() and plan out a series of moves, after which you will be unable to use most abilities until your Turn() becomes available again. There are access points periodically (read: after every fight, sometimes 2 after every fight) where you can choose your loadout, which is based on what functions you have available. You get to use up to 20 different functions, which can be assigned to either active abilities (abilities you actually use in combat), passive abilities (passively grant you bonuses, some of which must meet certain criteria), and enhancements/upgrades (buff a specific active ability to have extra effects). There are some really great combos that can be achieved, but you have to manage your abilities with your available memory, meaning you can't just dump all of your best available skills into your loadout and leave the smaller ones out to dry. There is a good deal of tactics involved.Another good point about the game is the enemy design. They gradually scale up throughout the course of the game in terms of what abilities they have. Early on it's easy enough to dispose of them, but when an enemy is able to cloak itself, and another is able to block out most of the screen during a turn, it can be quite frustrating to finish off the opposition before they knock out one of your abilities. Many of them also compliment each other in such a way that you have to be extremely tactical in how you maneuver so that you can eliminate a certain target while getting out of harm's way long enough for your next turn to come around.Now, for the bad stuff. My personal pet peeve was in how the loadout menus were managed. You would think that you could just bring up the loadout with all of the slots and just mix and match until your memory is full, but no. You are given your list of functions, and you get to assign each one individually. You want to put Breach() as an active ability? Better go find the correct function that is taking up the slot you want it to go in! Oh, you deleted the wrong one? Oops, lets go click on... Oh, you double clicked and accidentally put the wrong ability in that slot. And now you deleted the correct one, only to find out that it has one open enhancement slot when you want Breach() to have 2 enhancement slots. Time to go delete everything and just start from scratch. Yes, it was that tedious.The voice acting was just incredibly frustrating. I really liked Red (the protagonist), but she had her voice taken away right before the game started, meaning she doesn't talk. She can still hum (she's a professional singer), which is quite good, but that's it. The guy stuck in the Transistor that serves as the narrator has a lot of short quips that don't provide anything, and listening to the final boss talk for about 20 minutes until you reach him is as exciting as drinking battery acid.As for neutral stuff, the story is about a futuristic city where people can be digitized into this Transistor, and this group of people tries to take control and make their ideal world, and then they goof up and their army just obliterates everything because they accidentally threw away their only ability to control them. It's kind of interesting from a programmer standpoint, but it's not that interesting to me, especially from such a limited perspective (the only outside input you get are short quips from scattered terminals).The game includes limiters, which make certain aspects of the game harder, such as doubling enemy damage, making enemies spawn double cells when they die, shielding those cells, etc. They make gameplay more interesting, as you can essentially toggle the difficulty settings during the course of the game, with the reward being a small increase in experience.Overall, I would still recommend Transistor from a pure gameplay perspective. The tactics required in this game are very fun and even more rewarding; however, everything else just detracts from the wonderful gameplay. It's visually quite impressive, but that should never come into the equation when weighing whether a game is good or bad.I would give this game a 6/10. It pains me to be forced between a yes/no option, but I will ultimately say that it is worth playing if acquired during a steam sale."
