76561198116356628,Recommended,237930,32684728,Posted: 23 June,all,nihilist74,"I bought this game for 2.99$. At this price, i am not disappointed. The artwork of the game is worth this much. I was expecting a game that was more like bastion. This game is kind of a cross between turn based rpg and real time combat rpg. It is kind of interesting to preplan your movement and attacks. This is a good cyber punk sci fi kind of rpg game. I would have been mad if i paid more money for it.  It appears to be a well made game though. I think this game grows on you the longer you play it. If you were expecting more of a hack n slash game like bastion, this is game is not quite that."
,Recommended,237930,15067522,"Posted: 26 March, 2015",all,Sniper Joe,"I had a lot of problems with this game, but overall I think the positives outweigh the negatives.The primary positive for me in both Supergiant games is the sound direction, especially the music. Darren Korb is fast on his way to becoming one of my favorite composers and Ashley Barrett's vocals are amazing. The sound effects also stick out as appropriately digital, given the game's motif. Normally I would lead with sound direction and music as positives only if the rest of the game isn't up to snuff, but that isn't the case here: I just think that the auditory portions of this game are SO fantastic as to deserve top billing even among the other positives. Voice acting gets an additional nod, and while I don't think the ""narrator"" of this game reaches the grand standard set by Logan Cunningham (from Bastion) he does a great job nonetheless.Graphically the game is gorgeous, and there are several different types of setpieces that break up the isometric perspective you see in most screenshots. I suppose it's more correct to say that the first 3/4 or so of the game is gorgeous; due to storyline reasons almost the entire last quarter of the game is nothing but white cityscape, and while it fits with both the story and the tone it doesn't change the fact that it loses a lot of the visual appeal of the earlier sections. A sea of grayscale isn't particularly visually engaging, but on the plus side Red sticks out that much more in the blankness.Although the creators said during production that the gameplay isn't Bastion 2.0 (which would have been fine by me; I adored Bastion), fans of Bastion will notice one similar element: the ""choose a deity to make the game harder"" element of Bastion is matched in Transistor by the Limiter system, which functions almost identically. You are allowed to choose several limits for your character (less Memory, which is spent on moves, or more Cells to pick up after battle, etc.) which increase the experience gain for each combat session. Even taking every Limiter the game gave me, however, I was unable to reach max level on the first playthrough; you'll have to go through the game at least twice for those achievements, it seems.Combat, however, is very different. At max level you'll have 4 move slots, 2 upgrade slots per move, and 4 passive slots. Functions go in all of these slots and have different effects based on where they're placed (the function Ping can be a low-damage spam move, or when used as an upgrade for another function it reduces the cost for that function during Turn(), or as a passive it increases the amount of distance Red can travel while in Turn()). There are no weapons (the Transistor is your one and only weapon), merely Functions that you can slot as you will to create the exact moveset and passive benefits to fit your combat style. Do you want to be a summoner who can charm enemies? Use Help() and slot it with Switch() and you can now summon a robo-dog whose bark turns other enemies to your side. Want to be sneaky and backstabby? Use Jaunt() to teleport behind enemies and surprise them with a Breach() to the♥♥♥♥♥ boosted for backstab damage with a Mask() helper function. Or maybe you want to use Void() slotted with Spark() to doubly weaken enemies before hitting them with Crash() slotted with BOTH Switch() and Purge() to stun them, charm them, AND put a DoT on them all in the same move. And that's just a small taste of all the options you're presented with. Transistor does a great job of giving you building blocks and allowing you to make your own fun.While Bastion had a lot of reliance on timed hits and judgement of distance, the gameplay of Transistor is defined by its Turn() system. Using Turn() you plan out a set of moves for Red to perform, and when you end Turn() she performs all of those moves in hyper speed (not instantaneously, which is very important to note; she moves much faster but it still takes her time to perform all of the inputs). More powerful Functions require more of your planning time; when you run out of planning time, you can input no more commands. You can rewind your commands and see if a different set will give you the outcome you're looking for, however; your Turn() isn't set in stone until you actually end it. However, using Turn() means that you can't use ANY of your functions afterward until all of that planning is regenerated. Do you use up all your planning time at once for a big combo attack knowing that afterwards you'll be entirely helpless for a few seconds, or do you sacrifice on damage and utility during Turn() to use up less planning time so that your period of helpelessness is as short as possible?While you CAN play Transistor without using the Turn() system and simply manually inputting commands in real-time, I feel the combat is built around the system to such a degree that realistically it's a necessity. And that's one of my sore points with the game; due to the Turn() system the combat functions like some weird combination of RTS and action, but it blends them in such a way that the deficiencies in both systems are readily apparent. If you use Turn() the only thing you can do afterwards (unless you use a particular helper function) is run around like a chicken with its head cut off, but the game throws so many enemies at you in most combats that playing Transistor like a straight action game WITHOUT Turn() is an exercise in futility since you'll just be overrun. It certainly doesn't help matters that almost every single enemy in the game is faster than Red, ensuring that even with a head start provided by Turn() they'll be sure to catch up while she's recovering.As a programmer myself I got quite a bit of enjoyment out of the programming references in just about every facet of the game. The story is intentionally vague and cloudy in the beginning, which I found a bit annoying, but the game slowly fills you in as you go along and I eventually came to realize that it worked better by keeping you in the dark for so long. One interesting thing to note about the story is that, to get the most out of it, you'll have to keep mixing up your loadout; you can only get the backstory on all of the characters by using their related functions in each slot. Even if you find a very powerful Function combination, if you want that extra plot information you'll have to pass it up for at least a little while so you can use those Functions elsewhere. There are only 4 really important characters throughout the story (and only 3 of those are voiced) but there are plenty of background characters with interesting backstories that do relate to the ongoing plot.For a quick story synopsis: you play as Red, a singer without a voice, wielding the titular Transistor, a talking dual-combination sword and memory chip, fighting against both the mysterious Camerata, an Illuminatiesque organization, and their destructive Process, whose sole goal seems to be the utter destruction of your city. Getting too much more into it would rob you of finding out the information for yourself. I did find myself losing interest in the story after about the halfway point (the game's relatively short length does it favors here, I think), but the ending makes up for it.tl;dr Though I have some issues with how the combat plays out due to its odd mixture of RTS and action elements, they're relatively minor in the grand scheme of things and overall the gameplay is good. Music and voice are amazing just like in Bastion, and just like in Bastion they absolutely steal the show here. Graphics are good and art direction is (mostly) interesting. The plot becomes less interesting the more you learn about it (it starts off great and mysterious, but completely lost my interest about 3/5 of the way through) but pulled through in the end. Overall, I definitely recommend it."
