,Recommended,237930,10827937,"Posted: 26 June, 2014",all,Daddy,"I want to start by saying that if you are a hardcore fan of Bastion (Like me), then I absolutely recommend playing Transistor. However if you have never played Bastion, or for whatever reason didn't like it, then this is NOT the game for you.I expected a lot from this game, being from the same maker from Bastion, and for the most part I wasn't let down. The one problem with this game is the combat, which almost ruins this game entirely.Combat is completely based on abilities you use. You gain various abilities as you progress, but there are no basic attacks. Meaning the combat revolves around these abilities or ""Functions"" as the game calls them. With the new combat system known as ""Turn"" players can stop time and maneuver the around the fight planning what moves to make. I would relate it to V.A.T.S in the Fallout games, but much more in depth. Each move comsumes a part of your ""Turn bar"". When the bar is empty you can no longer make a move. In theory this is a great idea for a game and I was all for it in the beginning. The problem with Turn however is that a function like this should be up to the players choice in games, but with the amount of damage enemies do and the time it takes for you to cast a single ability, it is almost impossible to finish a fight sequence without relying completely on it. Now one would think you could solve this problem by just turning down the diffuculty. Unfortunately you the difficulty is set, and cannot be changed. To make matters worse once you have used turn it goes on cooldown (based on how much of the turn bar you consumed), making all of your ability unusable until turn is usable again. There is an ability in the game that can be used during turn's cooldown, and it can be applied to other abilities as well, but once again with the long cast animations and the amount of damage enemies do, it is much wiser to simply run away and wait for Turn to come off cooldown. This makes the game have very little veriety since you have to rely completely on a single function. Turn should be giving the player a viable option to change the flow of combat and not completely dictate it.However the ONLY problem I have with Transistor is the combat. The rest of the game is absolutely fantastic. The soundtrack is absolutely beautiful, the visuals are just stunning, the story is a little hard to follow but is interesting nonetheless, and the narration is even better than before. All of these combined are enough for me to look past the problems with the combat and continue playing.I was expecting a game that would rival Bastion. What i got was a game that can never hope to come near Bastion's level. In the end it didnt meet expectations, but is still an acceptable game."
