76561198057548220,Recommended,237930,12319051,"Posted: 1 October, 2014",all,Zatanna,"Transitor starts you off with a mystery that immediately piques your curiosity. You play as Red, a singer who has somehow lost her voice at the same time she came into position of the Transistor, a dimensional sword that serves as the weapon to combat the Process, who are the baddies of the game. The plot unfolds throughout the game via flashbacks and dynamic narration, on par with its predecessor, Bastion. As you progress, the mysteries surrounding Red, the Camerata, the Process and even the Transistor are explained to you and what you end up with is a very rich, detailed background to a fictional world that unfolds into a deep and involving plot.But Transistor's main gravitas isn't its intricate plot or mysterious characters. It's main selling point comes from its fantastic gameplay. Combat in the game can be played in real-time but it's main focus comes from the tactical planning. You can simply pause the action and plan out your moves. Doing so however, will require a specific portion of a limited meter and different skills will eat up different amounts. I won't go into details regarding the abilities but know that each one can work in a symbiosis with another and various combos can result from it, allowing for a stylishly devastating blow to your enemies.The use of this battle system is extremely well done and, if I dare say, even surpasses that of AAA titles. Even outside of combat though, the player can simply interact with the environment, digging up background info on the world and characters or simply just enjoying a stroll in the environment.The art style is very stylish and the music glues everything together. If people thought Bastion was beautiful, they would be very impressed by this too. I don't usually re-play games but I made an exception for this because it wasn't just a game, it was an experience. To enjoy beautiful art and great music alongside tight combat and a colourful plot, Transistor is definitely one game you should never pass up on."
