,Recommended,237930,10248422,"Posted: 26 May, 2014",all,pH,"I'll start by saying that this is a decent game and I'd recommend it, but while I enjoyed it, I still prefer Bastion.To be fair though, Bastion was definitely a hard game to follow up on, and in some respect,Transistor manages to improve, but in other aspects, it doesn't manage to beat Bastion.Bastion to me was worth more than twice it's price of 15$, whereas this, I think 20$ is quite on mark.One thing Transistor definitely surpasses Bastion, and almost any other game out there, is visuals and aesthetics.It's an absolutely gorgeous game with detailed and original artwork. Every scene in this game is worth staring at for hours.The music in general was music, but it didn't have any track that truly stood out like the 2-3 main tracks in Bastion.There also seemed to be less music centric scenes in the game, which were one of the strongest points in Bastion.The scene where you first meet Zia/Zulf, or the Zulf ending, those were such powerful and moving moments.As for gameplay, I'll first say that I truly respect when game makers try something novel and original.That being said, I personally didn't enjoy the new combat system too much. It was definitely interesting,but in general, I found it to get old rather quickly, even if there was an exponentially large number of combinations.I also found the game to have much less content, around half as much as Bastion (hence my price comment above).For example, Bastion had challenges for every weapon, each being fairly different and refreshing.Here, most of the challenges were very similar and just normal combat you'd get in the main game anyway.Finally, as for the story, I think it was on level with Bastion. It was a great, well told story.Some people have given it flak, but I think original and non-cliche stories are hard to come by,and this managed to be novel in some ways that I hadn't seen before.All in all, I'd give this an 8/10. Wonderful game from a promising studio."
