,Recommended,237930,21117197,"Posted: 10 February, 2016",all,Pyrolander,"Transistor is probably the most visually stunning game I've ever played. I like its art style so much, that ever since the game was released (maybe even a little before that) 99% of my wallpapers have been Transistor themed.Both the graphics and the soundtrack are amazing, but thankfully the gameplay is also fantastic! The mix of real time combat and turn() planning not only make the game feel fresh and serve to set it apart from Bastion, but also give the player the chance to experiment with two very different styles of play.Personally, I prefer to freeze time, plan carefully and then hit all my enemies with a devastating attack, so I try to use turn() as much as I can. But no matter which style you prefer, I'd recommend to everyone to play Transistor with a gamepad, the controls are super simple and feel very good.Another great thing about this game is how even though there are relatively few functions (abilities/attacks) available, all of them can be combined with each other to create improved variations of a base ability, or used on a special passive slot to gain completely different effects, which gives the game a lot more depth than you'd think.The story is beautiful and sad at the same time, and serves as a perfect backdrop for the gameplay. As it's usually the case with any good book, film or game, the only bad part is that feeling of emptiness after you finish it and realize that it's over. Time to play it again, drool over how beautiful everything is and try new combinations of functions!"
