76561197984387606,Recommended,237930,21185130,"Posted: 13 February, 2016",all,ZARBEAR,"An Absolute Stunner""Transistor"" is a combination of exquisite art and engaging turn-based combat. The world this game takes place in, the city of Cloudbank, is stunning to look at. The motif of the environment is an oddly utopian sort of cyberpunk, or that's at least the best way I can describe it. The point is that this game's look and world-building are its strongest assets.The protagonist, Red, has lost her voice after narrowly evading an assassination attempt. She fights an A.I. hivemind known as the Process, a rapidly spreading scourge that is destroying Cloudbank. However, Red has the power of the Transistor, a sort of giant sword/paddle that talks and is largely the only voice the player hears throughout the game. You have to guide Red through the city to uncover who tried to kill her, the truth behind the Process, and how to stop it.The combat in the game is above average, but it's not gonna knock your socks off. You enter a designated area and fight enemies in groups. After you've eliminated the last enemy you'll get experience and will be able to continue through the map. The key to combat is using the Turn() function to freeze time and map out you plan of attack. You're limited in how much you can move and attack during Turn() though, so you have to strategize and make sure not to die between usages as you're unable to attack until Turn() recharges.You can acquire loads of different abilities, known as Functions, in ""Transistor"" and each function can be used in three different ways depending on how you equip them. This makes for a very flexible and customizable combat experience. There is also a challenge mode are built into the main game where the player can run through different tests involving speed, strategy, and endurance. Successfully completing each test grants additional experience.I'd be remiss if I didn't mention the music in this game. Simply put, it's absolutely stunning and probably the best game soundtrack I've hear since ""Fez."" Lots of lilting, sleepy jazz tracks accompany you as you stroll the empty streets of Cloudbank. The music tends to be somber in most places and suits the environment and narrative well.""Transistor"" is a game that sucks you right into its world and make you fall in love with it. The audio and visual presentation is unforgettable. The game also manages a great world-building experience without any exposition, which I love because I personally can't stand exposition. The combat takes some getting used to and the fact that Red only moves at the same slow speed will frustrate some. However the high customizability of the different Functions means you can find your ideal way to fight.I would recommend ""Transistor"" to anyone and everyone."
76561198139373162,Recommended,237930,21218670,"Posted: 14 February, 2016",all,Zoro4rk,"In a few words, Transistor is simply gorgeous. The music is simply perfect, from beggining to end, the art is suberb and the atmosphere is great.Now, a game isn't only about its looks, and luckily Transistor is much more than that. The gamestyle is really smart and different, and that's really neat. Trying new functions is so exciting, and combining then is even more.The Turn system is so smart.Transistor also has a great set of characthers. From Red to the Camerata and the smaller ones, you'll eventually find someone that'll stick to your heart.The plot can be a really confusing tho, but the end is comprehensible nonetheless.So in short: Transistor is a great game and I can't stop recommending it (in fact, 5 of my friends have bought and enjoyed it) and it's even better with a discount. Supergiant is a great game maker and I sure hope to see newer games soon."
76561198080655729,Recommended,237930,13752149,"Posted: 31 December, 2014",all,Taylor Swift,Great graphics and music
,Recommended,237930,10976855,"Posted: 30 June, 2014",all,GRRRR,"Coming from the dudes who made Bastion it looks and sounds very good but beneath that is a pretty indepth combat system aswell.Bastion was abit simple, you found different weapons and could dual wield them. This time around you get 4 active slots for skills and each of these skills can have up to two other skills attached to it to alter or boost its effects and you also have passive slots. Theres no designated passive or support skills, each skill can fit in any slot.For example the basic attack can just be the basic attack - or you could take it out of the active slot and attach it to another skill which then gains a stun attribute or the like. In the passive slot it provides damage resistance. Theres about 12 different skills and its really quite fun to experiment around with what combinations do what, you can make your own ""builds"" so to speak.Another thing is two combat modes, Real Time and ""Turn"" (Matrix i guess). In Real time you run around in real time. Turn mode stops time and you can plan your movement and skill use within a fixed budget (altho that can be altered with certain skills in a passive slot) which then gets executed lighting fast. The catch is Turn mode has a cooldown during which you cant use any skills in realtime either (generally).Its somewhat linear, theres a new game plus but i guess the replay value depends on how much you would be willing to shake up a tried and true combination :P"
