,Recommended,237930,27337836,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,Cerulean,Best Game EVER!!
,Recommended,237930,10185598,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,McBoober,"I decided I would write a review specifically about Transistor's similarities to Bastion and what it does better and worse.Combat: Both games feature incredibly customizable combat. Bastion has around 10 different weapon, which can all be upgraded, and you can have two with you at a time for combos such as all melee, all range, mix, all fast, all slow, etc etc. Transistor gives you four slots for attacks, starting you off with a weak fast attack, a slow strong attack, a dash, and area of effect. However, it quickly becomes more than that. The amount of combat customization is staggering, you get a hefty amount of moves. BUT then very single move can be used as one of up to four passive abilities AND can be used to modify your current active moves. The customization takes it a step up above Bastions already impressive amount.As far as the systems go. Bastion was very much action oriented, The Kid has a dedicated Roll and Block button and the combat is that of an action game. However, it's much harder to draw similarities to transistors gameplay. It's much more tactical, you have the ability to go into a ""planning"" mode where time stops, and you can take as long as you want to choreograph a set of actions for the protagonist, Red, which she will then execute very quickly while the enemies must sit there and take it. After planning mode is finished and your moves executed, the meter must recharge before Red can do this again, leaving her vulnerable. She has no dedicated block or dodge, anything resembling these abilities must be achieved through the loadout you pick, leaving her vulnerable and her only option to find cover behind the protruding blocks on the ground, which can be destroyed by either you or enemy fire (they will regenerate.) However, while planning mode leaves you vulnerable, the ability to quickly execute moves makes it a must, activating abilities in real time alone isn't going to cut it. It's tough to get the hang of it, but once you find a build that works for you, and get a full grasp on how to best utilize the mechanics, that combat can be incredibly fun. Some may prefer the action combat of Bastion, some may prefer Transistors strategic approach, this will come down to personal tastes, however, Transistors combat mechanics are structurally in-depth and interesting, if they click with you I believe you will have loads of fun.Death in Bastion also has less long term affects. You run out of potions? Back to The Bastion with you. Transistor is interesting because what happens is when you run out of health your active more that uses the most power breaks, and remains broken for two savepoints. This is quite a bit more interesting as the penalty for running out of health is that you have to temporarily change up your strategy. Which is quite a bit more interesting than a game over. I do not know what happens once all four of your powers are gone. I assume once that happens you do experience a game over situation.Enemy variety is a bit down from Bastion. However the actually variety in function of the enemies is up. This is likely because of the more tactical aspect of the game. The enemies can come together in a perfect harmony that will make you really need to think about how you are going to approach a situation, and they can really keep the pressure on. Another thing worth noting is the enemies level up with you, so as you progress enemies you've been seeing since your first encounter in the game will continue to stay as threatening as ever.Fans of Bastion also might remember praying to the gods to impose more challenge on the game in return for rewards. This happens as well in Transistor, however, it is mandatory. Occasionally when you level up, you are essentially given a choice as to how the game will get harder for you, with each option also having a corresponding reward. This system is very cool, however this does mean you cannot pile all of these challenges on at will like you can in Bastion, which some may not like. Overall though there almost two different uses of a similar system. Bastion is essentially turning on hardcore mode within the worlds lore for some rewards. Where Transistor is essentially saying ""Ok, the game is gonna get harder now, but you get a choice in how that happens."" Another nice thing is the rewards are all just unlock slots for your customizable build, and the none of the challenges are expressly harder so which choice is the most desrable all comes down to you. Causing you run into interesting situation where there slot you want might make the game harder in a way you find especially difficult.Overall, the combat's level of customization is staggering, from a technical standpoint Transistor is quite a bit more in-depth.The hub world: This is probably the only area where Transistor falls flat. They decided to include a hub world. In Bastion, The Bastion is where you deal with a lot of your upgrades, as well as getting little tidbits of the worlds lore, and selecting which level you would like to go to (including challenge levels). In Transistor all of those things, including the lore tidbits, are dealt with via leveling up, and the terminals you run into throughout the game which also work as save points (there is no level system). From a gameplay standpoint, the only reason this hub exists is for the challenge courses. You also cannot visit it whenever you'd like, doors to this, as I recall, unnamed place appear throughout your game, you will not know when. Because of this going there essentially becomes a pain. Where as in Bastion it just happened. Making any of the content there less appealing. I would rather have accesed the challenge courses from the terminal I access everything else in. There is also seemingly some things to do, a hammock to lie in, a ball to bounce, I ended up with a tamed version of one of the enemies. But I don't really know for certain because by half way through the game I stopped even going in when I saw a door open for it. Short and simple, it was a neat little area, it didn't need to exist, or it should have been easier to access. However, this is the only time where the design of the game feels anything short of well thought out and smart. The game would have lasted longer for me if it wasn't a chore to get to the bonus content. This also brings me to my next point.Game length: I beat the game at around 3.8-3.9 hours of playtime, a bit under what seems to be the average of 5. Don't get me wrong, it was a damn good 3.8 hours I don't regret. But there was easily the possibility for two other bosses, two at the least maybe even three, that would not have detracted from the experience if they existed the game even sort of lead me to believe I would encounter. Bastion's playtime was also longer because it invited me to experience it's extra content, whereas Transistor made me go out of my way to find it. Which is why I ended up skipping it largely.Artistic design stuff: This is largely subjective so I'll be brief and just mention some changes people might want to be aware of.The voice of Rucks, Logan Cunningham, returns. This had me worried that Transistor would be ""Bastion but different"" but he is not a narrator this time, and he is actually using a (somewhat) different voice. His role feels different enough from his role as Rucks that the game doesn't feel like ""Bastion but this time x is different"". Some may also find him less ""intrusive"" this time  although I doubt anyone who liked the amount he appeared in Bastion will find him particularly ""absent"" comparatively. Artstyle is kinda similar but different enough, it's nice seeing a cohesive world in this style and I'm sure plenty of people will be glad to find you cannot fall off the edge of the world this time. Music is just as good I'm running out of space theres a button to sing to your sword it's great games great I highly reccomend it."
