,Recommended,237930,32236444,Posted: 7 June,all,miezkatz,"Transistor amalgamates incredible art, sound and story with engaging gameplay. It's hard to pinpoint which aspect of the game shines the brightest when everything is so well thought out and sincere.The gameplay is surprisingly profound with diverse approaches to its semi-turn based features. The balancing act between planned and real time combat is managed by providing enough abilities adjustable depending on the preferred playstyle. Through level ups and occasional finds the player obtains Functions that each can be used to either gain an active skill, modify an active skill or provide a passive boost. Restricting factors in composing a build is the available Memory, which acts as a permanent action point system. To clarify, only the amount and quality of Functions that can be assembled is restricted, not the combat itself. Although the range of enemies is sparse, they gain new upgrades throughout the game and gradually increase in difficulty. Optionally, the game offers Limiters that on activation further pose a challenge with a small experience benefit.Set in an alternate sci-fi reality, the peculiarities of the world seem intriguing and alienating at the same time. Cloudbank, the city it all takes place in, looks stunning. Its vibrant colours, interspersed with gold-plated Klimt patterns, are striking yet warm and glowing. Interrupting the scenery are a few select artworks which are across the board beautiful to look at.Melancholic music, sung by the protagonist Red, and devoted narration by the Transistor, the talking sword of Red, are the two main story assets of Transistor. The tale of these two characters unfolds and reveals a tragedy. While in the beginning the Transistor seems to be unnecessarily chatty, the voice actors' sublime performance soon proofs to be the most powerful and captivating narration conceivable.Above all, Transistor is a precious and heartfelt ARPG experience."
