76561198051474074,Recommended,237930,16672759,"Posted: 24 June, 2015",all,Malecord,"I thought it was a Bastion clone. I was wrong. It's way better.Don't misunderstand, I liked Bastion. The idea of the narrator is cool and the game art is something nice too. It's just that I don't super like it. The gameplay especially. I felt it a little slow.So when I came to transistor I was somewhat scared I would like it for the art/music but not so much for the gameplay. But indeed this is not a clone. You can recognize the style which is unique to SuperGiants ofc. But the game actually plays quite differently and the combat mechanics are another story than those in Bastion.The idea of battleplans is crazily good. It alternates phases of pure speed with phases of... well, planning. So you don't have the time to get stressed of running around overwhelmed by hordes of enemies nor you have time to get bored by all that turn-like combat planning. They alternates. And they actually interact with each other so that when you run around waiting for transistor to recharge you think of how to take time and where to go to start your battleplan. And viceversa when you are battleplanning you will be forced to think what will you do afterwards when the time starts to flow again. It's just a perfect mix. A great design idea. Chapeau to the devs."
76561198071240966,Recommended,237930,34349987,Posted: 19 August,all,Vas,OH MY GOD THE MUSIC IN THIS GAME
,Recommended,237930,20949024,"Posted: 4 February, 2016",all,aruvin,"Transistor, developed by Supergiant Games & Released on  May 20, 2014. According to Metacritic(http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/transistor), it's ranked:#30 Best PC Game of 2014#49 Most Discussed PC Game of 2014#97 Most Shared PC Game of 2014It's not often that you get to hear about indie game's making it into the spotlight or having set a particular standard@benchmark for it's genre/for a particular gaming market. Transistor is one of the many indie games which deserves recognition. A testiment to it's genre of what indie games are capable of. and more to come.I've never completed Bastion but the game is still fresh in my memory because of it's unique gaming experience. The narrator. The story. With the same formula, now comes Transistor. It is a RPG, set in the distant future where you play as a female character known as Red. You're wielding a mysterious swordlike object which happens to be the narrator for your entire journey. You will uncover the truth/secrets on what's happening around you and to the town.The controls are easy to master. The visuals are okay to me. What stands out the most is it's art syle. I am not sure how to describe it, plain, odd and yet pretty. From monster design to each character/ability profile.LoreThe game offers lore on the abilities you pick up from certain characters. In order to unlock the character's background information, you will be forced to use these abilities differently; active skill, secondary skill or as a passive skill - and this will change your style of play.Other than that, you will also have to choose limiters. Limiters are another set of passive skills which comes with a trade off. You get additional exp for a handicap in battle throughout the game. For example; You gain 4% more exp but The enemies will strike with twice as much power. User will overload more Functions at once and recover only one per Access Point for an additional 4% exp. This will certainly make the game even more challenging. The good news is that, you are able to disable the limiters.The MechanicsAt a glance, it looks like diablo/neverwinter nights type of gameplay. You have a hero with 4 active skill. That's on the surface, the fast action side on the battle. Transistor introduces turn - a mode where you will are able to enter and plan out your moves within the given bar? This is a unique mode which requires strategic planning; to maximize the moves with the allocated bar. or just for plain escape.In transistor, once you lose all 4 active skill, you die@lose that particular level of the game. You have to replay that part of level. If you survived a battle with remaining 2 active skill, you're stuck with them until you come across the next panel. There is no such thing as health potion therefore making each battle more RTS like. You can't go blazing around like in diablo. Most of the time, you will be required to use turn to plan and execute your moves.Enemy AIEach enemy was designed differently and they are smart. A mixture of different enemy types is enough to kill you -without proper planning. It can feel punisable at certain point of the game but that's just because we are not equiping the right skill for that combat. If it's too hard, just swtich off the limiters and plan your attacks using turn. Bringing in big guns@skills with takes up a lot of points, doesn't guarantee your success rate.The StoryTransistor uses the narrator to motivate you to go through the game. On theory, this should work however I find that the pacing is off due to it's design. That was what put me off from Bastion. After a battle, you suddenly find a hidden backdoor, after a battle you suddely let red rest/take shower. The pacing was off for me but I pushed on because I wanted to know Red's relationship with the man in the transistor. When the answer was obvious, I wanted to know how this would end. What happens to the Town and it's people?My Summary:Transistor is a creative product. Despite having a linear story and with little replay value, the combat system is fun where it allows users to mix & match their skills and work things out. The journey was worthit.I went through numeruous battles & deaths, took the puzzles and had a major annoying boss fight. What I got was a poweful, worthwhile & bittersweet ending. So far, only 2 games have left me with such strong impression & none of them are from AAA game titles. On the scale of 0 - 10, my personal rating for Transistor is a 8/10."
