,Recommended,237930,10195871,"Posted: 22 May, 2014",all,Player.-,"GENERALWhat's really weird about this game is the  fact that it doesn't have a main menu - it just drops you right into the game. You have different profiles, but the game automatically saves and reloads where you last saved whenever you start the game.The game has a slow start at first, though you quickly pick up extra Functions and add more versatility to your playstyle.FUNCTIONS(abilities):You get quite a few Functions; some you get via story, others via levelling up. Since you can equip every Function in an active, upgrade or passive slot, you have quite a few combinations available; though most functions have the same effect on almost every function, it can change your playstyle considerably. This comes to show later into the game, when you need to plan more carefully or else you die like a ♥♥♥♥♥, like I did. But instead of losing the game the second you lose your HP, you keep losing functions until you've lost all you have - survive the fight, and you'll take 2 save points to recover the ones you lost. Through this feature I changed my build and learned to appreciate Functions I never used. However, even at the final level, it feels like you are rather limited in the amount of Functions you get; You have 4 Active slots; you can unlock a total of 2 Upgrade slots for each as well as 4 passive slots. I've never managed to fill all the slots up.What I really miss here is a proper dodge function. You have a Function that takes care of it, but it has a long after-cast delay that you cannot really rely on it for anything other than Turn()Oh, that's another thing I haven't mentioned. Welp, you can plan your moves and attacks in a strategic mode. The problem? You're virtually useless for a few seconds afterwards, unless you have a survival ability or upgrade an attack function with the dash Function. Forgot its name.GRAPHICS:The visuals are stunning and flow quite well most of the time. My main complaint is that the character model seems to move a bit awkwardly. Then there are also cutscenes which are supposed to reveal crucial events of the story, that are shown simply as a still image with parts that are barely moving. So that's a letdown; especially when they're coupled with the Trailer music. You'd think it'd be epic or more action packed, only to get a very slow moving image.MUSIC:The music is amazing; though the tower song seems a bit too repetitive for my taste.STORY:Story is nice overall, though I'd say everything escalates all too quickly. You're dropped into the game and only later learn the circumstances surrounding you obtaining the Transistor; which is fine. What I do not like is that you fight just about two bosses and you're already retracing your steps back to the beginning and get to the finale. Supergiant Games' previous title had a lot more levels full of small things that enriched the story, and boss-like instances when it came to that. Here the environment does not really complete the story that well, aside from the terminals, which are quite heart-breaking towards the end. Bastion would take different turns, too, not just ""Start at point A, reach point B, go back to point A; visit point C. VOILA! You beat the game."" I was seriously hoping the game would have been a bit longer than Bastion and that the story would be more fleshed out, but nope. Though it feels quite rushed, it's still enjoyable nonetheless.PERFORMANCE ISSUES:I have a PC that's well above the requirements yet I experience quite a few bugs and random freezes. Hopefully they'll fix this in a future patch.FINAL VERDICT:It's a good game. Personally I'd give it a 7 or 8 out of 10. Had it been just a little longer story-wise and a bit more fleshed out, it would've been amazing and well worth the price. Right now, it just feels like I did not get quite what I paid for. Sure, good for casual fun, but didn't really touch me as much as Bastion did. Maybe wait till it's on sale?"
