76561197993078765,Not Recommended,237930,10919196,"Posted: 28 June, 2014",all,Ursan,"Very interesting game. Gameplay consists of combat against preset foes upon entering sections of a map. Exploration is not really important, but it will help find some additional story and gameplay. Combat is in two phases, real time action with a set of up to 4 skills, and pause-and-plan using the same 4 actions. During pause-and-plan you have an energy bar and each of your moves takes a different cost.You have four types of character upgrade options, each of which is chosen from a growing set of techs/souls, earned by leveling up and through the story. The options are actions, action modifiers, passive modifiers and limiters. Each tech/soul has a theme to it: pet, heal, poison, ect. Additional story is unlocked by using each tech/soul in each available upgrade type. I think this portion of the game could have been improved using voice acting instead of reading.The combat was interesting to begin with and stayed challenging throughout, but I didn't enjoy it as much as the combat in Bastion. It felt like each round of combat was a puzzle, but that I was forced to defend myself without defense abilities during the down time between pause-and-plan phases.The stand-alone challenge levels were fun, but a bit repetitive. The game shined in story and atmosphere despite a lack of depth or length. Knowing what I knw now, I probably wouldn't buy it again, but I would buy the soundtrack."
76561198148997598,Not Recommended,237930,12818292,"Posted: 6 November, 2014",all,The Iconoclast,"A textbook case of trying too hard. I hoped I'd have learned by now that when the vast majority of user reviews cites a game's story as a strong point without any concrete supporting reasons, it typically means that the story is, in actuality, flawed and whatever quality makes it that way is masked by other elements of the game such as music, atmosphere, visuals and other story-enhancing elements that aren't actually part of the story.It's not hard to see why a lot of people would like this game. The skill system is incredibly clever in its simplicity, variety and potency. It's the only game I've ever played where I haven't found a single skill to be useless or ineffective. This system alone merits praise and hopefully future emulation. The visuals are enchanting and the score haunting and every other superficial and mechanical element is in place to make someone enjoy this game...but beyond that is where things fall apart.The mystery of the story stretched all the way into my apathy as by the time the world revealed itself sufficiently, I had long stopped caring. It's not impossible to successfully push the exposition of a mystery all the way to the end, but there needs to be adequate engagement in the interim and SuperGiant did not provide. All they gave was an empty world with only the skeletons of characters, minimally fleshed out and ultimately not meriting sympathy or interest.Worst of all, the conflict made ZERO sense. *PSEUDO-SPOILER* High ranking public servants from the ""government"" plot to imprison influential, celebrity figures with the goal of abolishing a capricious democracy that renders their work meaningless. *END SPOILER* Are you kidding me? Government drones have an existential crisis and accidentally destroy a city? They should've known when they took their posts that government is ineffective and should be dissolved. In all seriousness though, no suspension of disbelief can make me take this plot seriously. It's like if a waiter reflected on the pointlessness of his job and decided to imprison all restaurant owners to end the drudgery of waiting forever. It just doesn't make sense! And the heroes are a singer and her talking-sword-lover, niether of whom had sufficient backstory to make me care about their relationship?!?...fighting against an army of robots who are just doing their job at the behest of a NON-VILLAIN who accidentally let them run wild?!?!?!?! All of this adds up to a conflict that simply doesn't exist, let alone make sense and all the beautiful music and scenery couldn't pull me back into this heap.The last - and a minor grievance - is that the gameplay, even the walking speed, could've been a little faster. It felt almost like a turn-based strategy game that ran too fast or an action game that moved too slow.The most effective stories have a simple premise but are delivered effectively with relatable, interesting, sympathetic characters as the agents of delivery. Transistor had an overwrought premise and failed to deliver it on all fronts and that's what I call trying too hard. Might be worth a purchase at $5 just to see some of the clever ideas implemented and, for aspiring story writers: how NOT to deliver a story. For me, it was too disappointing and even the sale price of $10 now feels like a cold slap in the groin."
,Not Recommended,237930,14870438,"Posted: 13 March, 2015",all,HyvelTjuven,"I want to love this game, I really do, the graphics are amongst the prettiest I've ever had the fortune to look at, the soundtrack is nothing short of amazing, the story is interesting, the voice acting feels really well in place and I really enjoyed that the game threw you right into the action from the moment you pressed play (after the inital loading screen, of course).But unfortunately for me I feel like the whole experience is dragged through the mud by a seriously uninspired and dull combat system. And there is a lot of combat in this game.You might have a different experience if you enjoy strategy games but as someone who is not too fond of them the ""turn()""-system which the combat is more or less entierly based around just feels tedious to me, killing enemies doesn't feel as satisfying as it should, in fact it felt like a chore and worst of all it makes the game feel like it's progressing far slower than it actually does, which is weird for a game as short as this.Fortunately for me I bought the soundtrack as well, so I get to enjoy that without actually playing the game!"
