76561197970297854,Not Recommended,237930,13775023,"Posted: 1 January, 2015",all,sickBoy,"Overall: 5/10This is one of the games where I really would need a neutral review option, since Transistor has a lot going for it, but ultimately it ended up disappointing, therefore it will be a thumbs down from me on this one.I loved Bastion, the previous game by developer Supergiant Games, so Transistor was an easy purchase, both games share a lot of similarities in art style, storytelling technique and atmospheric world building. However there is one major difference, while Bastion at its core was a very good action RPG that got elevated into something greater by is innovative narration and fantastic audio-visual presentation. The core gameplay of Transistor on the other hand is a weird turned-base tactical combat with a single character and modular skills. All the elevating elements are present around it, if you strip them away, what would be left is underwhelming, the combat is not as deep as it aspires to be, the difficulty is set too low (at least on the initial playthrough) and since the story is strictly linear, there is not much motivation for making use of the New Game Plus option. To be fair, towards the end the gameplay deepens a bit once your heroine levels up and acquires more skills, but it is too little too late, by then the story is almost over and I really can’t appreciate the design decision to make the character builds and fights more fun in additional sessions only. It is frustratingly hard to actually time the correct start of a turn and in between you run around like a headless chicken due to very un-precise mouse movement, the way you lose skills when your life-bar is depleted encourages experimentation, but gets annoying fast, since you basically spend too much time in the clunky menus re-assigning four functions after every second battle or so.It comes down to this, I did not enjoy the fights at all. The game is short enough to make me push through, the story is interesting enough to serve as motivation and there is much to appreciate along the way, from the gorgeous world design over the phenomenal driving soundtrack and the quality of the writing behind the transistors voice. But it all goes only so far if the core gameplay is completely no fun for the majority of the playtime and there is not much to do besides walk from fight to fight and read some environmental clues.I am still interested in what the talented people at Supergiant Games come up with next, but whatever it is, I hope they do not forget the most important principle of what makes a game a good game: gameplay first. I need to enjoy the interactive sections as much as the narrated ones, if there is a mismatch as evidently the case with Transistor the overall judgement has to be a negative one.Pros:- fantastic music/voice work- immersive environment designCons:- shallow repetitive combat- annoying heath system- linear and short- gameplay deepens only in NG+"
