76561197961494531,Recommended,237930,10181322,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,Rapscallion,"Transistor is breath-taking. Not only is the gameplay fantastic, but the art and music are something to behold even by themselves. Combine it all together with an intriguing story, and you got yourself this wonder of a game.Here's a quick look video if you want to see the game in action. Or if you prefer to read a more concise review, please continue below.http://youtu.be/oAq4GGFQAJMLet me start with gameplay, the bread and butter about what makes this game so good. You play as Red, and you wield a talking sword who I won't reveal is. But what can this girl and sword do? That's pretty much up to you and the huge number of ways you can customize her. To start, you have 4 abilities you can select between and use like a standard MOBA game. But the neat thing about it is you can put a wide range of different abilities into those slots that all do different things, such a setting a mine, a missile that drags enemies towards you, summon a hound, etc. You can then take it one step further and combine other abilities that modify an existing one. Like your dogs? Then combine it with a charm attack that allows their bark to turn foes to your side. What's that, you want another? Sure, take another split ability on it and have two dogs that charm. Hell, you can even put abilities as passives that grant you amazing buffs. There's a huge number of possibilities that you can do to play the game you want to play, and experimenting is half the fun.But don't get me wrong. While you may be able to do amazing things, the game is still challenging, and not in a cheap way. Everything comes at a price. If you load one ability to the teeth, your not gonna have enough memory to load in other abilities elsewhere, maybe not even be able to afford a passive. You also get a cool bullet-time mode that you're able to plan out moves and execute them swiftly and precisely. The only downfall is you have to wait awhile before you can do anything else as you recharge. The interesting variety of enemies you come across also make this game stand out, and simply the way you handle them. One enemy will charge at your relentlessly while another lobs grenades at you from a distance. You even have stationary enemies that provides shields or heal their buddies. And combining them all together in different groups adds a great deal of strategy and dynamics to every encounter. Even more so when you have to reach an enemy core before they respawn and you're forced to kill them all over again. Add in limiters that make enemies tougher for more exp, and you can make the game as unforgiving as you want.Now if that wasn't enough to grab you, then how about the fantastic environments that blend so well with the sci-fi theme? Or how about the the music that sets the mood and tone so well for the game. Or how do fancy the fantastic and dynamic voice acting that reacts to what you do and how you do it? That alone is a feature I really enjoy. Sometimes I just like sitting back and listening as more of the mystery unravels before me. But if you'd rather play the game, you can simply plow right ahead. Even the way you skip cutsceens is well done. You can choose to simply accelerate your bike or boat to head to the next area instead of listening, thus making you feel you're still engrossed in the world.But now that I sung praises for this game, it still has minor flaws.*My game crashed as I was heading to another area, and I had to restart the level. The game also froze for a bit when I was in a fight. I have a beast of a computer, so I know my end is not to blame.*The only thing you can customize in the graphics menu is resolution, which is named resolution accordingly. The game looks fantastic as it is for high-end rigs, but those who may want to skirt by the minimum requirements may not be able to.*Although I'm really interested about the story, sometimes I get the feeling I still don't understand what I going on when the answer appears to be right before me. The whole game is pretty vague, and the game simply drops you right into the action without warning at all. Personally, I liked that it does these things, but some who like to know everything as it happens may not like this.That's really all I can think of. I simply enjoy this game immensely, and I highly recommend anyone pick this game up. I feel like it's a steal at $20, and when it goes on sale, then there shouldn't even be a question anymore that you should get it."
