,Not Recommended,237930,34352155,Posted: 19 August,all,raikolives,"This game looks stunning. But like the main character once you get past the looks, all you get is a hum.Transistor starts out mysterious and ethereal, leaning into it's art style heavily, and that's great, but as soon as it wraps up it's little opening mystery - about 30 minutes in - the suspense, anything even remotely compelling, is gone. From there it's all just repetitive fights, incessant overly complicated unlockables and a soundtrack that drones on and on without ever really feeling like it exists in the same game. Building your powers is a great idea, and the way Transistor does it feels like it has potential, but the pieces come way too fast while the slots to use them in come way too slow.The game's fights, also, lock you into a tiny area filled with semi-destructable obstacles, making navigation instantly annoying. When the enemy units can float casually through or over the blocks and you can't, it becomes frustrating. When the pause-and-plan functionality feels like its more trouble than its worth, it just becomes a button-spamming simulator, which the build-your-powers system would make you believe it isn't. And when the game decides to make it too hard so you NEED to use the planning system, I turned it off.Drop this powerset-building mechanic into a brawler - 2D or 3D it doesn't matter - and you'll have an innovative system that works within your game. But everything about Transistor feels like it's holding me back or pushing me away, and while the end result of the unlockables system may be fun, I'm not about to slog through a boring series of samey levels to find out.If there was an art book of Transistor, I'd grab it. It's a beautiful thing to look at. But the game struggles to align it's systems, and make use of it's best parts."
76561198004585236,Recommended,237930,31716470,Posted: 12 May,all,AtlasDragneel,Just beautiful.
76561198010641857,Recommended,237930,14733291,"Posted: 2 March, 2015",all,Ivan Moreira,"Transistor is everything everyone says and more. The soundtrack, oh the soundtrack...Took me 10.5 hours to finish the first playthrough just because I want to listen to everything, see everything, try every possible combination on combat...Awesome, awesome, awesome game. Please, SuperGiants, keep them coming and keep them like that. Like Bastion. Like Transistor.10/10, will replay."
,Recommended,237930,17145602,"Posted: 20 July, 2015",all,Mom's Spaghetti,"As someone who went into the game without doing any research except reading the ""Overwhelmingly Positive"" consensus by other reviews, I was pleasantly surprised by what I found. I hadn't played Bastion and I'm not the biggest RPG fan, but turn-based combat fascinates me, and Transistor introduced a refreshing twist to this style of gameplay.GameplayTransistor is an action RPG whose combat involves a mix of RTS and turn-based fighting. You can choose to play the game straight and try to defeat all the enemies without a chance to stop and think, or you can press the spacebar to plan a ""Turn()"", which effectively pauses the game and gives you time to strategize. During your turn, you have the opportunity to move around the battlefield and use your abilities to blast enemies apart. Between battles, you use ""Access Points"" to customize your active and passive abilities and limiters. Only four active abilities can be equipped at a time, but the game allows the player to combine abilities to strengthen them. Limiters are unlocked as you progress, and are used to make the game harder, with the benefit of leveling up faster. Progression through the game is extremely linear, but the ability combinations and limiters can be used to fight the way you want, the principle on which the gameplay seems to be based.StoryDisclaimer: I'm not going into details (read other reviews for those).The story is well-written, the characters are kept to a minimum, the dialogue even feels right... essentially, it's kept to a level that's not too hard to understand. Replaying the game will give you a better grasp of everything if you didn't understand the first time. Unfortunately, the game is rather short and doesn't allow itself much time for fleshing out the characters we know; even character bios aren't exactly 100% satisfying (although they are intruiging as good short reads). I'd have liked to understood the main characters better, but I'm not complaining with what I have.Graphics & Sound10/10 in this department, as everyone else agrees. It's hard to find a game that looks and sounds as beautiful as Transistor. The art style is consistently fitting and amazing throughout the game's few-hour stay. Darren Korb did a spectactular job on the soundtrack and the voice acting is great (as well as Red's singing). I really can't find a fault with this aspect of the game.Obviously Transistor isn't perfect, but the few flaws it has are nowhere near enough to ruin the experience. It may feel somewhat shallow on the first playthrough, but it only takes a few minutes to realize that it's a worthwhile addition to anyone's game library."
76561197993333398,Recommended,237930,10181602,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,RedundantVagabond,"‘Transistor’ can only be described as a jazzy composition, seductive and melancholic. I felt as if a tenor sax was played before me.This performance does not hold any punches. From the get go it launches you into the game. No hand holding, it respects your intelligence as you begin to explore the world.Gameplay is reminiscent of Supergiant Games’ 'Bastion'. Isometric view and action packed, but what this brings is a more matured and well thought out experience. Aside from the obvious action orientated combat system, it allows for RPG elements to take hold. A plan of action can be devised, by using this new feature the player can plan a method of attack utilizing and maximizing on his carefully customized skills.The average time to complete this game is around 5 hours. Calculating the cost per minute of entertainment, it would be like buying an average movie ticket (being generous I assumed for a 2 hour length film for $7.96) for each minute one interacts with the game. It comes to a total of $19.90, and that is if you only play it once.If you need to save money, then wait.Hell, just watch a play through if you just want to consume the basic story. Though, I think you may get more out of it by actually playing it yourself.I stand by my purchase, and highly recommend this game."
,Recommended,237930,10181506,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,ChierΩn,"Even from the comparatively small amount I've played, this is well worth the purchase, both for people who enjoy story, or gameplay."
,Recommended,237930,10181637,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,♪Kyle³,"The game is just beautiful and visually stunning you walk through the game and cannot help but look at every bit of detail, The combat system works really well and I never feel like I have been cheated. The combat system is like your old rpg turn base games but with a modern day twist, The characters are really fleshed out and in depth even just the side characters have tons of lore that you can unlock and read about. 10/10"
,Recommended,237930,10181148,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,Mel,"The soundtrack is amazing, of course. The gameplay is interesting--there's multiple ways to play between attacking in real-time, attacking in the planning mode that gives you some time to think out and construct a more complex moveset, and the different attacks you can have set up for Red. Each attack can be slotted as active (using it as an actual attack), upgrade (using its abilities to upgrade one of your active skills), or passive (granting Red some passive skills like a counterattack, healing when not recharging a turn, etc.), and you're encouraged to experiment because more story is unlocked when you use each skill in its various potential slots.The story is interesting and one I found emotionally compelling, but it's one where you have to search it out and piece things together on your own a little, so if you like a definite, straightforward story, be aware of that, since you'll have to go out of your way a bit to get all the story information.The voice acting is great, though that was probably expected if you've played Bastion, and I found the central emotional connection between Red and the man in the Transistor to be one that held my attention--I cared about and wanted to see a happy ending for these characters.There's a recursion (new game plus) mode once you beat the main storyline; with additional plot elements and enemies trying to keep pace with you, this adds additional replay value, for those who want more bang for their buck. There's also a system in which you can upgrade the enemies with various limiters, making them more powerful or removing some of your own abilities for an extra challenge (and, of course, there are the associated achievements for getting through enough battles with enough of them active, for you achievement hunters).Overall, I would definitely reccommend this game. I personally enjoyed it more than Bastion, though I'm always a sucker for a female protagonist and a science fiction setting. It's definitely a good second showing from Supergiant Games!Also: Absolutely worth it just for the soundtrack. It's a gorgeous soundtrack."
