,Not Recommended,237930,24927790,"Posted: 14 August, 2016",all,Surprise Feudalism,"Disclaimer: contains very minor spoilers.Transistor is probably a fine game on its own, but it's very hard not to compare it to Bastion, one of my favorite action RPGs. Transistor is more verbose but nonetheless says less about its world and characters. Where Bastion made some motivations explicit and left others to the imagination, Transistor just left me scratching my head. Some of the plot twists and introduced characters seem abrubt or incomplete, making me wonder if parts of the game were cut or rushed.Aesthetically, the game starts out gorgeous and then devolves into geometric monochrome which isn't ugly but didn't wow me like the first few levels did. That's in keeping with the game's plot and themes, but it's still regrettable. The music is still great.The gameplay is still an action RPG with mix-and-match moves and perks to match your play style. The modular way you build your abilities and the power to drop temporarily into a turn-based mode keep the gameplay fresh as you advance. The game felt a little short; right as I felt the game was starting to enter the cool design space of end-game fights, the encounters all switched style and then I was at the final boss, who was disappointing and required entirely different strategies from the rest of the game. The ending was annoying and left way too many questions open.TL;DR (re)play Bastion instead."
