,Recommended,237930,24384361,"Posted: 17 July, 2016",all,ThisThing,"Yea I had just beaten Bastion and went to purhase this and to my luck it was on 80% sale or something. To counter that I realized I'd just spent 14 on Bastion 2 days earlier... Kewl.The game is just as deep as Bastion, if not more. Great graphics and art, nice music (even though I had my radio on in the BG), nice combat and the controls just works wonders. I had zero issues with wonky controls or anything, which was the same case with Bastion. Great and polished work. Do note, that while you might catch some familiarity with Bastion, this game is VERY different and that might put you off at first, but after 3-4 battles, you'll love it.The game is sadly EXTREMELY short. I picked up on my progress, by looking at how many skills and limits I had, and was surprised, that I was soon to beat the game. It made me a bit sad, but all I can say is that I was very entertained, from start to finish.The combat is very fun and can be performed in endless ways. If you get tired of your current playstyle, just shift and mix up your skills, to make a new playstyle. Nice and refeshing mechanic. It can however, stand out as overwhelming and confusing to begin with, yet you just have to battle a bit, read a bit of info, that is in the skill's description and you are good to go.While I really liked Bastion's extra content, such as getting memoirs, weapon tests and wave battles, Transistor offers this through repeated gameplays. You will most likely have to do a second run, in order to get all the extra stuff and steam achievements. Don't worry though, they are actually pretty fun. If you liked Bastion's, then you'll like Transistor's extra stuff. Though I must admit Bastion had alot more.That being said hurry up and buy, it really is a steal at this price. Other than that if you liked Bastion, or like Games, then you will enjoy this short, but very good and re-playable game."
