,Recommended,237930,11140524,"Posted: 8 July, 2014",all,Splan RIP Cassini 1997-2017,"Following the critically-acclaimed Bastion, Supergiant Games have released Transistor, an incredibly dynamic and quirky Single-Player Cyber-RPG. I picked this up during the Summer Sale, owing to my love of Bastion, and boy was I right when I thought this would be good - if not better- than Bastion itself. I finished my first play through in just over 7 hours, but a Recursion mode offers a New Game+ that shows me a further challenge in the same idyllic environment. Set in a Cyber-esque city called Cloudbank, A group called the Camerata try to assassinate the famous singer Red, with a weapon known as the Transistor; a sword that turns the personality of the person killed by it into a weapon. They miss, but take her voice, and as you journey through Cloudbank, fighting your way to the Camerata through their robotic minions - The Process, you slowly discover their plot to destroy the city. From minute one you are plunged into a dark and delicate storyline, starting next to an un-named corpse, The Transistor plunged through his chest, directing you to stopping the Camerata and The Process once and for all. Along the way you find the bodies of countless other victims of the Camerata, and with each one you begin to understand and unravel the mystery behind the storyline.The weapon system is unique; potentially the best I have ever seen. With a basic 4 equip slots, 4 unlockable passive slots and 2 potential upgrades for each equip, you are given a dynamic system that changes as you level up and find the corpses of the citizens of Cloudbank. Each combination of effects adds a new spin on an attack, which allows you to manipulate the battlefield in a variety of ways. Either via a real-time fight, or activating Turn(), a planning mode in which you can strategize where to move and attack in a split second, you can wreak havoc against your foes in a multitude of ways, be it with blinking around with a parasitic DOT heat-seeking- missile via Jaunt+Purge,  spawning robotic dogs that charm enemies to fight for you with Help+Charm, or going full frontal with a long-range slice that bounces between enemies and an AOE lifesteal  to boot with Breach+Bounce+Tap, the varieties in attacks are endless, although the system can be a bit clunky at times, due to heavy reliance on Turn() to survive later game thanks to its long cooldown. The Limiter system (a Brother-concept to the Shrine in Bastion) allows you to challenge yourself with extra difficulty for a %-based EXP reward. Each time you equip and fight with an ability in a equip, upgrade or passive slot, you learn more and more about each character, and how they got to be trapped inside, leaving you longing for more information about the city and its inhabitants.The Enemies of the game are varied, with Processes such as the Weed providing AOE heals for surrounding enemies while damaging you, Creeps proving a singular enemy an unbreakable force field, and Jerks slamming the ground in an everlasting oscillation that hits for huge damage to friend and foe, the game constantly varies how you must approach combat to make it an intuitive and responsive system. You unlock more information about them in a similar way to the abilities, by equipping them and reading the “Developer” notes on each subspecies unlocked after combat, with each entry detailed like a scientific report, describing the Camerata’s discoveries about the Process.However, this game isn't just about the fight, but the beauty and integrity of the plotline and setting. The artwork is fantastic, and each environment has its own little sparkle that shows the life that was once there, in each different way, From the portside in Goldwalk to the OVC terminals that allow you to order Junction Jan's famous Harvest garden or petition to change the sky blue to orange, the city is teeming with the sense of an artificial utopia-turned-wasteland by the hidden objective of the Camerata. And once again, Darren Korb composes a soundtrack that fits every minute detail of the stage you are in, sending riveting waves of emotion that combine and culminate with the colourful ambient lighting of the scene, giving you the ability to empathise with each soul captured within the Transistor, that allows you to understand the reasons for every action committed: a common, but often misconstrued effort at the improvement of Cloudbank, and the life of its citizens.Emotionally draining, Transistor is the game I have been waiting for from a Triple-A developer for years, but once again Supergiant Games have stepped up to the plate and shown how David can beat Goliath, and show him a few tricks too.Graphics: 9Music: 9Story: 10Combat: 9Character Development: 9Final Score: 46/50Verdict: Simply emotional, A Compelling storyline and beautiful setting make Transistor a game that will be remembered for years to come, and making fans increasingly wish for more Supergiant content with every passing day"
