,Not Recommended,237930,17598664,"Posted: 18 August, 2015",all,Ozons1,"Bought this game because I was fan of Bastion.If you can buy it while there is sales then sure, go for it. Otherwise I would really suggest thinking about it.Pros:+ Beautiful world (it felt ""artistic"")(Lots of beautiful scenes, could really imagine making wallpapers from them)+ Good music+ Narrator+ Skill upgrade system(We all know that feeling when we get new skill in game but it does not feel right for us or it is just really weak. In transistor even these skills can be used. You can upgrade your primary skills (using skills you do not use) or use them as passive bonuses (for example - extra damage, areal damage, shield, temporary clones and so on...)+ Death penalty(This is really good.  In transistor when you lose all your hp one of your skills (which you have equiped) gets discarded and you continue fighting with full hp, BUT you cant use this skill for set ammount of ""checkpoints"" (forgot the name, but basically small platforms in which you can customise your skills, if you die you need to discover 2-3 of them to get this skill back). In the meantime you can replace your discarded skill with other one. It makes players to experiment with most optimal skill set)Cons:- Fighting system(This is some kind of mix Bastion style of combat + turn base game. But action games aspect is a lot, lot weaker. Most of your encounters with enemy starts with position yourself in good place, activating ability which allows you to set limited count of steps (example - I go here, use this skill on enemy 3 times then retreat) and then you execute it. After that you usually cant use any skill at all (if you havent used 1 skill as upgrade, then you can use that all the time), so you just try to survive 4-5seconds and repeat. There is no use for fighting in ""real ""time"" because most of the time enemies are faster and hit pretty hard and most of your attacks takes a lot time to charge, so they just dodge it)- Story, ending(Wont spoil it, but it just didnt feel interesting. I barely had any attachment for our main hero and her sword or world at all. One of few elements I liked were the terminals in the game in which you get small info about world or get chance to vote about something, but the rest of story was... Just meh. Ending was dissapointing, maybe I didnt get the message which game developers wanted to deliver, but right now by emotional impact this ending could be compared to COD but without any kind of accomplishemnt)- Limiters(Limiters in transistor = Idols in bastion. You activate them to get bonus xp. In this way you can get more challenging enemies which make game more interesting and increase gameplay time. BUT, there is always but, limiters felt or I should better say were ""unfair"". I played this game 1 time and started new game+ so i had bunch of them. But I really could justify using only 2 of them (which gave in total 4%xp boost). Do you really think it is fair getting only 2-4%xp boost for activating limiter which increase enemies damage 2 times or give shield for their ""cells"" (you defeat enemy, he drops cell, if you dont destroy it fast enought the enemy will respawn back).  Yes limiters make encounters more challening, but as wrote before fighting system wasnt really that good)Transistor isn't a bad game, but if you hoped for a fast pace action game with good story then you will feel dissapointed. Characters felt weak (or at least not interesting), story - meh, combat slow.  But otherwise it is beautiful game with great music.If I had bought it for full price I would feel dissapointed but Summer Sales take care of that."
