,Not Recommended,237930,18216876,"Posted: 27 September, 2015",all,Ksempac,"As a game studio, when your first game is something as good as Bastion, it's a tough act to follow. And as a player, it's also tough to not constantly compare the two games, even if Transistor is not a sequel to Bastion. Unfortunately, that comparison only highlights the weaknesses of Transistor, which might be a decent game, but is severely below Bastion.The greatest part of Transistor is the story. I think the game shouldn't have started ""in media res"", because it makes for a confusing beginning, but once you start to get all the pieces of the puzzle, it all makes sense and paints an interesting picture. The world of Cloudbank is only hinted at, but it's an interesting, original world with interesting characters.However, it's a bit of a shame we mostly learn about theses people and that world through archive files, and that we have to go through a completely empty environment. For story-reasons that i will not spoil, the world of Transistor is empty. You will almost never encounter any life, only enemies. Bastion's world was a post-apocalyptic world, and yet, it was teeming with traces of past life, and also new forms of life. It was also very varied, with each level having it's own distinct feel and color scheme. In Transistor, every environment is a flat expense in the middle of the city, and all the levels look the same. Moreover though there are reasons that it's deserted, it's weird that you find absolutely no traces of previous life, or even a lone survivor to talk to.The fact that you won't meet anyone also creates another problem : the only ""person"" that your character, Red, meets, is her sword. At the beginning of the game, you grab the sword that was used to kill someone...and that someone has been absorbed by the sword, and is able to talk to you. I will not spoil who that person is, but he is gonna help Red survives her ordeal. However, Red lost her voice, and thus, the sword is the only one able to talk...and boy, he does talk a lot. The only voice you hear, offering advices, opinions, etc. He is supposed to be a friend, but since he is the only one talking constantly, and giving you advices constantly, it soon feels like he is just bossing you around. ""Go there, do that, etc."". An endless monologue, that is supposed to both guide the players, and help Red, and tell the story of the world...by being all that it just fails at everything, after a while that voice gets way too irksome, and you just want him to shut up.But enough with the atmosphere, and let's talk about the gameplay. Supergiant Games have created an original combat system. The game plays in real time, with an isometric view like Bastion offered. However, at any point, you have the possibility of stopping time. When you do it, it starts a ""turn"", with a tactical UI. Here you can plan your next actions as much as you want. Experiment with movements, attacks, and see the results. The only limit is the ""turn bar"", which depletes with each move or attack. Once you're satisfied with your plan, you go out of the tactical view, and all your actions executes as you wanted, while the rest of the game is almost stopped (it's not a total pause, but it's very close to). This gives you a tremendous advantage against your opponents, who only works in real time. However, once your action are done, you're not able to use turn until your ""turn bar"" is filled up again (which takes about 5s if you used all of it). Also, most of your attacks are disabled while the turn bar is filling up, which makes you very vulnerable. That makes for a different flow of combat that we're used and it's interesting to try it.This turns system is greatly enhanced by the ""function"" system of your sword. Your sword isn't a classic weapon. It has ""functions"", which you gain every time you level up. Most of them are for damage (such as Breach() which throws an arrow piercing enemies) but a few are purely for support like ""convert an enemy to your side"" or ""weaken an enemy"". You can only have 4 functions active at a time, but you can upgrade one function with up to two others, which will greatly change their effect. For example, you can have a function that damage and weaken an enemy at the same time and also makes you invisible for a few seconds. You can also equip up to 4 functions as global upgrades, which mean you're able to use up to 16 functions at the same time (4 attacks, upgraded with 2 functions each, and 4 global upgrades). On the whole, that function system is a great idea, because it allows you to customize your playstyle as you sit fit, and enhances the planning aspect of the game.So, a new tactical turn system + a very customizable attack system should make for great combat, right ? Well, it should, if the enemies were up to par. Unfortunately, that's where it completely falls apart. At the beginning of the game it feels like there are many enemies, each with their own role and way to screw you. However, the more you progress in the game, the more you will understand that they have the same strengths and weaknesses. Which mean that once you've found a function combo that works well, there is little incentive to switch to something else. The more levels and functions you gain, the more refined your ultimate combo will be, and the less incentive you will have to switch things up.If you're a tactical-minded player, it shouldn't be hard for you to find a great combo, and then spam it over and over again. There is none of the complexity of others tactical games, such as Tactical RPGs or western turn-based games. This is even more visible during the NewGame+, where enemies are totally unable to provide a challenge to your levelled up character. NewGame+ even randomizes the enemies, meaning they are even less tactically organized than they used to. Not that you care...every enemy is the same, a fodder for your unique combo.The game actually disincentive to try to switch things up. Bastion offered 10 idols that added 10 optional handicaps with greater rewards, to make it harder and more interesting for players who like being challenged. It really tasked you to get the most ouf of your weapons and really becomes better at the game. Transistor has a similar system, the ""Limiters"", but it fails to be as interesting as the idols. In truth, most of theses limiters are barely noticeable. I've been playing my NewGame+ with all 10 limiters, and barely feels the effect of them because I'm cruising through with my unique combo. However, one of them actually penalizes you for switching your functions in and out, which mean that if you have a combo that works, it's better to keep using it, than try playing with the function system.So the conclusion is unavoidable: When you're spamming the same combo over and over again, against enemies that feel the same, that can have only one issue : boredom. And that's definitely how i felt. There were a lot of times when i was playing and then after a while i was thinking ""i don't want to keep at it"", and just stopped playing. I forced myself to go through the game to be able to see the end of the wonderful story. And then i forced myself through NewGame+ to be sure i wasn't missing anything, and unfortunately, the more i played, the more i noticed the game's weaknesses.A great story with interesting characters can't save all by themselves a weak gameplay, especially since the irksome companion also fails to be as compelling as Bastion's narrator was."
,Not Recommended,237930,14162098,"Posted: 25 January, 2015",all,Atlas,"The game tries way too hard to be art. Every few seconds it desperately screams ""Hey, I'm a special snowflake, I am not like the others!"". In pursuit of delivering a unique product, Supergiant Games ended up with mix of random creative mishmash that don't work well together. Their artists and musicians are talented, but the game is only good on screenshots."
76561198071689614,Not Recommended,237930,16466132,"Posted: 17 June, 2015",all,Mystic Exarch,"This game is made by Supergiant, the company that made Bastion. I expected similar quality with this game but it's not even close.First of all, the naration is awful. Yes, it's the same voice actor but he doesn't do anywhere near as good a job as in Bastion. He delivers lines without any passion and just doesn't have the same charm. Plus, you can barely hear him because he is really quiet even on max volume.In Bastion he explains what's going on, gives you the background information of the story, and tells the story gradually as you play it. It was really fun to learn about the lore and listen to him tell the story. And the best part was, you get to actually play the game while doing it. In this way there is a perfect blend of action and storytelling.All of this is missing in Transistor. The narrator just makes a bunch of dumb general comments that barely have anything to do with what's going on. He doesn't give you any background information about the setting, explain the lore, or tell the story. You just wander around in a city, feeling confused without even the most basic context or narrative. I've played for several hours and have no clue what's going on. When you take away the story, really all you have is a bunch of combat. Which wouldn't be too bad by itself, except for the fact that the combat sucks.The main problem is that the combat is not only WAY too hard, but also severely flawed. Your character is etremely weak and can die in about two seconds from enemy fire. You can mitigate this by using the turn feature. Basically, you can pause the game and issue orders to your character. When you unpause, she carries the orders out while all the other enemies are frozen. It's not as broken as it sounds. When your turn is over, every single one of your abilities is on cooldown until turn recharges, meaning that you can't use them. Which means you are defenseless after using your turn. So basically the game is use your turn so you can actually kill stuff, and then run away and try not to die for 5 seconds. This is a lot harder than it sounds and is also just boring to do.In addition, when you kill an enemy a battery pops out. You have to run to it pick it up in 5 seconds or the enemy respawns with FULL HEALTH. On top of this, it's even shielded from damage and you have to damage the shield to be able to pick it up. When you use up your turn to kill an enemy, you oftentimes cannot break the shield on the battery because you can't attack yet, and so the enemy respawns with full health.It wouldn't be so bad if there were actually a difficulty slider. Or like in Bastion, you can do challange areas to gain upgrades if you're having a hard time. Instead, the challenge rooms give music tracks as a reward. Seriously?So essentially it's a game with no story and ridiculously hard/flawed gameplay.I expected the soundtrack to be amazing like in Bastion, but again this game doesn't deliver. The soundtrack isn't very unique, it sounds like generic video game music. And you don't get to hear it anyway because the music turns off when using your turn feature. What a bummer.Oh and this game doesn't have a start menu or anything. Literally, the most basic feature in video games is missing.The only reedming feature could be the graphics I guess. The enviorments are absolutely beautiful, just like Bastion. However, a game needs to provide solid gameplay and a story and can't get by with just fancy visuals. That's why they're called ""games"". If you want good art, go to a museum or watch a movie.There is also only about 5 hours of gameplay. It took me that long to beat it. But even then, the game time was artificially inflated because of difficulty. It would probably be like 3 or 4 hours if you are skilled at action games.TL/DR: No story, bad narration, flawed/ridiculously hard gameplay, lack of features, poor soundtrack."
,Not Recommended,237930,16752669,"Posted: 27 June, 2015",all,HSuke,"I bought this game because I loved Bastion. Its witty narrator and gorgeous soundtrack were simply amazing. So I was quite surprised that none of the things that made Bastion a great game are present in Transistor.- The narrtor came off as a bland and diatribe. In fact, the voice acting of all characters was really lifeless. I realize the city is rotten and dying, but having a lifeless narrator destroys the game.- Your character's singing doesn't match the background music. More importantly, the soundtrack doesn't match gameplay.- The gameplay itself was boring. I absolutely hated how slow my character walked around. Combat is tedious and not well-balanced.- There's not much of a story. Whatever barebones tale Transistor attempt to tell didn't make much sense. By the end of the game, I didn't care for a single character. It wasn't like the ending of Bastion, where I was nearly heartbroken when character X dropped everything to save character Y."
