76561198075541199,Not Recommended,237930,28484966,"Posted: 20 December, 2016",all,_myon,"Sadly, this game is not as memorable as Bastion.Visually, the game is very beautiful. The narrative technique is as good as it gets. The music is great as you might expect from this developer. The story is okay. But the game is let down by its overly-complex combat system and its corresponding configuration UI.The game makes no (zero!) effort at introducing you to the complex customizations that are possible. It uses a lot of jargon that it doesn't explain and an absurdly complex UI that is completely non-obvious. I actually had to watch a youtube video explaining it after I managed to re-arrange my abilities in a way that made sure I could no longer kill enemies. Oops?Finishing the game felt like a chore as I button-mashed my way through enemies. Eventually, I kinda-sorta figured out how to use the battle mechanics to string together some combos but by then the game was ending.(Not as big a deal, but I found the default controls to be unplayable. The auto-cast option was a disaster that contributed a lot to the button-mash-and-pray playstyle I used for the first half of the game. I highly recommend turning it off.)The combat system is notbadonce you understand it, but its complexity isn't warranted for a game of its length (which took me 4 hours, skipping the trial rooms). This game would be much more enjoyable on a second playthrough.I don't recommend the game if you don't have the patience to learn an intricate combat system for a very short game. You'll probably like this if you liked Bastion, though."
