,Not Recommended,237930,16575068,"Posted: 20 June, 2015",all,Thermohaline,"I am very sad to not recommend this game as the gameplay, art direction, and overall design is as solid as it gets.I was  a bit dissappointed that exploring the maps was not rewarded like it was in Bastion. Especially where choice is a theme emphasized by the OVC terminals.Unfortunately, the plot leaves something to be desired. I don't want spoil the whole plot but,I can't resisit writting a large amount of information in the blacked-out ""spoiler space"" to make it seem like I am.  I really love the suprise beginnig and the late plot twists.  I really, really liked the villans.  They were well-developed, myopic, and good-intentioned citizens thinking they had the ""greater good"" in mind.  But the Romeo+Juliet finish is a bit much for me.  Romance was not sufficiently integrated to the plot.  The sum total of the plot was about high society dealings, cult-driven terrorism, and individual ambitions over status quo.  The ending was about irrational love.  If they wanted a love-theme they should have emphasized that rather than these other, competing themes.It really bothered me that they chose to emphasize the ""choice"" theme via the OVC terminals.  Only, in the end to not really choose the way that SuperGiant gave you a choice last time.One last thing: HOLES. Gaping holes in how the protagonist(s) got ~100 blocks from the empty set to the scene where she first draws out the transistor.  Never explain how they ""took Red's voice"", or why she never gets it back, never adequate information for conjecture of where Breaker came from, etc.Please don't get me wrong, I don't dislike this game beacuse it ""isn't Bastion"". I dislike this game beacuse they didn't use the same compositional techniques of theme integration that leads the player to a satisfying conclusion that fits the plot in all the right ways.If you feel that plot stuff is not part of your gaming experience, then by all means, dig in.  It is  a fun action/puzzle challlenge in a moving sci-fi utopia gone-wrong atmosphere."
