76561198168346778,Not Recommended,237930,35352774,Posted: 30 September,all,Atrushan,"I wish I could recommend this game. I loved ""Bastion"" and I really tried to like Transistor, but it's just not nearly as good.The biggest issue is the story. It's way too vague and confusing to make heads or tails. The motives of the characters are unclear and so is the whole setting and what's happening around.How are you supposed to care about anything if the game doesn't give you enough information to begin with? However that's not the only problem. If you want to gather even the flimsiest of hints about the story, you have to switch the ability positions (and therefore their effect). That may sound innovative at first, but in truth it just prevents you from having any working combination at all for most of the time.Speaking of abilities: If you happen to lose, the fight will just continue but the game locks one of your very few skills until you get to the next save point. And having to fight (and win) with your main ability disabled is... just as fun as it sounds: annoying.With the story and battle system ruled out, what's left of the game? A decent running time (didn't feel short), nice music and a good ""narrator"" doing the commentary. At the bottom line it's not much and even though I bought it on discount, I feel like both my money and time were wasted."
,Not Recommended,237930,35397905,Posted: 1 October,all,chum dumpster,"There's a lesson to be learned from Transistor (or at least i tell myself that so I don't feel like I completely wasted the 5 bux I spent on in). See, it's no longer enough to simply look at reviews for a game and focus simply on the percentage of positive reviews; that's the mistake I made. When an indie game is Overwhelmingly Positive like Transistor is, you've got to put in a bit of work by going down and reading some of the top reviews. If you find a lot of people jerking off over how ""emotionally breathtaking"" the game is, or calling it ""an experience for the soul"" or some such garbage, without anyone saying the gameplay was really cool or fun, understand that the game is almost guaranteed to be pretentious trash that only appeals to obnoxious dickweeds. In Transistor's case specifically, I kept seeing reviews for this game where people would recommend it despite admitting they didn't understand the story OR the gameplay before they finished the game. How dense do you have to be to play through an entire game without knowing what the ♥♥♥♥ you're doing and then turn around and say it's good?The gameplay is confusing and bad, the story sucks, and every single character is annoying. Special regards to the support character (a sword) who literally never shuts up and speaks every line in an annoying hushed whisper of a voice. Try playing this game without getting irritated by him, i DARE you. It's got some nice art, sure, but do you want to pay $5-20 so you can admire a couple pictures in a video game? If so, what the ♥♥♥♥ is wrong with you?Oh, and you can legitimately beat the game in 3-5 hours, too (I did it in 2.6, apparently, but I obviously just wanted it to be over so I could say I finished it). If you want to dismiss my other critiques because they knocked the beret off your fat head, fine; but the game is super short and has no real replay value. There's no defending that."
,Not Recommended,237930,13962416,"Posted: 12 January, 2015",all,Kurosawa-Fan,"It pains me to write a negative review about something that I had anticipated for quite some time, but there are a few aspects about Transistor that irritate the hell out of me. I wasn't as smitten by developer Supergiant's previous game Bastion as some others, but the game was aesthetically beautiful and its mechanics, whilst simple, worked when paired with the often interesting narrative.But Transistor is a swing and a miss this time around. Of course it looks and sounds beautiful, its unique visuals and haunting soundtrack being two of the game's biggest pluses, but that's where it ends. The story - well, what story, really? Honestly, the story seems to be deliberately vague as if that alone invites interest, but it's more infuriating than intriguing. I haven't finished the game yet, so perhaps this is a moot point, but the way the story is dished out to you isn't compelling me to finish the game any time soon. The world itself is innovative, but so sparsely populated that at no point does it feel truly immersive.The combat system is initially interesting, given that you can play in a quasi-turn based style or real time, but after a few fights the flaws become apparent. The skill pairing and upgrade system is a little confusing at first, at least in my opinion, and I found that you ultimately rely on one or two attacks for most of your battles. Most fights end up being repetitive and dull. You move from zone to zone, from one fight to another in tightly contained areas, scarcely interacting with the world. There are some cut-scenes, quizzes and bits of text that are presented to you from time to time which I assume are meant to give us more information about the world, but Transistor falls into the same trap that a lot of games do with regards to world-building, which is that it tells us rather than shows us what we want or need to know.Plus to add insult to injury, the narrator's voice simply rubs me the wrong way. Perhaps it's the delivery, the tone, or the echo-ey effect given to the sword, but I found it simply grates.Transistor is a weird blend of okay-but-hardly-revelatory fight mechanics and a barely interesting story. It looks and sounds beautiful (if you ignore the narration) but is nowhere nearly as compelling as Bastion was. I absolutely wanted to like it more than I did, and given all the overwhelmingly positive reviews for this I guess I must be missing something, but in the end I felt let down by its mechanics and narrative. I will play it to the end, but am in no rush to do so.PROS:+ unique and gorgeous art style+ beautiful, moody music+ combat system tries something different with its blend of real-time/turn-based strategyCONS:- repetitive fights- confusing skill system- dull, deliberately obtuse story and weak world-building (though the world itself is fascinating in its own right)- narrator's voice (for me) gets on the nerves"
