,Not Recommended,237930,15590502,"Posted: 27 April, 2015",all,TheFinkinator,"Here is the most important thing I can say about Transistor:IF YOU ARE THINKING ABOUT BUYING THIS BECAUSE YOU LOVED BASTION, THINK AGAINNow that I've made that point, the rest of this review is just well thought out, analytic fluff.I had such high hopes for transistor. Bastion was a masterpiece. This game has great art just like its older sibling, and while the soundtrack cant touch Bastion's, all of the tracks that include lyrics are still pretty good, though all the ones that dont include a voice are painfully forgettable.  A game doesnt have to have an award winning soundtrack like Bastion, but if I put four long hours into a game, and then after listening to the soundtrack cant recognize ONE track, then you did something wrong.Transistor is based around a very good idea, but one that was executed poorly. The battle system revolves around the main plot device - Your talking sword, which has reality warping capabilities, namely slowing down time. You choose up to four attacks to use, and customize them with a very sophistcated system that Ill explain later, and with one attack assigned to each face button on the controller, you can attack at will. But doing this will inevitably get you killed. The only way to win, and what the game encourages you to do, is to use the time slowing power I mentioned.To do battle, (and there are A LOT of them), you press the trigger to initiate Turn() which stops time. You have an action meter at the top of the screen that will slide down as you do actions like walking or attacking. When it reaches 0 you cant do anything else. Then you hit the trigger again and watch as the main character Red does all the moves you did super fast before enemies can react.This is where it starts to go bad.After you execute all your attacks, the Turn() meter has to refill. While it is refilling, you can do NOTHING. Let me explain how much sense this makes. Like I said, when you are in battle, you can attack at will, as much as you want, and it doenst affect the action meter at all. But after you use the Turn() function, NOW ALL OF A SUDDEN, the lack of a full action meter is preventing your attacks from working. It goes further than that though.Youre defenseless (theres ONE attack that can be used during this recharge period. and attacks can also be equipped to other attacks as modifiers. so this can be equipped to let you use any ONE attack during recharge. Ill get back to that.), in a field of enemies that generally move faster than you do, with no run function. So youre going to take damage. And since there are no health restoring items, other than two horrible health regen abilities late in the game, youre eventually going to die. And what happens when you die?YOU LOSE AN ATTACK. YEAH.Like I said, you get to pick four attacks. Whenever your life drops to 0, you lose the ability to use one of those attacks for a while. lose all four, you have to restart at the last save point. How does the game decide which attack you lose? You lose the attack that takes up the most memory first. Better attacks take more memory, and equipping modifiers or buffs to an attack increases the memory it takes up. long story short, you lose your best attacks first.AND, because like I said earlier, you can use attacks during the recharge period if you equip this specific attack to them, chances are that attack is going to have high memory, and thats the one youre going to lose first. The one attack you have to defend yourself during recharge is the first one they take from you.It gets worse.How long do you lose these attacks? Until you access TWO save points. TWO. You would think that if you lost one of only 4 attacks that you have, you would regain them at the end of the battle if you won. But no. You need to reach a checkpoint...AND THEN ANOTHER ONE. So you reach that first checkpoint, and swap out your best attacks that you lost for the ♥♥♥♥♥♥ ones you never use. Then you die because you dont have your best attacks and lose more attacks, then you get your best attacks back at the next save point, only to have to replace the second best attacks you just lost with more♥♥♥♥♥♥Who ever heard of a game where you reach a checkpoint that didnt heal your wounds? EVEN DARK SOULS ISNT THAT CRUEL.Think about that. EVEN DARK SOULS doesnt say, ""oh, you can use your souls to level up, but you have to get to the NEXT bonfire if you want to regain health and refill your estus.""So lets do a quick recap to finish this up:1. The game wants you to use the Turn() function to fight, and its basically impossible to win without it2. Using Turn(), doing EXACTLY what the game wants, rewards you by putting you in a defenseless situation where your bound to take damage eventually.3. When you die because you played the game correctly, you lose access to your best attack, and have to fight maybe 3-5 more battles before you can get them back. good luck not dying until then!Ive never ever played a game like Transistor. One where I honestly, 100% felt like I was being punished for doing exactly what the game wanted me to do. Imagine if in Dark Souls (thats just on my mind today), when you hit a boss with your weapon, it caused you to lose souls.I mean its just really poor game design. And I had such high hopes. SuperGiant did such good work on bastion, and there was such potential for Transistor, but it was just put together all wrong.And I even teared up a bit over the story. The game looked and sounded great. But the gameplay was so horrible that I couldnt overlook it. And if you knew me, the fact that I said that would be all it took to turn you away from this game."
