,Not Recommended,237930,30410439,Posted: 9 March,all,Kryyss,"In 2007, it was revealed the winner of that years world cricket tournement would be presented with a diamond studded cricket ball with gold trim estimated to be worth $68500. If you've haven't seen pictures of it then go take a look because it is really quite a stunning peice of craftsmanship and artistic design - it is also completely useless and could never be used to play cricket with. Transistor is that cricketball in every way.Visually Transistor is visually stunning. Gorgeous to look at with a distinctive art-style that clearly had a ton of work put into it. The audio design is pleasing with some great voice acting that puts a wierd spin on the 1920s era with some Tron-esque elements. Unfortunately, the same effort didn't go into the game itself as it is clunky, tedious, short and not at all engaging. How anyone could consider this a good game boggles my mind because I heard of this game from a number of sources as being a great indie title but clearly these people were either bamboozled by the visuals or they have limited experience with this type of game.In terms of how it works, its a strange mix of real-time and turn-based combat. You can pause the game to chain up lightning fast attacks and movement but when you have used your allocated chunk of time you have to wait for your turn-bar to recharge. During this time you have to run around avoiding attacks or use your abilities that quite often root you to the spot so its better to avoid attacking during this time. As such, it would be a mistake to call this an action-rpg at all. The trouble is that causes combat to move in fits and starts and the limited size of the areas you are contained in during these battles means that tactics really are shallow at best. The ability to mix functions (the games method creating attacks and abilities) is initially interesting but since it doesn't have a distinct offense/defense/support design you are left with all attacks - either ranged, melee or summons. As you can imagine, this means the appeal of this system quickly wears off as you realize your choices only impact the distance at which you need to engage threats.Speaking of the 'threats'. The game has no memorable encounters. Enemies lack personality and are very limited in variety. There are some 'bosses' but these are just damage sponges rather than being difficult to defeat due to clever design. As I said, all the effort went into the look of the game and the game itself was left as an afterthought causing it to become a tedious and boring mess partly due to how plain the combat is and also due to how it is so linear as you progress from area to area with the game leading you by the nose. So it even lacks any meaningful replay value.All in all, I could never recommend this game even on sale. It is a diamond ball of eye-candy without substance to its gameplay or the storyline."
,Not Recommended,237930,12769071,"Posted: 3 November, 2014",all,not rip,"tl;dr: plays like a puzzler with cool mechanics, amazing art+music, but a really detracting attempt at a plotI bought Transistor upon the recommendation of a friend and the overwhelming number of glowing reviews it had. I was expecting a really amazing game, but after having finished the game, my opinion is that it is just a textbook example of style over substance.  Don't get me wrong – the artwork is amazing and immersive, the music is exceptionally well done (sans the lyrics), the combat system is interesting and very enjoyable (if not occasionally glitchy). But otherwise... there's nothing here. The entirety of the attempt at a plot is literally just incohesive narration about how some people tried to change everything and it all went wrong. Nothing is actually ever explained, no real motives are revealed (unless you count ""We just wanted to change the city for the better!"" as a strong motive), and character development never happens. Places are talked about and then visited (but then it's just a level that looks like any other level), enemies are mentioned and then killed, people are vaguely discussed and then, well, suffice it to say that you literally learn nothing after you meet them.It's really a pity because by silencing the player and forcing them to accept information only through narration and environment interaction, Supergiant Games has full control over the player, being able to make the player believe and feel whatever they want the player to (think Portal-style, for instance). Instead, they completely wasted the opportunity, delivering nothing of substance through any of the channels of storytelling available to them. You never feel anything or root for any characters in this game. I saw another review that likened this game to just a puzzler, and I fully agree.The failed attempt at a plot was by far the biggest flaw of the game, but I'd like to point out some other things that could have been improved:The voiceover is interesting at first, but quickly becomes really annoying (this is mostly a side effect of there being no plot to narrate). It basically alternates between rambling about how cool the protagonist is/was, and contempt and confusion about what the antagonists are doing. It narrates and comments on your actions, too, which is amusing until you hate the narrator. The two things it doesn't do are 1. say anything useful or 2. effect emotion in the player, which are things I think narrators in games should do.The artwork is unique, laying out a steampunk-ish twist in a digital setting and executing it really well. Unfortunately, the designers forgot the other aspect of game art, which is differentiation. With the exception of a plot-spoiling feature, *all the levels look the same*. It's ridiculous. There is so little differentation between the player's regular neighbourhood and the supposedly luxurious and lavish residences of the rich bad guys that I didn't realize how close I was to said bad guys until I was in the same room with them. There were only two levels whose artwork stood out to me as really well designed: the opera house, and the dark walkway near the end.That's all. I'm including a lot of superfluous details because although reviews are meant for people who haven't played the game, they're primarily judged for merit by those who have, so oddly enough those are the people I have to convince of my opinion. Cool medium-length puzzler. No plot. Possibly not worth your money, and definitely not worth universal acclaim."
