,Not Recommended,237930,11498418,"Posted: 31 July, 2014",all,[Mar] Lux,"This is an amazing, beautiful, and powerful game. Once.The problem with this game is that it becomes very, very clear that there's a specific way the game wants you to play (by using the Turn() system). And that isn't always the fun way to play the game. At times, the game seems to want you to just go all out in a massive battle royale, but after the first ten minutes of the game that's always going to get you killed, or at the very leastreduced to limping along with only a few of the functions you dislike the most.The various trial-mode challenges do a little too good a job of explaning to the player several strategies that can destroy just about everything (Crash+Void, Crash+Void, Crash+Void, get behind them, CULL). Later on in the game, it gets pretty apparent that you won't ever need to take another approach to a target and can proceed as normal.The story is really hard to follow at times, and actually wants for an exposition dump somewhere. Yeah, they intend for the story to be a mystery that's revealed to you bit by bit, and for you to play it again to take a fresh look at things in NG+, but that's not a lot of an excuse when it's a chore just to figure out who the people are you're going after and what the hell happened in the first place, or even anything about the setting itself. I feel like this is a rare case where ""the hero has unexplained amnesia"" would actually benefit the story, because it would explain why so, so much is left for the player to puzzle together.All this having been said, the art direction, music, and voice acting is superb. Supergiant Games is still an absolutely top-notch studio in those regards, and boy do they know how to make a game beautiful.Also, if your favorite part of Bastion was upgrading weapons and playing with drinks in the Distillery, forget everything I've said above because the weapon system in Transistor is basically porn for people like you (and me, for the record).In most cases, though, wait for a Steam Sale. It's worth experiencing, but not at full price."
