76561198015569520,Not Recommended,237930,11969721,"Posted: 3 September, 2014",all,atreju,"Ничего не понял, какие-то роботы, куда-то надо бежать... Наркоманы сюжет писали. Бастион в разы лучше был."
,Not Recommended,237930,11534254,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Salacavalini,"If you loved Bastion and were looking forward to Transistor for ""more of the same"", you're going to be disappointed. I know I was.That being said, objectively speaking it's probably a solid enough experience. It's just a whole different type of beast, and I guess I didn't want different.Supergiant keeps up the whole pretty aesthetics and good music thing people like them for. Instead of floating islands with a pseudo-American-frontier vibe, you have a weird sci-fi city thing going on, and the music is more... clubby. Again, matter of preference here. It's nice to look at though.The combat was what ultimately made me dislike the game. Maybe I just never really figured it out properly, but if you can beat the game without figuring out what makes the combat system work, that's probably a failing of the game more than it is of the player. In any case, it's nothing at all like Bastion, which is kind of a repeating point for me I guess.Basically, there's three different phases of combat. Starting off, you have the whole real-time running around and smacking things. Unlike the Kid, Red has no means of self-defense like blocking or parrying, and has to rely on just running out of the way or using a teleport skill with a cooldown and recovery animation. The downside here is that enemy attacks are generally rapid-fire homing missiles with no wind-up, and they move faster than you. Unlike Bastion (lol), a no-damage run of Transistor is just plain impossible, the game is designed with the idea that you WILL be taking damage no matter what - this becomes obvious as you notice several design choices which I will not go into detail for here.Red's attacks are also incredibly slow and sluggish, with long wind-up and recovery animations, during which enemies will happily dart about at high speeds to either dodge your telegraphed attack or take potshots at your exposed healthbar - it feels like YOU'RE the clumsy exploitable enemy and they're the nimble players. There's a couple of exceptions, but these skills tend to do abysmal damage.Now, there's also Turn() mode, which is... well, it's not a turn-based combat system toggle, this isn't Arcanum. It's basically a fancy timestop thing during which you have a set limit of actions you can queue up - movement, attacks, etc. Mixing up different attacks lets you use up the gauge more efficiently. It also shows helpful little tips like projectile trajectories and estimated damage output. Once you're happy, you can end Turn() mode and Red will zip about performing the commands you gave her in rapid succession.There's a few problems with Turn() mode too. For starters, the damage/trajectory indicators aren't exactly accurate. Not only do enemies still move (albeit very slowly) while Red zips about, making it very possible to miss completely, sometimes the damage estimates predict a kill but for one reason or another this doesn't happen. The opposite can happen too, resulting in unpredictable cases of overkill. Projectile trajectories can be inaccurate due to Turn() being somewhat poor at estimating obstacles in their paths. Still, all that aside, Turn() is your ace, letting you actually kill things without having to waddle amidst a horde of enemies in realtime as they whittle away at your health by being faster and stronger than you.And then comes the real stinker, the one combat phase that completely ruins any possible fun for me. The Turn() cooldown phase. This phase is basically the time it takes for the Turn() bar to fill back up, and can vary depending on how much of it you used up in the first place. Doesn't sound too bad, right? Well, you also cannot use any skills other than a select few non-offensive ones during this phase, meaning all you can do is run away from enemies that are faster than you and shoot rapid-fire homing missiles. Did I mention the enemies also destroy cover as they shoot it?There are ways to make some aspects of the combat less terrible, but they're often mutually exclusive for various reasons. Want to make an attack usable during cooldown? Just slot Jaunt() into it. What's Jaunt() normally do? Why, it's the teleport skill, which is your only means of evasion beyond ""a brisk jog"". Yeah, skill modifiers and passives are the same things as your attacks, just depending on where you slot them, so you have to compromise the hell out of your setup.Real-time combat rapidly becomes non-viable as you reach the lategame. NG+ is right out. It basically just devolves into running around like a headless chicken until Turn() is ready, assassinating one enemy (you will not do enough damage to kill multiples in one Turn()) and repeating until the encounter is over. It's tedious and not fun. Certain enemies even counter your Turn() power by obfuscating vision in Turn(), or - one of the earliest enemies in the game does this - teleporting away after the first hit, making you whiff the rest. No, there's no way to predict where they'll teleport to and aim the next hits accordingly....Maybe I got a little ranty in the end there, but honestly, I regret buying Transistor. I didn't have fun with it, I didn't enjoy the combat system at all, it was awfully short and the plot was dumb. The story never explains anything and ends with a pretty bad anticlimax of a solution. You might have some fun with it if you play on a low difficulty - it has Limiters which work like Idols did in Bastion, although this too isn't done as well as one of them did literally nothing until it was patched, and several are barely noticeable while others cripple you excessively - but I honestly doubt I'll be able to bring myself to finish NG+. Not because it's too hard - I beat the base game by using all the limiters I had available and NG+ just amounts to ""more/stronger enemies"" - but because I have actually enjoyable games I could be playing instead."
76561197991088572,Not Recommended,237930,26637904,"Posted: 16 November, 2016",all,FuzzyPat,"The main premise of the mechanics - that all ""weapons"" (all named as if they are programming functions) can also be used as modifiers for other weapons, applying some trait that is reminiscent of its effect as a weapon, or can be slotted to gain some sort of personal passive buff related to the function's use as a weappon - is interesting, but needs some refinement before I would call it successfully implemented.  The game drowns you in options.  I'm not that far into the game, but with the 9 functions I have collected so far, the number of possible combinations, between 4 weapon slots, 5 modifier slots between those, and 1 passive slot, is mind-numbingly large.  I understand wanting to encourage experimentation, but I feel like I've been put to work at one of Thomas Edison's laboratories, expected to iterate through every possible permutation to try and find the best one.  Which you have to do, because the penalty for not being optimal is apparently ludicrously high.  I would be fine with not every combination of functions slotted as weapons, modifiers, and passive buffs being equally as powerful or useful, but during my play I have more than once barely made it through a fight after losing multiple lives.Which is its own problem, because the functions *are* your lives.  Every time you get knocked to 0 life one of your functions gets burned out, and cannot be used until you've made it to a specfied number of ""Access Points"", which makes it impossible to do anything like experiment when half of the things you're trying to learn how to use are unusable for large stretches of the game.  All because you hadn't found the magic formula when you turned the corner and bumped into the next wave of dudes.In a game that seems bound and determined to force you to try new combinations over and over and over again, you would think the game would allow for the reallocation of functions whenever you wanted, but this is not the case with Transistor.  Remember those ""Access Points"" I referred to earlier?  Those are the only places you can modify your loadout.  This, combined with the game forcing you to finish every combat by locking you into a sort of arena for every confrontation, which never seems to include one of these Access Points, you have better hope your build is optimal for what you're facing, otherwise you're going to be stuck using unfamiliar functions to try and eek your way through the next few combats, so that you can hopefully get to enough access points to get the original list of functions back.  Only *then* can you try experimenting, making modifications to your original build to try and find out why that pack of dudes you ran into turned you into mincemeat, and what changes you might make to keep yourself out of the grinder next time.I am sure I could go online and watch a few hours of poorly edited youtube video explaining how everything works, and maybe afterwards be able to piece together something that works for me.  Also, I am sure I could find a few fan-made wikis for the game, and after trying to read through them find out enough information about function effects and combinations to be able to better optimize my build.  Never mind that it is poor game design to force someone to *leave the game* to figure out how to play said game, it is even worse to force them out of your game just so they can learn how to get through the game.In short, the game has too many possible combinations of weapons, modifiers, and passives, and the penalty for a less-an-optimal combination is too steep, limiting access to the main story behind a wall of senseless experimentation and iteration.  I remember hearing it said that the developer's previous game, Bastion, lacked interesting gameplay, in part due to a lack of options available for weapons and abilities.  I fear that my ptoblems with this game stem from the devs' response to this criticism, and I feel it only makes this game worse, swinging wildly far past the point of balance, making the gameplay tedious and boring.  Maybe they could have solved this by giving you the option of letting the game pick a loadout for you.  It wouldn't need to be the best of all possible combinations, but if it were, say, at the midpoint of the optomization spectrum for the next encounter, you coukld not only go into the next fight/set of fights not only knowing what you might need to get through them, but also be given hints as to what awaits, allowing the player to try and infer how to use these assigned tools to win the next encounter.  Instead, you have to hit up youtube and the vast stacks of Wikia just to get through the damn game.In the face of this, I cannot in good conscience suggest anyone purchase this game."
