76561198007633209,Not Recommended,237930,10213151,"Posted: 23 May, 2014",all,Leethus,"Summary: Disappointing as an RPG. The gameplay is interesting and noteworthy, but the story is wasted.Start with the good stuff: Gameplay. The combat system sounds interesting at first, but ends up being a bit dull for a while. By the time you're 2-3 hours in, and have a good variety of abilities to choose from, things turn around and it gets pretty fun. I'm sure there are people who specced completely different from me, and it's interesting to play around with all the skills to see what you can get away with. In this respect, Transistor reminds me of games like Valkyrie Profile and Resonance Of Fate, other RPGs with combat systems that seem kind of awkward and disjointed at first, but reward you greatly as you get the hang of it and learn their intricacies (though Transistor is not as deep as either of those games).Now the bad: The game completely lost me on the story, though. It seems a bit open to interpretation, and things are never clearly explained to you. This *can* be done in an interesting way (I love a good mystery as much as anyone), but I had no emotional investment or attachment to anyone or anything that occurred in this game in the slightest. There's no character development whatsoever, just a couple random details about people, most of whom are pretty inconsequential. That leaves you with a disjointed, unexplained, and irrelevant world. I was never given a reason to care about the fate of the city, Red, or the Transistor.The music didn't really strike me, either. It's not bad, but having recently played through Child Of Light and To The Moon, two games that definitely made me take notice of their music, I'm disappointed with Transistor's soundtrack, especially considering the praise that other reviews have been lauding upon it.I feel like I'm missing something, because everyone else seems to love this game. I went in expecting to love it, but ended up waiting for a revelation that never came."
