76561198005772592,Not Recommended,237930,10271188,"Posted: 28 May, 2014",all,Awsumpossum,"Keep in mind, I have only played this game for 2 hours, but this has been my experience so far.I never played Bastion, so I wasn't won over by the hype of Transistor and I wasn't jaded at all by my experience with Bastion.  I entered Transistor with a relatively open-mind, but I quickly realized the game just wasn't for me.  It isn't necessarily bad, it's just not great.What does the game do well?  People like the art, the music, and the story.  Some, though more rare, even like the gameplay.  To those who fall in those categories I say, ""Eh, they're alright"".Sure, the hand-drawn atmosphere is impressive, but is it impressive because it is hand-drawn or is it impressive because...well, the graphics are truly impressive?  In my opinion, it's the former.  Is the story good?  Some people love the narrator style-driven story.  For me, it was mostly annoying.  Parts of it were cool, the parts that felt like the narration was actually telling a coherent story, but most of the time your sword is just babbling which eventually becomes kind of annoying.   The way you unlock elements of the story is neat [by using combinations of abilities in combat]; unfortunately, in order to successfully do this, you're forced to play with combinations of abilities that you might not enjoy.  So, is it a pro or a con?  I don't know, make up your own mind.Why would I not recommend the game?  Well, for one, combat was weak.  There are basically like 4-5 skins of monsters through the majority of the game that you just continuously fight over and over and over.  Once you figure out who does what, how they do it, etc.  you kind of have an idea of how to play every encounter.  Yes, you can turn on ""limiters"" which make combat more difficult, but don't really change too much of your general strategy.Second, the game is way too linear.  Essentially, you walk on a platform for a bit, maybe you encounter some world objects that open up some of the story, then you run into enemies, you clear them, you walk some more, you encounter enemies, wallaa.  At this point you've seen all the game has to offer.  Sure, occasionally you hit a side area to explore that opens up some more story, but it really doesn't do much to alter gameplay.  To me, the game really feels more like a turn-based platformer than an ""ARPG"" which is what it is billed as [Yes, I knew it had a turn-based element before buying it - my point still stands - but most ARPGs are a little bit more ""open"" and less linear].Third, the graphics and music and story, most things that other people highly touted, just really did not do much for me.  Maybe I'm a stickler, but I think the people that will enjoy this game are indie bandwagon fans eager to tout a small studio's effort.  To me, it is a game that is far too straight-forward and lacks any real depth."
