,Not Recommended,237930,10192705,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,I AKU!,"Everyone’s going to downvote me to hell and back but I’m going to give you all my honest opinion. Transistor is a massive disappointment and ultimately a  rather mediocre game. Bastion is one of my favorite games and that’s why I pre-ordered this game the day I was first able to. Now I'm really starting to think Bastion was just a fluke by Supergiant, because this game is way under par. The combat is a slog, it’s either a real pain or a total cakewalk. Losing abilities when you die is a real dumb idea and if you screw up enough can leave the game unwinnable. The combat has some interesting ideas, but it just ends up being boring and it feels a bit more complex that it needed to be.Unlike Bastion which had likable characters and an interesting and well-written story, Transistor has cardboard cutouts for characters that the game expects you to really care for and a plot that tries to appear deep and layered when it’s really just convoluted and vapid. I love a really good story driven game with likable characters, that’s why I loved Bastion so much, but Transistor utterly fails at this. I felt nothing for the characters and didn't care about what was going on, the exact opposite of Bastion. There is no sympathetic and morally gray antagonists like the Ura and Zulf, but instead we got a bunch of janitors that cause every problem in the game because they are bunch of incompetent buffoons. They're neither threatening nor interesting.  Attempts at character and charm just feel artificial and forced, the game just tells you the characters’ relationships instead of showing you.  Red and the sword's being chief example, you never really get a good understanding about either them and Red being a mute really doesn't help matters any. The plot is filled with holes and never adequately explained, as stated before the whole game wouldn't have happened if the Camarata weren't all braindead. The ending also makes Red comes across as really selfish and unlikable because of it. Finally, the Transistor’s narration just seems forced and it lacks a lot of the charm and character that Rucks had. Most of his dialogue is also pretty pointless and doesn't illustrate the world and characters nearly as well Rucks did.The only good things about Transistor is the aesthetic and the soundtrack. Both are real quality stuff but they are wasted on everything else. Overall this game seems like had an extremely troubled development because there’s so much potential that gets utterly squandered. What we get is a hollow facsimile of Bastion with little of the heart. I say don’t buy the game, (If you really, really want to though just get it when its a lot cheaper) just buy the soundtrack and/or play Bastion again. I’m probably not buying anymore of Supergiant’s games if this is what they’re going to be like from now on, it’s a real shame."
