,Not Recommended,237930,10183585,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,ringhloth,"Whether or not you like Transistor depends on whether or not you're immediately charmed by the graphics. Those are definitely the games strongest point, if you're into them. They're quite nice, but there are plenty of other games with great graphics.The narration undoubtedly takes a page (or the entire book) from Bastion with the talking sword, but it's pretty sparse, and doesn't really deliver too much, especially in terms of story. Undoubtedly, its weakest point, the story confuses minimilism with sparseness. There's incredibly little motivation, information about what is happening, or really much of anything. It's really disappointing. Minimalism should highlight the best parts of game by cutting the worst parts out, rather than leaving out the core of what a story needs to have.The combat is pretty iffy. Not really terrible, but around the third wave of enemy upgrades, the game decides to frustrate you, throwing away its own mechanics in a desperate attempt to keep the game fresh. Otherwise, it's quite easy, even with keeping all of the handicaps on. There's no other gameplay besides the combat.The interface (especially the access point screen) is clunky, at best. If you wanted to build your build from scratch, it'll take 20 or so screen switches by mid game. By end game, it might go as high as 32 screen switches. Very slow, and while the game treats you with story to reward switching up your build, it punishes you big time with the sheer amount of effort it takes to do so.Personally, I liked the graphics, but I don't believe they can carry a game, and nothing else about Transistor was particularly enticing."
