,Not Recommended,237930,10190196,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,Cypher,"-= Post Contains Spoilers =-The Pros- Great Soundtrack- Good Visuals- Gameplay that will remain entertaining for the short time you play- Good SettingThe Cons- Short Game- Glarring Plot HolesI feel that Transistor as a game was cut or rushed out. There are cutscenes and area's in the trailer of the game that you do_not_see in the actual game itself. The Cameratta are not very fleshed out as to what exactly they are hoping to achieve or how they set about doing so. They have a generic goal of creating a static reality because they don't like change and create the process to stop this.  The game allows you to piece together your own conclusions with what sparse plot information it gives you but it leaves glaring holes in the overall story. You go through the game hearing about other citizens disappearing but then you never see any of them alive. The few you do see are dead and you absorb them. That stops happening pretty quickly.The process has a sort of obsession with red shown with the Camera-like enemy taking pictures of reds poster and the theater incident where cluckers are shown in the seats. Yet this is never elaborated on. It feels like ""The Process"" as an enemy were to be so much more but were cut down in the last second decision to be simply ""The Antagonist."" The evolving form of The Process is shown in the later enemies more human appearance and seemed to be a precusor to a revelation in the making about this enemy. Or when you enter into the Dark Lady Nursery.Another thing is how did the Process became what it is, which is not explained, simply shrugged off with a ""I gave the Process to a guy for a second and then he screwed it up."" Or when you find the first of the Cameratta but they have been somehow turned into a Process being which is never ever explained.There are several places that are mentioned in the game but never seen, the country is refered almost constantly yet what it actually is, is unclear in what was a digital utopia. The other place that was refered to was ""Underground"", where the process came from as it has the cube like spawner enemy which the Transistor mentions is bringing them up from below. This game feels like it had a lot of missed potential.Then we come to the Deus Ex Machina ending. The ""Cradle"" of the Transistor which when used will destroy or contain all of the Process. You want reasons to why this happened? No, ♥♥♥♥ you, no reasons for you. This happens because plot. This and the fact that for some reason it creates another Transistor sword which the last remaining person other than you has and you have to kill them to get out of the random plane of existence you've been teleport to.Summary: If you are looking for the sequel to Bastions great storyline and narrative you won't find it here, if you are story nutI advise you pass this game on. But if you want a game with a great soundtrack, good visuals, and entertaining gameplay you've found your game."
,Not Recommended,237930,10184965,"Posted: 20 May, 2014",all,Lavender Gooms,"Poor gameplay that never feels fluid, an irritating running commentary by a character we're never sure who he is or why we should care about him, absurd difficulty spikes, and a horrible final boss and ending.Bastion is one of my favorite gaming experience ever, so there was never a possibility where I wasn't going to buy and play SuperGiant's next game. So with that in mind I won't say I wish I hadn't played it. I just wish I could have appreciated the incredible visuals and fantastic soundtrack without the gameplay and narration constantly interrupting and getting in the way.The entire length of the game I felt like the gameplay was working against me. Every ability you have can be combined in different ways and then used in combat either real time or by pausing the game and choosing a sequence of actions to set up and then have executed automatically. Interesting idea, but the way it was implemented I could never find a good balance. Either I was using an ability combo that absolutely trivialized the encounter to the point where it was boring, or I was getting my butt kicked with little opportunity for me to recover. The gameplay always hovered between mildly frustrating and jaw-clenchingly irritating.There's nothing wrong with a game being five hours long, which is how long it ended up taking me to beat it. A game that short can have a lot packed into it to make it an incredibly worthwhile experience. Transistor doesn't have that, though, and in fact started to outstay its welcome before I had even gotten to the final areas. The final boss is a terrible mess of a gameplay mechanic completely unlike the rest of the game, forcing you to come up with new strategies on the fly and learn new ways to approach the game. The ending, which I will absolutely not spoil here, was right in line with the rest of the game in that it was a frustrating kick in the pants that was completely unearned.It's confusing, frustrating, irritating, absolutely gorgeous, and has an incredible soundtrack. Unfortunately those last two don't make up for the rest."
