,Not Recommended,237930,10195437,"Posted: 22 May, 2014",all,Tizmah,"I can't reccomend this game.First, the game has a great soundtrack and artstyle.  Great atmosphere.  That's about all the good I can say about TransistorThe story is vague.  Very vague.  So vague that I can't follow along with anything.  A sword is speaking to the voiceless ""Red"" who seems to only show any personality through art pieces.  You learn about other characters through skills after having found them in a dying state.  You get a snippet of dialogue about the character and a view lines of text.  So basically, it feels like tidbits of lore, but the plot doesn't go anywhere for quite a while.  I like mystery and stories where you figure things out only until the end, but this...it's just so empty and vague with little to no motivation.The gameplay boils down to walking down corridors with the occasional alternate ""dead end"" path leading to more short tid bits of the sword speaking to you about the spot, or a communication hub.  Thus you learn short bits about the characters previous life, but little to no exploration of the actual world.  It's basically running from Save Point- Enemy Fight- Story bit, Repeat.  Also, while roaming the levels you will see ""flashes"" of other players playing the game.  Well, so I hear.  I don't think the game ever really tells you that.  But apparently, this is what causes the 3-4 stall/freezes you will also run into in the game for such a pointless feature. They could have just made that client side, because in other games it actually has a purpose (Dark Souls).Besides that, the combat.  What a mess.  What we have here is a blend of turn-based and action.  Sounds cool, and I actually could see it working.  But it doesn't here.  You will spend your time in turn based because that is where the most damage and safest way to be is.  The downfall is that this game does a horrendous job of telling you what you need to do and giving you decent feedback.  Now, when you go into turn based mode, the world will phase out and stop.  The game shows you arcs of the moves you choose and also shows just how much HP will be taken off or if the enemy will evade/block it.  The fact is, this system is highly inaccurate.  I've chosen AoE moves, and it clearly shows my AoE should hit 3 of the targets because they are highlighted.  Guess what?  One didn't get hit, even though he was highlighted.  In another instance, I qued up three attack moves and that turn based system said that enemy would die, and after executing, it did not die.  Why give me misleading information?Now, perhaps I missed something.  I don't see how though.  Although, the game does a bad job of teaching the player how to play.  Oh yes, I enjoy learning things on my own.  I don't like to be hand held and have a tutorial for every little thing.  This though...The UI for assigning skills and such is not very self explanatory, combat is a mess, and when you die, you lose a skill until you reach the checkpoint after next and get full hp to finish the battle (Usually I just hit retry, because a. I don't like losing a skill and b. I don't like being held by the hand.  I find it an insult to just replinish my hp to full automatically so I can defeat the already beaten down enemies).  Which can hinder you badly, especially if you have limiters on.  All lmiiters do is enhance the enemies, giving you more exp for the difficulty boost.All in all, I found it more frustrating than I did enjoyable.  Shame though.  I hate seeing games with great music and art style have cumbersume design and messy gameplay."
,Not Recommended,237930,10194081,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,GooseComics,"I loved Bastion and the concept of that game. This game I thought I was going to enjoy it. I've had the game now for 24 hours, and it will just not open, and EVERYTHING that Supergiant Games has suggested to me will not fix the problem. I've asked for a refund, and I haven't heard anything back.Apparently this game is still in BETA, but released so that they could get more testers to fix bugs. I didn't sign up for that."
,Not Recommended,237930,10192252,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,bropocalypse,"Supergiant Games aren't taking the route of perfecting a certain genre of games, but rather perfecting a unique approach to a game. Like Bastion, the story is told in a non-conventional way, player choice for combat style (weapons/loadouts/dynamic difficulty) is paramount, and the art direction is breathtaking.Unlike Bastion's fast-paced arcadey shmup-style combat, the combat in Transistor almost feels like a cross between DOTA (this game is obviously influenced by one of Greg and Amir's favorite games) and Shadowrun Returns, XCOM, or similar turnbased strategy games. Most combat can be played either as real-time or turnbased with seamless switching between the two. It makes Transistor an entirely different genre than Bastion even though the presentation is so similar.So why won't I recommend this game?Well, it's difficult to make things so black and white as YES/NO. I really, really love the artstyle. The audio/visual aesthetic alone might be worth the price of $20 or more, BUT you've still got the game on top of that.I'm not saying that the game is all that bad... but it's just not good enough for the price of admission.Let's start with the story. Like Bastion, the story is told to the player in bite-sized chunks from a singular narrator. Unfortunately, the story just isn't told very well. Not enough is ever given to the player to know what is ever going on. The question ""why"" will pick away at any given turn, and many things are simply not explained. (Oh and that ending, I'll be the first in line to read why that ending made any sense whatsoever because I'm lost)In Bastion, many things about the world were unexplained or left unanswered. Here, Transistor tries a similar approach, but often just seems ambiguous and complicated for the sake of being ambiguous and complicated. The characters will drop hints left and right but not directly tell the player much of anything about anything. In Bastion, there were many one liners that were snarky, witty, poigniant, and, most of all, relevant. In Transistor the characters make several of these one-liners that have exactly none of these attributes.It also doesn't help that all of the characters in the game seem to have taken morphine before trying to talk to you. Seriously, if the character has something to say there's absolutely know reason that they cannot just say it without all the pausing and repeated words. There's only one time that it makes sense for a character to be slower in his speech, but that's another can of worms. I'll spare you the rant, just know that there's about two hours of dialogue in the game that's actually just dead air.Now for the actual gameplay. At first, I played Transistor heavily turn-based. It's what made sense to me, and the real-time elements felt clunky. About halfway through, though, I began to realize the DOTA influence, changed the keybindings to match, and found that the real-time combat was far easier that what I had been doing.At the end of the day, however, the combat still feels weak. I didn't feel like I had enough mobility in either play-style. The Jaunt() is good, but is most useful in a fully real-time strategy and still not fast enough to feel like I can get out of tough situations, nevermind just walking out of them. Hammering escape/retry became a staple for me at the end.Fortunately, there's a save-point after nearly every fight where you can fully regain your health. Unfortunately this ends up being every minute or so.Fights are small and quick. I can see this as an advantage for the player, but really it makes them feel like fights have no consequence. Sure there's an ""overload"" system whereby if the player takes too much damage, then they will lose a Function. But if the savepoint was literally two-seconds before the fight, then why would I not just restart the fight?That's not mentioning the bugs where I've launched enemies out-of-bounds and therefore unable to stop them from respawning... Or where you can exploit the upgrade system... Or how the final battle is just an exercise in frustration and avoiding tossing your keyboard through the monitor (0/10, will not fight again)... but I'll spare you.Finally there's the exploration. Walking around, there are many places that the player can click on and learn a little more about the environment or the story or whatever. There are also places that will transport the player to somewhere else and they will be unable to return. There is no differentiation between the two. It's far too easy to mistake a gateway for a senic overlook and find that content will now be missed. There are too many times where the player must approach a hotspot with trepidation of whether they will be forced into the next area or would be better to keep exploring.The ""backdoor"" areas are nice in theory. They allow for a break of sorts, but really have nothing to do with anything and just grind the story to a halt (which is already difficult to keep track of). They're an interesting idea, but just take far too much from the story.And there you have it in a nutshell. It's an interesting idea.Transistor is full of interesting ideas. It's got, really, one of the best presentations ever made, but the execution just doesn't quite hit the mark. It's a $30 game aesthetically, but only a $10 game, maybe, to play."
