,Not Recommended,237930,10186463,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,Kana,"Having loved Bastion, i so wanted to like this... but i can't. There's no charm whatsoever, and the story is indecipherably delivered in an absurdly non-user friendly system. The character voice accompanying you is as flavorful and soulful as listening to a drunken oaf constantly jammer on about nothing of value...The good sides can be summarized quickly; the art style is pretty fantastic, the music is overall good if a bit spotty in places, and the way skills interreact with eachother can give some very interesting results... even if they feel overtly sanitized.The bad sides are... not so easy to talk about.The way you figure out the story in the game is not by gameplay.Every character you meet (dead or about to be as they are) leave behind skills for you. These skills can be slotted in 3 manners; 1, As an actual usable skill 2. Augmenting another 3. As a passive.To unlock the story, every skill you get must be once planted in one of these slots for a minimum duration of one combat where the skill must be used.The way the story is delivered to you is a couple of paragraphs of plaintext with some uninteresting and unenlightening comments given by the voiceactor. This would be fine and understandable if the game were like Baldur's Gate, where you expect to ponder on choices and actually react to dialogue... this is as interesting way to deliver a story as reading a random fanfiction about something you are inherently assumed to care about, even if you're told pretty much nothing of it.The combat is... an incredibly dull blend of active and turn-based in the same vein, if worse, that Fallout 3/New Vegas VATS system screwed things up. It's difficult to explain, but i'll try:You can use your skills in real time, they have short cooldowns and differing amount of animation times to use them.However, you pretty much never will, because there's an alternative... ultimately more boring method to fight, which is required of you in most fights, (as you have no other way of dodging enemy attacks) the turn-based system.The turn system practically freezes time for you, allows you to do a set number of actions, including movement, until a certain amount of time is used up, after which your character will perform the actions automatically in pseudo-freeze time.This system trivializes any and all difficulty in the game, and yet it is absolutely necessary that you utilize it.After you've used the turn system, you wait for it to recharge for a few seconds in real time, and just so happens, pretty much every skill you have will be on cooldown during this time... so you can't have any kind of fun during waiting it to come back, unless you consider hiding behind breakable walls and just casually walking (running not allowed) away from enemies.There are also spikes in difficulty, but even with a vast amount of things that are supposed to make the game more difficult (They really don't, such as needing an arbitrary additional hit before you can collect the capsule that makes an enemy respawn is not about difficulty, it's about tedium), the game is overall non-challenging to likely anyone. ""Spikes in Difficulty"" just means you walk away slightly further from your enemies. The combat feels sluggish, there's no adrenaline rush for achieving anything, and it all feels like a big chore.The game also keeps crashing both itself and steam, because for some reason they're using a really poorly coded version of Demon's/Dark souls type system where you see blurry phantoms of other players roaming about. If there's any sort of a hitch in the system, the game freezes up and crashes Steam with it... and there's nothing you can do about it, outside of doing it in offline mode, and this game certainly is not worth that much effort.---Ultimately it's a hugely disappointing experience for me.As an aside:I should know well better to buy titles from indie devs that hit it big only once before, as personally, Arcen had already burnt me violently on that regard. Having loved AI War, the abysmal A Valley Without Wind deserves nothing but scorn. This isn't as bad, comparatively, but considering how unconditionally Bastion was loved... it's not a far off deal."
