76561198025658316,Recommended,237930,10579034,"Posted: 20 June, 2014",all,lukehauge,"Other reviews have covered the great parts of Transistor, and I agree that is a beautiful game with an immersive story and great gameplay, etc. I do want to give a bit of a warning, though:The story can be overly subtle, especially if it's not fully explored. I enjoyed unlocking snippets of character backstory and interacting with out-of-the-way terminals and scenery, but anyone who doesn't do so is going to miss out on a lot of the story. Even those who read and interact with everything are going to find themselves with questions. The story is too important to the gameplay to be ignored, so if you buy Transistor give it your full attention and you'll be rewarded.It is a short game and replay value is fairly low. Already on the second playthrough (even with Limiters and New Game+ spicing up my possibilities) I felt less ""magic"" than the first time--I already knew what was going to happen, after all, and so much of the excellence of the first playthrough was in the plot. Casual players ought to expect six to eight hours of gameplay in a single playthrough, only the most dedicated are likely to get more than 12 or 16. I think that for most people Transitor will be enjoyed once or twice and then set aside.The mechanics, like the story, are immersive and require dedication. It is tempting to find a single combination and use it through the whole game in the same way, adding on a single new power or slightly altering your layout with each level increase. There's a reason, though, that you're prompted to change your skillset every time you reach a checkpoint. The upgrade and passive ability system offers so much customization that by the end of the game I was finding testing new strategies and messing around in the skill menu at least as much fun as pulling off a well-executed combo (which, though awesome and enjoyable, did get a bit repetitive after ten hours).If you're not put off, though, please do buy Transistor with all haste. It is magnificent, artistic, mechanically brilliant, and intensely enjoyable."
