76561197960648149,Recommended,237930,10428594,"Posted: 11 June, 2014",all,Taku ♪~,"I'm not sure I can recommend this enough.  Clocked in at around 7 hours for a single play through and, in an unprecedented turn of events, I intend on playing through it again.  Soon.  It has a new game+ option, keeping your upgrades and level, as well as the level of your opponents.  There are extremely minor differences in the game, but none that will give you explicit explanation of the story, if that is what you'd hope for.Oh yes, the story.  The game doesn't give you much exposition.  It just tosses you in.  Now, there are bits of character back story you can unlock through playing with certain skills used in specific ways, and contained in there is information that can help you glean an idea of what this world is and where it came from.  It won't hand you the back story, you have to work for it.I love this game.  Love it.  The visuals, the soundtrack, the method of narrative, the voice acting, fantastic.  All of it.  At 7 hours, you have to decide if the cost is worth it for you, but it was for me.Quick note: I never played Bastion.  The visuals and the tone didn't appeal to me enough to really captivate me.  Where Bastion missed for me, Transistor hit right on the mark immediately.  This game has caught some flak when compared to Bastion on the Steam forums, but being unable to make that comparison myself, I can say this game is fantastic."
