,Recommended,237930,10478178,"Posted: 14 June, 2014",all,Jarik Spiegel,"A terrific story, a moving conclusion, and an environment that draws you in and wraps you up in a fantastic and colorful world slowly being white washed. It's hard not to love this game and all its little moments, from the way the music matches a gorgeous environment that wraps you up, to the little bites of this world that help make it seem more than a game board that you slide your character across.The combat system is quite charming; with a system built in that helps regulate difficulty as well as a time freezing trick that you can toggle when needed. The result is something that can delight everyone from the twitch player looking for the adrenaline pump of rapid tactical choices, to the labored perfectionist who tries to build just the right combination of steps to create the final satisfying conclusion. Both styles are rewarded well through Transistor's clever mechanics which was a delight to see and play with.The story did seem a little odd at first, as you start in media res a tense escape against unknown assailants in a world unfamiliar to you; but everything comes together quickly and it's not long till the pieces start fitting together. The characters are a wonderful match; Red as the ever capable fighter whose voiceless dialogue told a wonderful story of the sort of person she was, and the Transistor itself voiced by the ever amazing Logan Cunningham who plays the perfect counterpart of being both helpless and ever hopeful lover who is really just forced to watch from the sidelines as the world unfolds around him.I'll confess choking up when Red delivers her choice at the end of the game, and I found myself both understanding, dreading, and cheering it. Something which one doesn't always find when they embark on any narrative.In short; I loved Transistor. It may not be for everyone, but it's a fantastic experience with a colorful narrative and characters that you'll fall in love with."
