,Recommended,237930,10701373,"Posted: 23 June, 2014",all,Minzoku Bokumetsu,"Short version: If you like Bastion, you'll like Transistor... because you've already played it.Long version: Transistor is like a high-tech, watered-down version of Bastion, with Art Deco in place of mysterious rising bits of landscape. There's visually a lot more going on in Transistor, if the frame rate on my computer is any indication [chugging somewhat at the lowest resolution], but the game is completely linear, where Bastion allows a choice of what land to visit next. To make up for it, the Transistor is capable of equipping and ""upgrading"" four different attacks (""Functions""), which double as life extensions (lose too much life, and a Function overloads--Red dies if all Functions overload). The Idols in Bastion reappear in Transistor as Limiters, providing additional experience at the expense of added difficulties.What sets Transistor apart from Bastion the most is the Turn() action, which is by default automatically activated at low health, though it can also be activated at will. Turn() is a Frozen Synapse-style ""freeze frame"" where Red can plan out a set number of attacks at leisure before enacting them, at the penalty of leaving herself unable to attack until her Turn() meter resets. Mastering Turn() can mean the difference between winning and losing, especially in the Sandbox tests. The most fun is experimenting with stacking Functions for effectiveness in battle, and finding all the cute flavour text hidden throughout the stages.Once again, if you like Bastion, you'll like Transistor... because you've already played it."
