76561198042257937,Recommended,237930,10239368,"Posted: 26 May, 2014",all,ShoopufSenpai,"Once upon a time, there was a city in the clouds where gods and people lived in harmony. There were gods of justice, gods of strength, gods to inspire the masses, and gods who changed the color of the sky itself. The people worshiped their gods, showering them in praise, and the gods responded in kind, granting the requests of their beloved citizens. But none was more beloved than the goddess with hair of red. She was a goddess of song and it was said her voice awakened something beautiful within everyone who listened, god and mortal, alike. However, none loved her more than one man in particular and the goddess loved him, as well.Yet, despite the peace and prosperity of the city in the clouds, there were those who did not celebrate. Among the pantheon, four gods grew tired of the ever changing whims of the people. They convinced themselves that with enough power, they could make a perfect version of the city. A city that would never have need to change. A city they would control.So it was, that the four gods forged a weapon of ultimate power. With it, they began to trick their fellow gods, one after another, sealing their power within the weapon so that their own strength might grow. As their plans came to fruition and their power grew, they began, in secret, to raise a demon army, that would help them secure the city of perfection for which they lusted.Before long, the four came for the goddess with hair of red. Brandishing their terrible weapon, they stole from the goddess her beautiful voice. However, the four did not know of the man whom the goddess loved, and before they could seal her away in truth, her love stepped between them, taking the fatal wound that was meant for his beloved.With their plans foiled, the four fled, but the damage was already done. The goddess with hair of red had lost her voice, and her love had become another victim of the terrible weapon, his soul sealed within. Even worse, with their great power lost to them, the four gods who had conspired against the city could no longer control the demon army. With no master to guide them, the demons besieged the city, destroying its many wonders and citizens, alike.The goddess knew that only with the power of the weapon could anything be done to save the city and bring back what was. With a heavy heart, she pulled the weapon free of the man she loved. A voice spoke to her.“Hey Red, we're not gonna get away with this, are we?”--This message brought to you by Junction Jan's! Try the Sea Monster!"
76561197997008069,Recommended,237930,10239822,"Posted: 26 May, 2014",all,[LRR]Steve,"A wondeful combination of 2D Isometric art style with an emotive sound track. It's a game that a great experience to have. Unlike some other ""art games"", it also have really good gameplay. Almost similar to Bastion, it has action slashy-smashy gameplay, but also the unqiue mechanic of ""Planning"".Pause time an plan your next moves. Movement on the battlefield and executing abilities eats up alloted ""Turn Time"". You can undo any actions and replan at any point during the pause. When you're happy, execute your plan. The whole world will mostly wait as you stab and wreck at hyper speeds. After, simply wait for your ""Turn Bar"" to recharge before ""Plan""ning again.The narrative is around you. The exposition isn't heavily in your face. It's drip fed to your nicely through the environment. If you want to know more about the personalities of the world, you can read an expanding biography of them. But it's not crucial. You can get a statisfactory story experience playing through.This game is heavier on the RPG than Bastion was. You can switch in and out abilities in up to 4 ability slots. Other abilities can be attuned as ""Passives"" that affect one of your skills (kinda like Runes in Diablo 3 or World of Warcraft) or as a Passive for yourself (More damage. Chance when you enter Planning Mode to Transcend gaining the ability to deal heavy AOE damage or taking less damage passively. Each Active ability has a maximum of 2 Passive slots. You also have a limited about of ""Memory"" that caps how many skills you can equip at once. Levelling up gives you access to more Abilities and choosing if you want to increase your Memory's capacity or unlocking more Passive slots.If you enjoyed Bastion, you will enjoy this game.If you haven't played Bastion, but enjoyed playing Dragon Age 1, you will probably enjoy the game. I felt the Planning Mode was similar to pausing during Dragon Age 1. It lets you review the battlefield at your own pace and strategically plan your moves. Later on in the game, it benefits you to enter planning mode at the right time, as opposed to entering it when ever it's off cooldown.Otherwise, maybe watch some lets plays to decide if it's the game for you.Some people have said it was a short game. I think it was just the right length. It finished when I was happy for it to finish.Personally, I haven't played a game that affected me in the same way since Mass Effect 3 (ignoring the ME3 ending controversy)."
