,Recommended,237930,10303996,"Posted: 31 May, 2014",all,Luparax,"After playing Bastion I simply had to take a look at Transistor and let me tell you: I am not disappointed.The story starts off quite confusing but bits and pieces of story are scattered around the game world and add up to a disturbing picture of a dystopia where no one is ever really free. As with Bastion, Transistor's story takes some twists and turns, though not as much as Bastion's.The combat system was something completely new for me, mixing real-time and round-based gameplay elements to something extremely fun to play around with. With a controller at hand walking around and/or fighting feels smooth and quick. Effects are well animated and smashing enemies to pieces with a well placed PFUMPSHSHSHSH is very very satisfying. Level progression and combat both is well balanced and fun.With the sound design it was a little different. While the effects and environmental sounds feel a little sterile - which seems to be intented so the music is in sync with the game world - the real beauty lies in the rich background music and songs. If you have the time, stop and listen for a moment. Also (Warning: small spoiler ahead) the main character is able to humm songs of which many are a reward to certain challenges. Again, worth listening to if you want to take the time.As I stated above, the effects are well animated and the rest of the graphics feel just right for this type of game. I like the design as well as the sounds design for the main character and her ""companion"". Was a little different to what I am used to in games these days, maybe because I haven't played adventure games in a while. Having said that, Transistor is as much of an Adventure game, as it is an action game, an rpg or a strategy game. Supergiantgames tried hard to make this game stick out from the crowd and I believe they have achieved that.If you are looking for a fazit:Worth spending money on. Hours of gameplay, an intricate story, different yet fun gameplay, sounds design really worth mentioning and art-like graphics.P.S.: If you haven't played Bastion yet, you should do that now."
