,Recommended,237930,10329682,"Posted: 2 June, 2014",all,Devil's Advocate,"If you liked Bastion you'll like this game.  If you didn't like Bastion you probably wont enjoy the game very much.If you've never played Bastion you can think of this game as an Isometric (Read: Top-down view at an angle) action-adventure game where you acquire abilities to use while alternating between real-time and turn-based combat.  These abilities can be combined with one another to create new hybrids of abilities which extends the life of the game's combat system dramatically.  The story is told as you explore with a handful of minimalist cutscenes thrown in which showcase the 2d art style.  Understanding the story requires the player to pay careful attention to dialogue and explore the environments for context.The game is about 6 hours long and may be repeated in New Game+ (Recursion Mode) to continue acquiring abilities and attempt more difficult combat challenges.  A repeated playthrough is also recommended to see the story through again with the context given to you by the initial playthrough.  This is the kind of game they have long articles written dedicated to piecing together what was really going on in the game's story, without being the kind of game that you'll find yourself completely confused by if you choose not to engage in the larger conversation happening around the game's opening and ending.$20 is a steal.  If you're into Indie titles, Bastion, or want to explore what indie titles have to offer to the video games market this isn't a bad place to start."
