76561198038058805,Recommended,237930,10470632,"Posted: 14 June, 2014",all,ChibiMik3,"Thrown into a beautiful world that you know nothing about and the first thing you see is a ""dead"" man with a swordlike weapon, which seems to know you, stuck on his chest.Once again you have million questions and on your way to find answers to them you are confronted by countless waves of ""Process"".The main protagonist ""Red"" has lost her voice and Logan Cunnigham narrates the game as her swordlike weapon ""Transistor"".Story is mostly told by the ""Transistor"" and the antagonists but you will get more info about the city through OVC Terminals and it's citizens by inspecting Functions.Game is a Sci-fi Action-RPG in which you battle the enemies either in or outside Turn(). It also has a leveling system which lets you choose from different Functions, Limiters and Passive slots or MEM to use Functions, each time you level up.Turn() is a system that will freeze all the enemies and gives you a chance to plan out your next couple moves. Each function (which skills are called) will use a certain amount of Turnpoints (amount will change with some Function combinations and you may extend the overall amount by placing a Function as passive) and after all of them are spent you may activate your Turn() and watch as you rip your enemies apart with different combinations of Functions. When Turn() is on cooldown you may only use Jaunt() or Functions that are upgraded with Jaunt() and because of this and the difficulty of the enemies, fighting outside Turn() is hard and risky and I recommend you to just evade with Jaunt() untill Turn() is usable again. There are also enemies that will stop you from using Turn() which will become lethal especially on your second playthrough.Functions act a vital part in this game since you cannot attack without them and when your health reaches 0 one of your active Functions will overload and save your life. Overloaded functions can be recovered by accessing new Access Points(save points). Losing all your active Funtions will lead to a game over. There are 16 different Functions in total and each of them are ""voices"" of the former citizens of Cloudbank. Each Function may play its role in Active, Upgrade or Passive slots with varying effects. By combining Functions you can create 3360 (or 3840 on your second playthrough) different active Functions. The amount of different skillsets with 4 Active slots, which have 2 Upgrade slots each, and 4 Passive slots is just insane. So you will find yourself changing your skillset after each encounter and experimenting for the combination that suits your playstyle the most. Game also encourages you to try out different combinations by giving you info about the citizens when you have played through an encounter with the Function in a different slot. And to get all the achievements you must play with every Function and try out their Active, Upgrade and Passive effects.There are Limiters which give you different handicaps and award you in EXP if you survive the encounter with Process. It has a system similiar to that of the Function that gives you info about the varying types of Process. There's also an achievement if you survive 5 encounters with all the Limiters on which makes each battle a struggle for life. Be prepared to lose atleast one active per encounter when you're trying to get this achievement. There are also 4 levels of each Process type and when you play the game for a second time the enemies levels won't reset and you will encounter even the endgame Process from the very start.There's also a secret room that you may access from different locations throughout the game after the first boss battle. It has multiple doors with different challenges varying from speedbattles to fighting a copy of yourself with all your Functions. For each victory you are awarded with a piece of the games soundtrack that you may play at the central hub of the secret room.After 13.7 hours of gameplay and starting my 3rd playthrough I have still not found the final version of the Process which should be Level 4 and I'm missing few duplicate Functions even though I'm level 28. So yeah.. There's still stuff to do.I though that the game would get boring in the second playthrough since normally it would mean that you get to fight the normal starting enemies with overpovered skills but was happily suprised since the game was still getting harder even though I had full MEM and slots.Turn() system is unique and amazing since I have always loved the combination of action and strategy.Artwork is similiar to their earlier work, Bastion, but this time in sci-fi setting and the music is amazing and fits the theme very well.I'll also applaud Supergiant Games since they were able to make the final boss (both battle and the character) very interesting and after the varying types of Process (even boss versions) the final boss will be something totally different.Conclusion:Is playing through a linear game with beautiful graphics and awesome music while slashing through endless waves of Process and fighting epic boss battles worth 19€?Most certainly! 5/5But it is only my opinion."
,Recommended,237930,10472953,"Posted: 14 June, 2014",all,Grifous91,"Have you played Bastion? No? Then go play Bastion. Then get Transistor. If you enjoyed Bastion (which you should), you'll love Transistor.The game play is phenomenal. The hybrid turn-based combat is super fun, and makes for a perfect balance of challenge and fun. The powers system is also really well done, and actively encourages you to experiment. Whether it's to find out more information about the characters in the game, or because you're forced to after ""dying"", you will want to try out every combination you can with all the abilities you get.And the music... oh man that music. Darren Korb returns from Bastion, and knocks it out of the park again with Transistor.tl;dr: It's an excellent game, just try it. It looks amazing, it sounds amazing, and it plays amazing. And it's only $20! Although trust me, you'll want to spend the extra $10 for the soundtrack."
