,Recommended,237930,10187442,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,Nekura,"IntroFirstly, I've just beaten the game so I still have a little bit of that ""wow"" factor in my eyes, so bear with me if I am a little blinded to some of the flaws, this will be updated after a ""Recurse"" runthrough as a more detailed review; however, this, like Bastion, is more of a ""first impressions"" kind of game, so, without further adeu, the show. Oh, and no spoilers. TL;DR list at the bottom. Oh, and the beauty of the graphical goes without saying, so there's no real exposition on that below.The StoryI gave a glimpse through the negative reviews and saw one that spoke of a con of the story being that you had to ""read between the lines"" to get the full picture. For one, a story SHOULD make one think. To take the pieces of the puzzle and put them together before they're all wrapped up together. Now if you blazed through the story, equipped only one combo, found it best for you, didn't read any terminals and ignored the mysterious man in the mechanical sword then you will be hopelessly lost by the story's end. All you'll know is that there was this guy. He's in a sword now. Things happen. Ending happens (no spoilers!) It's a game you can do that in. But if you take your time, explore, read the terminals, stop moving when the sword speaks so you can listen, try out all the different possible ways you can slot the transistors abilities, read all the files, save the cheerleader and save the world? You'll know EXACTLY what's going on any you'll be sucked right into this graphic, interactive novel of a game. Just like with a graphic novel though, you can't black out all the words and hope to get a story out of the pictures alone. I will say that, to some gamers who aren't usually completionists (I'm far from it!) this may seem daunting and tedious and you may lose interest on the firet playthrough, and that's okay! This game's made to play again, just like Bastion was. This, as was Bastion, is a game created almost entirely to tell a story. As I related it, a graphic novel except you're burning baddies rather than flipping a page.The GameplayThis might just be me, but I never found a combo I juststuckwith. I was constantly trying new things, shuffling things around. Always looking to see how I could best tackle a situation. Now once I got a certain later-game power, I will admit that I ended up with a bit of a god-complex going around and smashing everything in sight. Then one group of enemies out-numbered and out-smarted me. That said I needed  to change my strategy once again. You basically have three ways to play. Head-long like Bastion, which is technically doable... full strategy by utiliszing movement-enhancing abilities while out of ""Turn()"" mode and relying completely on ""Turn()"" for your attacks, or a fusion of both as I did, utilizing Turn() for big damage combos and then mopping up in normal combat while my Turn() was on cooldown. All in all, the gameplay is very engaging and, while repetitive (and what game isn't, at it's core, a little repetitive?), offers enough variety in strategy and personal gameplay choices that I think most gamers would be satisfied. Just keep in mind that this game IS heavy on the strategy aspect. If you don't like strategy games, you may not like this game. There's also one thing that's been bugging me as well. Sure they're nice to have and neat little character pieces to have in the game but there ARE two seemingly useless controls in the game. The first is (with KB+M mind) holding the tab key to hum. it creates a beautiful accompaniment to the beautiful music in the game, but it serves no gameplay purpose. As with using the ""Q"" key out of battle to perform a ""flourish"" in which Red tosses the transistor up, leaps up to it, then lands a few inches away. Completely pointless, can't even do it in combat as some flavor thing. It's just there. I'll forgive it since I have a (not so) secret love affair with the fact that SG Games seems to focus entirely on story and these abilities lend toward character quirks of both Red and the Transistor, but it still would have been nice to have had some serious implementation into the game's function. (and if there is, it's not apparent, so if I am mistaken feel free to disregard. There isonelevel where the humming does something, but it's another bit of story flavor.)The CharactersWhile you don't get to see much of these characters, save for Red, the game sure paints a pretty picture about every single one you ""encounter."" I'll focus on the characters you see the most of. Red and The Transistor. Red is, from the start, porteayed as a very independant woman. There is one thing I love about her though. While she's strong and independant, she's still a woman. Beyond that, she's human. Too often female heroines are made to be either dainty yet defiant or so hulk-like they'd even put a man to shame. She has this wonderful balance of being a strong, independant woman that does get scared and does act a little irrational at times; yet, she knows what she has to do and she perserveres through it. She casts aside her gown, dons the jacket worn by the man that saved her life, and just kinda gets to it. She actsnromaland I think that's the first thing that got me about her. They don't play up her being strong and shove it in your face, nor do they assume that just because she's a woman she must be frail of emotion. Both sides of the emotional / strong coin are done in such a beautifully subtle way that it just comes out right. This is no different for the Transistor. (Minor spoler, sorry!) The Transistor is not just the sword, the voice is that of the man that saved Red's life. Now I won't get too much into that, but his personality just works well. The game managed to make me feel badfor a sword.Now I will say there's one problem with Red. A lot of what you get is second-hand. You get a feel for Red through the speech of the Transistor and that's where the Transistor comes in so well. He paints a wonderful picture that's supplimented by little return comments on terminals and expressions in cutscenes and little subtle things she does in her actions. Read into all of that and you'll see that these are two very real characters. To harken back to the graphic novel analogy, you wouldn't get a complete story if all you did was read the words either. It takes both the images and the words to make the story complete. So too with this game, and the characters are what tie things together.The MusicThe music in this game is spectacular. There's not too much more to say. While there's nothing really ""catchy"" that you might find yourself humming as you go about your business, it's still beautiful nonetheless. Oh, and when you're in the sandbox (you'll know what I mean eventually, only a minor spoiler, I promise!) give the record a kick and hum along with a few songs. It's really interesting and fairly haunting to hear them with that hummed accompaniment. It makes you realize that all of the songs are technically songs by Red. Makes you wonder if she hears them in her head while she's out and about.And so, in trying to avoid the character limit and to add in points that really are just bullets, here's the TL;DR list.Personal Pros:Compelling storyActive, strategic gameplayEngaging charactersBeautiful, Artistic graphicsPossible Cons:Story isn't thrown at you, takes some seeking outAs with most strategy, some may find it repetitiveDue to the ""active storytelling"" syle, some might find the Transistor a bittoochattyAll in all, I dodn't find much wrong with the game at its core. It's something I think more games should strive for, and that's to be a vehicle for a story with some fun gameplay and great graphical artwork along the way.If you're apprehensive, don't be. Even as a poor man, I can say that it was well worth the twenty bucks."
