,Recommended,237930,10281257,"Posted: 29 May, 2014",all,toomuchdog,"Just finished the game.There're a couple of small ways in which this game tries a little too much to be like Bastion, but honestly I have almost exclusively positive things to say about it.The gameplay is based on mixing and matching a set of abilities that have different effects when used as active skills, upgrades for other active skills, or passive skills.  The sheer magnitude of options available is both impressive and carefully tuned so that it doesn't really become overwhelming.  The delivery of the story and setting is extremely varied and the devs were willing to allow the player to piece things together or his or her own with the fragments earned from how skills are used as well as the main narrative.And as one might expect, both the music and art are absolutely phenomenal.  Not only are they amazing in their own right, but each compliments the setting and narrative of the game very effectivley.  Can't say I mind having a heavier focus on Ashley Barrett's vocals either.  Logan Cunningham's voice acting performance feels a little awkward at first, but as you get to know the character, grows to be as great as ever.While the game feels a little shorter than Bastion was (and a little shorter than I'd hoped), the pacing is very reasonable and the experience is very dense with impressive art, music, and play.  I would have liked a bit more, though.The only other complaint I might have is actually only partially a complaint:There are tons of references to programming syntax in the names and descriptions of various parts of the game.  While those were really cool to me (a programmer), I feel like they could be odd or confusing to others.  Of course, I can't really speak from that perspective.Overall, I thoroughly enjoyed Transistor and I'm looking forward to my second playthrough.  If you'll excuse me, I'm going to go buy the soundtrack."
,Recommended,237930,10281267,"Posted: 29 May, 2014",all,The Cinnamon Disappointment,"I'm going to start this off by saying I wasn't a fan of Bastion. I had played the first hour or so of it, but it never hooked me. This game though...this game hooked me.The art style is gorgeous with its art deco sci fi aesthetic and cyberpunk influences. The story isn't given to you all at once or in a few places with massives amounts of information. Instead, it's given to you in packages through various means, all of which is effectively delivered. Especially effective is the voice acting. Throughout the game, you are really only given one voice to listen to, that of the person inside the Transistor, but it never feels like a game empty of people. The voice is warm and treats the player as if they already know each other, and it makes you want to listen to what he has to say.The gameplay is intriquing as well. You can play it real-time, as if it Diablo or a similar game, or you can activate Turn() mode, which pauses the game world allowing to play your actions ahead of time. It's a satisfying feeling to be able to tally the hitpoints up before hand to know that the enemy will be dead very shortly and then actually see it happen.Overall, I'd say this is a game worth getting, and if you have doubts as to that, wait for the inevitable sale and buy it then. This game was hooked from the very beginning, kept my interest, made me want to play it again, and even made me want to revisit Bastion just so I can see what else this game developer has done."
